<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Election Being Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OGDEN, Utah (AP) -- Weber State University's legal staff is  
investigating the school's first ever online student elections, 
believing state or federal laws may have been broken. 
</P>
<P>
	Administrators say someone or some people fraudulently voted at  
least 40 times last week by using other students' Social Security 
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	President Paul H. Thompson said WSU's legal counsel, computer  
experts and police officers are trying to find out if there was a 
misappropriation and unauthorized use of student ID numbers. They 
hope to conclude the investigation within a couple of days. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week students voted for half of the student body officers,  
including president and vice presidents, using their Social 
Security numbers through the university's Web page. The special 
constituency senators were voted on by paper ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	The final election was declared void Friday after about 30  
students reported not being able to vote because their ID numbers 
had already been used. 
</P>
<P>
	The school's staff looked at the computer voting patterns and  
found more discrepancies. 
</P>
<P>
	One off-campus computer was heavily used between midnight and 6  
a.m. The university called the students who reportedly cast their 
ballots on that computer and 10 said they had not voted, Thompson 
said. Other on-campus computers have similarly strange voting 
patterns and Thompson said the internal review could unearth more 
fraudulent votes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
