<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nick Grippo -- Caterer to the Stars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Nick Grippo is a familiar face on the Hollywood party circuit.  
He's at star-studded wrap parties, celebrity birthdays, Beverly 
Hills society events and Oscar night galas. 
</P>
<P>
	Seeing celebrities in their homes -- getting ready for a party or  
eating a relaxed dinner with their families -- gives Grippo a 
glimpse into their personal lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``They do a lot of normal stuff. They have real lives, with  
families and kids. And they have to eat, just like everyone else,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Grippo is offering a glimpse into the kitchens and dining  
rooms of his celebrity clients with ``Hollywood Dish! Recipes, Tips 
&AMP; Tales of a Hollywood Caterer'' (Angel City Press, $29.95). 
</P>
<P>
	``People will probably buy my book because of the stories,''  
Grippo acknowledged. ``But the recipes really are good. I tried to 
pick recipes that are not complicated or intimidating. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of the recipes are 'comfort food.' Celebrities eat that  
kind of food too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grippo's only formal culinary training came when he was 11 and  
worked in his father's Chicago sandwich shop. 
</P>
<P>
	So most of his recipes have evolved over the years, with Grippo  
learning on the job. (When he is testing a new dish, he will eat it 
four nights in a row before serving it to friends.) 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Taylor, who wrote the book's foreword, particularly  
likes Grippo's Caesar salad with Parmesan croutons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rodeo Drive ribs'' and ``haute dogs'' were served at her  
Fourth of July barbecue. 
</P>
<P>
	At Barry Manilow's Thanksgiving dinner, the menu featured turkey  
and cornbread, sausage and mushroom stuffing, served with a 
cranberry, shallot and dried-cherry compote. For Harrison Ford's 
birthday party, the menu included poached salmon with dill sauce 
and coconut angel food cake. 
</P>
<P>
	Grippo also counts Patrick Swayze and Carrie Fisher among his  
clients. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-three years ago, Grippo left his home in Chicago and  
headed for Hollywood, hoping to see his face on the big screen. He 
enrolled in acting classes at Los Angeles City College and 
graduated from UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
	He got acting jobs in a series of ``forgettable movies.''  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, his reputation as a cook grew.  
</P>
<P>
	His apartment was often filled with friends from his acting  
classes, who enjoyed the recipes his mother taught him because she 
was worried that he would starve, living so far away from his big 
Italian family. 
</P>
<P>
	Those friends included Ted Danson, Michelle Pfeiffer and Cindy  
Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Grippo got his first paying job as a caterer from Ms. Williams,  
who had just started work on ``Laverne &AMP; Shirley,'' which became a 
hit TV series. Since then, Ms. Williams has hired him on a regular 
basis. (He will cater her New Year's 2000 party.) 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Grippo's clients favor relatively simple but flavorful  
foods that take advantage of the fresh fruits and vegetables that 
Southern California has to offer. 
</P>
<P>
	But the food he serves is not the low-fat, low-flavor cuisine  
that one might imagine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Years ago, everyone thought Los Angeles' food was only for  
dieters -- fruit salad with a little Mexican food on the side,'' 
Grippo said. ``But 'California cuisine' now offers excellent 
dining.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gourmet Italian food is very popular at the moment, Grippo said.  
And that's fine with him; he's a caterer who loves a good olive 
oil. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of his celebrity clients -- like Ms. Fisher -- have shown  
talent in the kitchen. Grippo has taught cooking classes in her 
home. When Ms. Fisher learned of his longtime crush on Beverly 
D'Angelo, she invited the actress to join them in the kitchen. 
</P>
<P>
	As it turned out, Ms. D'Angelo had a knack for using Parmesan  
cheese. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd never know whose head was going to come through that  
door,'' Grippo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
