<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Everglades Restoration Moved Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The Army Corps of Engineers on Wednesday  
accelerated the pace of its ambitious plan to restore the Florida 
Everglades, which has been abused by agriculture and development 
over the last half-century. 
</P>
<P>
	The corps released a revised plan for its $7.8 billion  
Everglades project and speeded it up by 20 percent. That was a 
concession to environmentalists and scientists who said the 
original plan Vice President Al Gore announced in October was too 
slow. 
</P>
<P>
	``The greater Everglades ecosystem is nationally significant and  
unique in the world,'' the corps' report begins. ``If actions are 
not taken now, irretrievable loss of this extraordinary resource 
will occur.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The revised plan is to be formally handed over to Congress on  
July 1 after yet another review by the public and government 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The corps is essentially undoing the job it did a half-century  
ago, when it carved the canals and built the levees that rerouted 
water across South Florida. As it turned out, that put the 
Everglades in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan seeks a delicate balancing act: restoring traditional  
water flow through the Everglades to save bird and fish populations 
that have decreased in some species by 90 percent in the marshy 
estuaries and sawgrass prairies. 
</P>
<P>
	The corps must manage to do that while ensuring a future water  
supply for burgeoning South Florida and without flooding suburban 
developments that encroach upon the wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Many key components now will be completed by 2020 rather than  
2025. Forty-four of the plan's 68 components will be completed by 
2010. In the original plan, few projects were scheduled to be 
completed in the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The corps' report said the increased pace should not raise the  
total cost of the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
