<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kissinger, Ueberroth Join IOC Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Henry Kissinger and Peter Ueberroth have  
accepted appointments to a panel that will rebuild the 
International Olympic Committee in the wake of its biggest scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC said Wednesday that Kissinger, a former secretary of  
state, and Ueberroth, the chief organizer of the 1984 Los Angeles 
Olympics, agreed to serve among the two dozen members of IOC 2000, 
the committee's reform commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Also accepting appointment was Anita DeFrantz, an IOC vice  
president from Los Angeles, committee spokesman Franklin 
Servan-Schreiber said. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, told The  
Associated Press on Tuesday that IOC president Juan Antonio 
Samaranch had asked Kissinger, Ueberroth and DeFrantz to be on the 
panel. 
</P>
<P>
	A fourth American, U.S. Olympic Committee president Bill Hybl,  
was the first appointment to the commission last month. 
Servan-Schreiber said Italian industrialist Giovanni Agnelli also 
had accepted Samaranch's invitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Kissinger's New York office confirmed his acceptance but said he  
would have no further comment. Ueberroth and DeFrantz did not 
return messages left at their southern California offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch wants the commission to meet by early June, with an  
interim report presented to the IOC general assembly later that 
month in Seoul, South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC 2000 was set up last month as the committee's primary engine  
for change after the Salt Lake scandal, in which six members were 
expelled in a million-dollar gifts-for-votes scheme involving the 
Utah capital's successful quest for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission will have 20 to 24 members, half from the IOC and  
half ``leading personalities who understand sport,'' and 
essentially will come up with a new version of the Olympic Charter, 
the IOC's century-old bylaws. 
</P>
<P>
	It will study and make recommendations on selection of Olympic  
host cities, how IOC members are elected, term limits, structure 
and membership of the ruling executive board and further roles for 
Olympic athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel also will look at revenue sharing and the evolution of  
the games themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 22:51:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saints Want Ricky Williams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The New Orleans Saints want Ricky Williams  
and the Heisman Trophy winner would like to be a Saint. 
</P>
<P>
	New Orleans is willing to trade every draft pick this year -- 11  
of them (a second-rounder was dealt to the Rams to get wide 
receiver Eddie Kennison) -- and throw in some picks from next year. 
Maybe even a couple of roster players if need be. 
</P>
<P>
	But Williams doesn't think that's enough to clinch the deal.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's going to happen,'' Williams said Thursday.  
``I want it to. Ideally for me, the Saints trade to No. 1 and I'm 
the No. 1 pick. But I'm pessimistic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams spent the afternoon being wooed by coach Mike Ditka,  
owner Tom Benson and general manager Bill Kuharich. It was the 
second stop of a three-day tour of six teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ditka's a great coach and I'd love to play for him,'' said  
Williams, although he admitted he was afraid of Ditka before 
meeting him, worried about the furious man he'd seen stalking the 
sidelines at games. 
</P>
<P>
	``But he's the nicest guy in the world,'' Williams said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Saints offense was 28th in the NFL last season and was dead  
last in the league in rushing. Williams said Ditka would like to 
change that with a running back who could do for him what Walter 
Payton did in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said he likes to run the ball. He's not going to throw the  
ball around and turn it over. He's just going to run the ball,'' 
Williams said. ``They'll get mad at him and it'll be boring, but 
he'll win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Saints are scheduled to pick 12th in the first round. They  
have picks in every round except the second. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to get a feel for who would be interested in dropping  
down to the 12th spot,'' Kuharich said. ``In dropping down to that 
spot, you get a very different group of players than you get in the 
top 10.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cleveland Browns have the No. 1 pick, and while they are  
thought to be looking for a quarterback, Browns director of 
football operations Dwight Clark said Williams impressed him at a 
workout held Tuesday. Clark said Cleveland is the team New Orleans 
should talk to. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Saints want to make sure they get him, that's the place  
to go,'' Clark said. ``To me, you've got a great player with little 
knowns vs. a quarterback with a larger amount of unknowns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams' agent agreed. Leland Hardy said he believed that,  
after seeing Williams on Tuesday, the Browns will need only about 
five seconds to make him the No. 1 pick on draft day. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is all about minimizing risk,'' Hardy said. ``Now you  
tell me, what's the greater risk, an unproven quarterback who might 
work out, or a proven running back who was the greatest college 
player in the history of the sport?'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Kuharich said if a deal can't be made with the Browns, that  
doesn't mean there won't be a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Browns are where we start, but that doesn't mean we have  
to go that high,'' Kuharich said. ``Speculation is that the first 
three teams will take quarterbacks. Of course, the closer you get 
to the sixth spot, the more problematic it becomes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams also went to St. Louis on Wednesday. He was going to  
Washington and Philadelphia today and heads to Cleveland and 
Indianapolis of Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 13:25:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Down; Corn, Soybeans Up / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures retreated Wednesday on the Chicago  
Board of Trade, while corn and soybeans moved higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures fell amid concerns there will be continued delays  
in shipping aid to Russia because the NATO bombing of Russian ally 
Yugoslavia has strained relations with the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans gained despite the recent expectations that  
farmers will plant huge tracts of corn and soybeans this spring. 
Meantime, harvesting of bumper competing crops in Argentina and 
Brazil is proceeding with little disruption. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for May delivery fell 4 1/4 cents to $2.84 3/4 a bushel; May  
corn rose 1 1/2 cents to $2.17 3/4 a bushel; May oats rose 4 1/4 cents to 
$1.09 1/4 a bushel; May soybeans rose 2 1/4 cents to $4.80 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange amid perceptions supplies will be ample through the heavy 
summer grilling months. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle fell 0.38 cent to 64.92 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle fell 0.42 cent to 73.55 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell 0.90 cent to 54 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 1.22 
cent to 52.10 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
