<DOCNO> APW19990407.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 15:34:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USDA: Pork Board Too Close to Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A quasi-governmental board created to promote  
pork is too closely tied to the industry's trade association, the 
Agriculture Department's inspector general said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But the audit found no evidence the National Pork Board misused  
dollars collected from farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our evaluation showed that the board basically used checkoff  
funds to finance pork promotion, research and consumer education 
projects,'' inspector general Roger Viadero wrote in an audit. 
</P>
<P>
	Hog farmers contribute 45 cents of every $100 of animal value  
for a federally-mandated checkoff fund. The money goes to the 
board, which later contracts promotion services through the 
National Pork Producers Council, the trade group. 
</P>
<P>
	While the audit did not find ``misuse or loss of checkoff  
funds,'' the report concluded the board ``has relinquished too much 
authority to its primary contractor,'' the council, and ``has 
placed the NPPC in a position to exert undue influence over board 
budgets and grant proposals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The board has awarded all program grants to the NPPC since  
1996,'' Viadero wrote, recommending the board take actions to 
``accomplish appropriate separation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Council officials said the inspector general's concerns were  
unwarranted. 
</P>
<P>
	``What really stands out about this report is that it shows we  
did nothing wrong,'' NPPC president John McNutt said during a 
teleconference with the board. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Viadero ``wants to dramatically change a well  
established and well functioning organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``An arm's length relationship does exist between the National  
Pork Board and the NPPC,'' said Greg Boerboom, a producer from 
Marshall, Minn., who is chairman of the board's budget committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The audit comes amid a movement by some pork producers for a  
referendum on whether the checkoff should be voluntary. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing separating the NPPC from the pork board except  
a couple of inches of Sheetrock. It says we're justified,'' Rhonda 
Perry, a Missouri organizer of the anti-checkoff effort, said about 
the audit. 
</P>
<P>
	The board rents space in the council's Des Moines, Iowa,  
headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Perry said the group would announce next week it has enough  
signatures to force a vote on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The board, made up of 15 producers appointed by the agriculture  
secretary, was created by Congress 12 years ago to strengthen pork 
industry promotion. Last year, the program collected $47.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar programs are in place for everything from beef to  
almonds and cotton. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the problems cited in the audit is that the board, with  
its staff of two, is understaffed and too reliant on the council to 
handle its duties. 
</P>
<P>
	``The board's dependence on the NPPC to administer subcontracts  
and carry out much of the board's work resulted in a weakened 
accountability over contributed funds,'' the audit said. 
</P>
<P>
	The inspector general recommended that USDA officials work with  
the board to develop a plan to ``accomplish appropriate 
separation'' from NPPC, including providing sufficient staff and 
accountability checks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 10:45:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Carson Daly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As the host of MTV's daily music-and-interview  
show, ``Total Request Live,'' veejay Carson Daly has what many 
young people consider to be one of the coolest jobs in the world. 
(For the uninitiated: veejay is to video jockey as deejay is to -- 
well, you get it.) 
</P>
<P>
	Daly, 25, is not too much of any one thing. He's funny, but very  
understated. He's smart, but not intimidating. He's good-looking, 
but he's not a pretty boy. Sitting in the veejay's chair in MTV's 
Times Square studios, Carson seems as interested in talking to 
Marilyn Manson as he is chatting with his viewers, who call in and 
say things like ``Play more 98 Degrees because they're hotties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Remember last year's veejay search? Spiky-haired Jesse Camp, all  
of 19, beat out 4,000 contestants and made MTV unpredictable and 
fun to watch. Camp told MTV, ``To be a veejay? C'mon! It's like 
being president of the United States, and MTV is my White House!'' 
</P>
<P>
	On April 17, finalists in MTV's Wanna Be a VJ Too Contest will  
go on the air with Daly for four hours. Viewers will pick the 
winner. Auditions were scheduled this week in Los Angeles and 
Chicago, and will be held in New York April 12-13. Twelve 
semifinalists will be selected: eight from New York, two from Los 
Angeles and two from Chicago. MTV will narrow the list to five 
finalists. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly came to MTV in 1997 after briefly studying theology and  
working as a radio deejay. 
</P>
<P>
	1. Are you going to miss Jesse Camp?  
</P>
<P>
	Daly: Yes, I'm going to miss his eating habits especially, like  
ketchup on coleslaw. He's just fun to watch eat. But I'm going to 
miss him primarily because he got such a green light here. I mean, 
he could do anything he wanted, and I lived through him. He runs 
100 percent on passion and passion only, almost to a fault. 
</P>
<P>
	2. Who was your favorite original MTV veejay?  
</P>
<P>
	Daly: I remember Martha Quinn more than anybody, mainly because  
my sister's name is Quinn. We did a 'Where are they now?' veejay 
thing and I got to meet all of them. They were my constant reminder 
of whether or not I should become an MTV veejay. Because the big 
thing is, well, look at them now. I never made a decision like 'No, 
I'm not going to become an MTV veejay because veejays do Noxzema 
commercials after and that's it.' I was like, 'I'll be happy to do 
anything.' 
</P>
<P>
	3. Any advice for the latest veejay search contestants?  
</P>
<P>
	Daly: Keep it real and and don't be scared. The first time I  
ever did anything on tape was my audition. MTV said, 'Here's a 
camera crew. Go out and toss to some videos.' And I thought, 'How 
difficult can that be?' I didn't know what it meant, but I didn't 
care. I wasn't nervous, I just thought, 'these people are going to 
like me for me, with all my stuttering and all my not looking 
good.' 
</P>
<P>
	4. Do you ever watch yourself on television?  
</P>
<P>
	Daly: Never. Never ever. I can't stand it.  
</P>
<P>
	5. For MTV's ``Celebrity Deathmatch,'' who would win if you  
paired Serena Altschul against Martha Quinn and Kurt Loder against 
Jesse Camp? 
</P>
<P>
	Daly: Serena would definitely win, and Kurt would win,  
absolutely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 22:13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM's Sales Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- U.S. sales of cars and light trucks were up a  
surprisingly strong 8 percent last month, despite a 2 percent sales 
decline at General Motors Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	March sales capped a robust first quarter that exceeded industry  
expectations. First-quarter sales increased 11 percent, led by a 15 
percent rise in truck sales and a 7 percent improvement in car 
sales compared with the first three months of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	GM blamed its lower-than-expected performance on a lean  
inventory of its hottest-selling vehicle, the full-size Chevrolet 
Silverado pickup. GM's car sales increased 1 percent, based on the 
daily sales rate, while sales of light trucks were off 6 percent 
from its strong performance in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a bad performance, but when you look at the  
competition, they had a much better month than GM did,'' said 
analyst Greg Salchow of Roney &AMP; Co. on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Roy Roberts, GM's North American sales chief, said he had not  
seen such a strong quarter in a decade: ``It's really been a shock 
to all of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts noted that GM economists predicted sales industrywide  
this year would run between 15 million and 15.2 million light 
vehicles; in the first quarter, sales ran at a seasonally adjusted 
rate of 16.4 million. As a result, GM has updated its industry 
forecast to 15.7 million units for the year. Last year the industry 
sold 15.6 million cars and light trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It clearly is going to be a very strong year,'' said Mike  
DiGiovanni, GM's head of market research. ``We do see as we move 
into the latter half of the year and next year, some minor slowing 
in the industry because (the growth) is not sustainable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past week, Ford Motor Co. reported its March U.S. sales  
were up 14 percent and DaimlerChrysler AG said its Chrysler unit 
posted a 17 percent improvement. Most major foreign automakers also 
reported strong gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately for GM, many buyers have been turning to Ford and  
Dodge dealers when they've been unable to get a new Silverado 
pickup equipped the way they want. The Silverado is all-new for 
1999, as is its GMC twin, the Sierra. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is virtually selling as fast as we can build it,'' Roberts  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though GM has plans to build 250,000 more trucks this year than  
last, that extra production has only recently begun to kick in. 
</P>
<P>
	While inventories of the more expensive Sierra are fine, GM says  
it has been unable to get stocks of the Silverado up to where it 
wants because of the strong demand. 
</P>
<P>
	GM also sold about 10,000 fewer pickups to business, government  
and rental fleet customers last month than it did in March 1998, as 
it focused on meeting more profitable retail orders. A total of 
53,097 Silverados and 20,042 Sierras were sold last month. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said it has an inventory of about 155,000 full-size pickups,  
but needs between 165,000 to 175,000 to meet dealer needs. About 
30,000 of the current inventory are in transit to dealers. Roberts 
said he expected inventories to reach adequate levels in about five 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts said GM also sold fewer of its compact pickups last  
month because it declined to match the level of sales incentives 
offered by its competition, opting for higher profits over 
increased market share. GM's compacts also lack four-door versions 
that some competitors offer. 
</P>
<P>
	GM's U.S. market share last month was 29.5 percent, down from  
29.7 percent in February but ahead of last year's strike-effected 
29.1 percent. GM has started the year with the goal of gaining 32 
percent of the market, but that's appearing unlikely. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 06:01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NATO Attacks Continue in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Dismissing President Slobodan  
Milosevic's unilateral cease-fire with ethnic Albanian rebels, NATO 
stepped up its airstrikes overnight, hitting military targets in 
Kosovo and inflicting heavy damage elsewhere in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia, meanwhile, emptied a border enclave where tens of  
thousands of Kosovo refugees had been trapped for days in squalid 
conditions. The country has sharply criticized the United States 
and its NATO allies for failing to anticipate the flood of refugees 
driven from Kosovo by Serb forces enraged over NATO's air campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	In Cyprus, the acting parliament speaker said today he was close  
to arranging the release of three American soldiers captured by the 
Yugoslav government. 
</P>
<P>
	Spyros Kyprianou said he will fly to Belgrade today to work for  
the release of the U.S. soldiers. He said his announcement followed 
``informal consultations'' over the past few days. 
</P>
<P>
	Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; Spc. Steven M.  
Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas; and Staff Sgt. Christopher J. 
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.; were captured last week near the 
Yugoslav-Macedonian border. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandy Berger, President Clinton's national security adviser,  
said he was aware of Kyprianou's efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We certainly would welcome the release of the three American  
soldiers but I can't confirm that is going to take place,'' Berger 
said on NBC's ``Today'' show. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, Air Marshal Sir John Day told reporters that the  
increasing intensity of the NATO air campaign against Serbian 
forces was continuing. 
</P>
<P>
	He said 10 Harrier jets attacked four sets of Serb military  
targets in Kosovo, including tanks and convoys of vehicles that 
were targeted with cluster bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said: ``Over the 15 days of  
the air campaign, some 190 attacks have been conducted. Over 80 of 
them have been in the last four days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO airstrikes late Tuesday and today followed a  
declaration by Milosevic's government of a unilateral cease-fire in 
its battle to crush rebels in Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia's 
dominant republic, Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said the cease-fire, which began Tuesday evening,  
was to honor Orthodox Easter. It included an offer to forge a peace 
agreement with moderate ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova, 
under which an estimated 500,000 Kosovars -- overwhelmingly ethnic 
Albanians -- could return home. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbian television said today that Western rejection of the  
unilateral cease-fire proved NATO's ``criminal intentions'' to 
impose foreign ``occupation'' troops on the country. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement from the Yugoslav army said the armed forces were  
abiding by the cease-fire and there was no military activity in the 
province except NATO attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the cease-fire declaration nor statements from Yugoslav  
officials said anything about holding fire against NATO forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after the cease-fire went into effect, air raid sirens  
sounded in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, and explosions were 
heard near a military airfield on the northern rim of the city. 
State-controlled media reported attacks on fuel depots and other 
targets throughout the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Government media said targets included attacks today on a fuel  
storage facility at the airport near Pristina. Serbian TV said NATO 
wiped out a residential area near the old post office in central 
Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	``Undoubtedly there are dead and injured'' the television report  
said, but gave no further details. 
</P>
<P>
	A fuel depot in the village of Devet Jugovica and unspecified  
targets in Ajvalija and Gracanica on the outskirts of Pristina were 
also reported hit. 
</P>
<P>
	State television also said the garage and warehouse at an oil  
refinery in Novi Sad, Serbia's second largest city, were destroyed. 
The official Tanjug news agency said the industrial zone in the 
central Serbian city of Nis was attacked. 
</P>
<P>
	Western leaders denounced the Yugoslav cease-fire as a sham and  
pledged to press ahead with airstrikes until Milosevic accepts 
Western terms. They include withdrawal of Serb special police and 
military units from the province and a three-year interim autonomy 
agreement to be policed by 28,000 NATO-led troops, including 4,000 
Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslav government has rejected that formula, especially  
the presence of foreign troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia, a Yugoslav ally, welcomed the cease-fire declaration.  
``Any peace initiative must be useful,'' spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin 
quoted President Boris Yeltsin as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Yeltsin appealed to Western leaders to halt airstrikes  
and resume talks on ending the crisis over Kosovo. Yeltsin has sent 
messages to several NATO nations, Russian Foreign Minister Igor 
Ivanov said, declining to say which ones or give any details. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen visited NATO headquarters in  
Brussels, Belgium, today for consultations on Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav television stations reported attacks Tuesday night  
around the Kosovo capital of Pristina; at Uzice, 75 miles southwest 
of Belgrade; near Kraljevo, 75 miles south of Belgrade; and at 
Pancevo and Cacak, two industrial towns. U.S. officials say there 
is a munitions plant at Cacak. 
</P>
<P>
	Another missile struck a residential district in Podgorica,  
capital of the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro. There were no 
injuries, but several buildings were damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	As the bombings continued, NATO nations and others rushed in aid  
for the ethnic Albanians who have been driven out of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Aid workers and soldiers set up rows of military tents and  
latrines for the refugees, while aid flights clogged airports, 
including the one at Tirana, the capital of Albania. Some doctors 
were on hand at the camps, but the squalid conditions and lack of 
sanitation left many refugees sick with diarrhea. 
</P>
<P>
	Conditions were most desperate at Blace on the Macedonian  
border, where some refugees have died. Macedonia, governed by a 
fragile coalition of Slavs and ethnic Albanians, fears the influx 
of Kosovo Albanians will destabilize the country and wants the 
refugees out as soon as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Western countries have begun an airlift to evacuate thousands of  
refugees from the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 06:01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
