<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NRC Cites New England Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New England's largest utility was cited for  
violations Tuesday in discriminating against workers who raised 
safety concerns about Connecticut's Millstone nuclear power plant. 
But it escaped a fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission appointed an independent  
review team to review the discrimination cases in January after 
questions were raised about its own failure to punish the company 
earlier for actions against whistleblowers. 
</P>
<P>
	The review team found adequate evidence that Northeast  
Utilities' nuclear subsidiary, Northeast Nuclear Energy Company, 
discriminated against three workers in 1993 and 1995 for raising 
safety concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	There was not sufficient evidence of discrimination in a third  
case involving 1996 dismissals, it found. 
</P>
<P>
	The NRC, based on those findings, said the utility would receive  
a notice of violation for three violations to ensure that such 
discrimination is not repeated. 
</P>
<P>
	It also sent a notice of violation to a former utility vice  
president, who has since left the company, and letters of reprimand 
to four company managers. The identities of the managers are to be 
made public after they have had a chance to respond. 
</P>
<P>
	But while a ``civil penalty normally is considered for such  
significant violations,'' the NRC refrained from levying a fine 
because of the progress that the utility has made in handling 
employee concerns and creating a workplace environment that 
stresses safety. 
</P>
<P>
	The utility's history of harassing and intimidating  
whistleblowers contributed to an accumulation of safety problems 
that ultimately led to the shutdown of all three Millstone reactors 
in 1995 and 1996. One reactor has since returned to power. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, the NRC lifted an order requiring independent  
oversight of the utility's employee concerns program to guard 
against discrimination, harassment and intimidation. 
</P>
<P>
	Northeast Utilities serves 1.7 million people in Connecticut,  
Massachusetts and New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, the NRC's Office of Inspector General issued a  
report on the agency's handling of harassment and discrimination 
complaints made by 22 Millstone workers who were among 102 
employees fired in January 1996 as part of a cost-cutting 
reduction. 
</P>
<P>
	It found that NRC staffers, in December 1997, decided to take  
accelerated enforcement action against the utility based on 
evidence that a former vice president has discriminated against two 
or possibly three workers who raised safety concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	The company could have been subject to a fine of $100,000 or  
more, but the NRC's Office of Enforcement never followed through. 
Instead, the initial decision was dropped at a second enforcement 
conference meeting, and the inspector general did not find a 
written record of the reason for the change. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the independent review team reached a different  
conclusion, it did not criticize the NRC staffers' handling of the 
case. However, it recommended improvements to the agency's 
investigative and enforcement processes. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
