<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suzuki Buys Into General Motors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Suzuki Motor Corp. has acquired a stake of  
less than 1 percent in U.S. automaker General Motors Corp. to 
strengthen an existing alliance between the two companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Suzuki has bought 500,000 shares of GM, representing a 0.7  
percent stake in the world's largest carmaker, for about $37 
million, a Suzuki spokesman said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Last September, GM announced it would increase its stake in  
Suzuki to 10 percent, and Suzuki's acquisition the American 
company's shares is intended to bolster their partnership, 
according to the spokesman, who spoke on condition that he not be 
identified by name. 
</P>
<P>
	The two carmakers already have a joint venture in Canada and  
have been increasing coordination of their global manufacturing 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Suzuki has primary responsibility for the design and development  
of small passenger vehicles, particularly in Asia. U.S.-based GM is 
responsible for midsize and large passenger vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Suzuki is Japan's largest manufacturer of mini-vehicles and the  
world's third biggest motorcycle maker. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement comes amid a wave of global consolidation  
within the auto industry. Last month, France's Renault acquired a 
36.8 percent stake in Japan's ailing Nissan Motor Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, a newspaper reported that Japan's Mitsubishi  
Motor Co. and Mazda Motor Co., which is controlled by U.S. carmaker 
Ford, are in negotiations to form a broad technological alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 19:42:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ripken Misses Start Due to Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- For the first time since 1982, Cal Ripken  
missed a game because of injury Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, who left the Baltimore Orioles' season opener Monday in  
the third inning with stiffness in his lower back, watched 
Wednesday night's 8-5 loss to Tampa Bay from the dugout while 
Willis Otanez took over at third base. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could beat my head against the wall and go do it today, but  
it doesn't make sense,'' Ripken said. ```We're going to just work 
toward being ready tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last Sept. 20, Ripken voluntarily ended his record streak of  
playing in 2,632 games by sitting out the Orioles' final home game 
against the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, his absence was not by choice.  
</P>
<P>
	``He told me was 90 percent better and I told him I'd rather err  
on the side of caution and give him another 24 hours,'' manager Ray 
Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my heart I know he never played a game just because of the  
streak. Fortunately for us it's not there anymore, so we can use a 
little better judgment,'' Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the streak were still alive, it probably would have come to a  
dramatic conclusion Wednesday night. Ripken, 38, removed himself 
from Monday's game because his back locked up, leaving him unable 
to continue. 
</P>
<P>
	Although his back felt much better Wednesday, it was far from  
perfect. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it was 90 percent, playing would be a no-brainer,'' Ripken  
said. ``Every situation is different, but I doubt I'd play tonight 
regardless if the streak was still alive. ... I want to be able to 
contribute this whole season, and it wouldn't make sense to push it 
just to play one game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Ripken missed a game because of injury was in May  
1982 after he got beaned by Oakland rookie Mike Moore. His record 
streak began later that month and survived two ankle injuries, a 
twisted knee and a herniated disk in his back in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	None of those injuries affected him the way his injury did  
Monday, when he was rendered helpless by stiffness, tightness and 
spasms in his lower back. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't consider myself superhuman. But I never reached a  
point where I couldn't play until the other day,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Orioles shortstop Mike Bordick expected it might be a bit  
strange when he looked to his right and didn't see Ripken standing 
there at third base. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's surprising not to see his name in the lineup. Everyone  
just expects that name to be written in,'' Bordick said. 
``Obviously he must be hurting. For him to come out of a game the 
other day the way he did, he obviously must be in some pretty good 
pain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Otanez was just happy to get a chance to play. When Ripken sat  
out last year's game against the New York Yankees, Ryan Minor 
manned third base. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice for me, I was happy to see I'm playing,'' he said.  
``But I don't want my teammate to get hurt like that. That's not 
good. I hope he gets well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Otanez doubled and hit his first major league homer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
