<DOCNO> APW19990407.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 23:32:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Celtic Great Reflects on Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- His opinions were as plentiful as his  
characteristic cackles. Bill Russell was back in Boston and, as he 
did in his playing days, made his presence felt. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been 30 years since he left the NBA with his 11th title in  
13 seasons with the Celtics, but he still watches plenty of 
basketball -- as many as three games a day on television -- and 
doesn't like everything he sees. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I have a complaint, which I don't usually have because I  
like the game, I think the coaches are in charge, and so there is 
no creativity among the players, not very much anyway,'' he said 
Wednesday night before Boston's 108-87 win over Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like to see creativity,'' he added. ``I like to think when I  
was a young player I was very creative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the center known for his intensity and defense has been  
impressed with another aspect of the modern players' performances. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing to watch people with that much money work that  
hard,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Then his face broadened into a wide grin and he laughed  
heartily. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell, who lives on the West Coast, made a rare appearance at  
a Celtics game to promote The Bill Russell Tribute scheduled for 
May 26 at the FleetCenter, adjacent to the site of the old Boston 
Garden and the team's home for the fourth year. 
</P>
<P>
	His No. 6 will be re-retired at an evening of entertainment,  
with a cast scheduled to include Bill Cosby, Aretha Franklin, 
Muhammad Ali, Wilt Chamberlain, Hank Aaron, Julius Erving and NBA 
commissioner David Stern. 
</P>
<P>
	That number originally was retired on March 12, 1972 with, as  
Russell desired, much less fanfare. He and his former coach, Red 
Auerbach, tugged on the ropes that raised the banner to the Boston 
Garden rafters one Sunday morning before any fans entered for an 
afternoon game. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell, one of the NBA's greatest players, couldn't understand  
what the fuss was about. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still don't particularly like awards and things, because I  
always felt I was just doing what I was supposed to do,'' he said. 
``I had the same reaction when they wanted to put me in the Hall of 
Fame. I just never liked that kind of thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he agreed to the May 26 ceremony, in part, because proceeds  
will go to The National Mentoring Partnership and the Mass 
Mentoring Partnership, a state organization. 
</P>
<P>
	And he wants his ex-teammates to know ``it does me honor to be  
on a banner with them,'' he said. ``I don't think there's any place 
on the planet (with) a better group of men than the guys I played 
with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He shared plenty of other opinions:  
</P>
<P>
	--''The old Garden was really a dump,'' he said. ``This new  
building is quite sterile, but then the Garden did have character, 
and rats. But this is a nice building.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--If the young Celtics, 11-22 and almost certain to miss the  
playoffs, ``can be patient and keep those guys together and ... 
realize that the better the guy next to you plays the better you 
are,'' they will improve. 
</P>
<P>
	--With teams playing illegal defenses, pro basketball ``is a  
little dull sometimes'' and he blames the coaches' tactics for 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	--He starts watching NBA games at 4:30 p.m. on the West Coast and  
often sees three in a row, ``but I stop to watch Jeopardy,'' he 
said with another laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	How does he do?  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm OK,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	He usually was. After all, he averaged 22.5 rebounds per game  
for his career and was named the NBA's greatest player in 1980 by 
the Professional Basketball Writers' Association of America. 
</P>
<P>
	And as a player-coach with Boston, Russell won titles in two of  
his three seasons after first telling Auerbach he didn't want to 
succeed him. 
</P>
<P>
	How did he explain his change of heart to Auerbach?  
</P>
<P>
	``That's the one time I could make sure that I have a coach I  
like as much as I like you,'' he recalled, ``maybe more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then he laughed again.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
