<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 14:05:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Lays Off 280 in St. Louis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Boeing Co. is laying off 280 workers on its  
fighter aircraft line and says as many as 620 more employees could 
lose their jobs by fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The layoffs stem largely from a slowdown in orders for its F-15  
Eagles, Boeing said. 
</P>
<P>
	The union workers who received pink slips include sheet-metal  
workers, material handlers, and machinists. They will work until 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing said Tuesday that as many as 320 more production workers  
and 300 non-union employees could lose their jobs within six 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The projections, which the company called a ``worst-case  
scenario,'' could mean that Boeing will have trimmed its St. Louis 
work force by 15 percent -- from 22,800 employees to 19,600 -- in 
less than two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle-based Boeing is the world's largest commercial aircraft  
maker and the nation's second-largest defense contractor. St. Louis 
is the headquarters for Boeing's defense division. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has about 36 remaining orders for the F-15 Eagles  
from the Air Force and Saudi Arabia. But the last Eagle will be 
delivered early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing had hoped to receive orders for as many as 40 Eagles from  
Greece as early as last December. The Greek government has 
postponed its decision several times. Boeing also expects to learn 
in May or June whether Israel will buy more of the Eagles. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing hopes to avoid shutting down the Eagle production line  
because restarting it would be costly. The company is slowing 
production to two Eagles a month from three a month earlier this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Work also is slowing on Boeing's biggest production line in St.  
Louis, the F/A-18 Hornet strike fighter. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 15:25:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Cops Arrested in Conn. Crackdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Two Hartford police officers were charged  
Wednesday with demanding sexual favors from prostitutes under 
threat of arrest, and another officer and a former colleague 
pleaded guilty to related charges. 
</P>
<P>
	More arrests are expected from the six-month investigation by  
federal, state and local authorities, said Chief State's Attorney 
John M. Bailey. More than 20 police officers have been ordered to 
appear before a grand jury, The Hartford Courant has reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``These officers betrayed their trust, but more importantly they  
betrayed the other officers in the department,'' said Michael Wolf, 
acting special agent in charge of the FBI's Connecticut office. 
</P>
<P>
	Since October, a federal grand jury has been investigating  
alleged corruption in the department, including the prostitutes' 
allegations and the possibility that officers were involved in two 
unrelated, unsolved slayings. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Courant, prostitutes have told grand jurors  
that officers assigned to two Hartford neighborhoods have ordered 
women into their patrol cars under the threat of arrest, driven 
them to cemeteries and other secluded spots, and demanded oral sex. 
The women said the conduct has gone on for at least two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrol officers Michael Basile, 41, and Jesus Rivera, 30, were  
charged with violating the civil rights of Hartford-area 
prostitutes. Both pleaded innocent and were released on $100,000 
bond. 
</P>
<P>
	Officer Salvatore Abateillo III, 35, pleaded guilty to aiding  
and abetting Rivera. He said he was present during alleged sexual 
acts but did not intervene. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Officer Jose L. Pizarro, also 35, pleaded guilty to  
providing Rivera with a camera used to take nude pictures of the 
prostitutes. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the alleged crimes happened while the officers were in  
uniform and on duty, prosecutors said. Abateillo, Basile and Rivera 
were suspended without pay, police Chief Joseph F. Croughwell Jr. 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 15:43:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Excerpts From Recent Editorials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers in the  
United States and abroad: 

</P>
<P>
	April 4  
</P>
<P>
	The Sunday Oregonian, Portland, on Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	The air attacks speak to Slobodan Milosevic in a language that  
he can understand. He is unlikely to care about military, or even 
civilian, casualties from the NATO bombs. But he does care about 
his own hold on power. 
</P>
<P>
	That hold is partly the result of his pervasive military and  
security apparatus -- which is the target of these attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslav dictator cannot easily replace the guns, missiles,  
tanks and troops that he is losing every day to NATO attackers. 
When Western military planners say they want Milosevic's oppression 
of the Kosovars to be costly, they mean exactly that. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, it may not even be Milosevic who decides that the  
price for oppressing Kosovars is too high. It may be his military 
or other beneficiaries of the last totalitarian regime in central 
Europe who decide. 
</P>
<P>
	For now though, Milosevic appears to be betting that his  
resources will hold out longer than the West's political resolve. 
If civilized, democratic ideals are to prevail in this troubled 
part of Europe, it's critical that Milosevic's bet turn out to be a 
bad one. 

</P>
<P>
	April 4  
</P>
<P>
	Las Cruces (N.M.) Sun-News, on Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	Americans, in the comfort of their living rooms, hear the  
warnings from the TV newscasters: ``The pictures you are about to 
see are unpleasant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then they show video just brought out of Kosovo by an ethnic  
Albanian man of the bodies of up to 100 men in his village who had 
been executed by invading Serbs. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Americans can turn off the TV, and go onto other things --  
pleasant things. They know that some of their fellow Americans are 
carrying the bulk of the load in NATO's mission to stop the mass 
killings of Kosovars and are bombing Yugoslavia and are striving 
against tough odds to get food and water and medical aid and 
shelter to the refugees. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The day will come ... where those who survive will be in tents  
and under the care of humanitarian organizations. Whether and when 
they will ever return to their homes in not known. 
</P>
<P>
	... It can only be hoped that the refugees can someday sit  
peacefully back at home and watch TV themselves to see Milosevic 
and other thugs being tried and convicted by an international war 
crimes tribunal. 

</P>
<P>
	April 1  
</P>
<P>
	The Times-Picayune, New Orleans, on Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	The mess that Operation Allied Force in Yugoslavia has become is  
an embarrassment to NATO and the United States and a disaster to 
the Kosovars the operation was designed to protect. 
</P>
<P>
	The first purpose of the massive airstrikes against the Serbian  
military infrastructure was to keep the Serbs from further attacks 
on the Kosovars, yet the Serb attacks were speeded up and increased 
in savagery. ... 
</P>
<P>
	NATO admits that the obviously well planned Serbian campaign  
took them by surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	After more than a week of NATO bombing, the Yugoslav President  
Slobodan Milosevic's barbaric scorched-earth ethnic cleansing 
against Kosovo and Kosovars continues unabated. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The other goal of Allied Force has been to compel him to sign  
the agreement on a transitional peace settlement that the Kosovars 
have already signed. ... 
</P>
<P>
	But that idea now seems gone by the board. ...  
</P>
<P>
	Without a discernible NATO exit strategy, the ball remains in  
Mr. Milosevic's court. He must decide whether virtual destruction 
of his military power is worth refusing to deal with the Kosovars. 

</P>
<P>
	April 4  
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati Enquirer, on Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	If the U.S. and NATO airstrikes stop the Serbs' brutal campaign  
to eradicate Albanian Muslims from the Kosovo province of 
Yugoslavia, a noble chapter in world history can be written, 
telling how the world's greatest superpower used its might not for 
self-interest, but to protect innocent people from savagery in a 
faraway land. 
</P>
<P>
	But history mocks attempts to achieve ground-level goals with  
air attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the best thing Americans can do now is to pray -- and  
help the tidal waves of refugees flooding into Montenegro, 
Macedonia and Albania, poor neighbors that could be dragged into 
war by the burden of hundreds of thousands of desperate, starving 
families. 
</P>
<P>
	Humanitarian aid may stop the spread of war and stabilize the  
region. 

</P>
<P>
	April 2  
</P>
<P>
	Odessa (Texas) American, on Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	As NATO steps up its air raids on Serb targets and as U.S. and  
NATO officials hint at the possible commitment of American ground 
troops to the region, Congress is out on spring break until next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	While Kosovo burns, members of Congress are tackling constituent  
business, working on various issues in Washington or traveling the 
globe in pursuit of some policy objective or another. 
</P>
<P>
	It's yet another example of how Congress has abdicated its  
constitutional war-making authority to the executive branch. 
</P>
<P>
	There's nothing wrong with getting back to their districts. But  
both parties' congressional leaders, whether they support the war 
or not, should have kept the House and Senate in session to hold 
hearings about the many facets of this escalating military mission. 
...
</P>
<P>
	One advantage of the congressional recess is that legislators  
might get an earful about the air strikes from their constituents. 
Perhaps that might entice them to take a more active role in this 
very dangerous military action. 

</P>
<P>
	April 5  
</P>
<P>
	Star Tribune of Minneapolis, on Iraq:  
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the sudden cataclysm suffered by Kosovars, the ordeal of  
Iraqis is prolonged. Nearly nine years of international sanctions 
have driven an oil-rich country from a prospering society to one in 
which most people -- though not the governing elite -- lack adequate 
food and medicine. Once again the United Nations is trying to help. 
Once again Iraq says no. 
</P>
<P>
	The impasse seems unbreakable, but experience suggests it is  
not. In the early 1990s, the U.N. Security Council, with strong 
U.S. endorsement, agreed to permit limited Iraqi oil sales to 
purchase food and medicine under U.N. supervision. The offer 
remained on the table for more than a year before Iraq reluctantly 
accepted. The original ceiling, $1.6 billion a year, has risen to 
$5.2 billion every six months. 
</P>
<P>
	So international persistence in dealing with Iraq's unpleasant  
leaders is one route to helping its people survive. But persistence 
has proved difficult lately. Differences within the Security 
Council became acute last fall when Iraq ended all cooperation with 
the U.N. Special Commission charged with overseeing the elimination 
of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction. Differences became still 
more acute in December after the four-day bombing campaign by 
Britain and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to bridge those differences, the Security Council  
appointed panels to evaluate Iraq's humanitarian conditions, 
disarmament and reparations due Kuwait for its 1990 invasion. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Although the panels' findings respond to criticism of U.N. and  
U.S. policy toward Iraq, they also show a welcome tough-mindedness. 
There is no suggestion of abandoning supervision of Iraqi arms. ... 
Nor is there any suggestion that the panels accept Iraq's 
demonstrably false claim that it is complying with Security Council 
resolutions. That is why the embargo must remain, as the panels 
acknowledge. ... 

</P>
<P>
	April 1.  
</P>
<P>
	The State, Columbia, S.C., on the Kevorkian verdict:  
</P>
<P>
	A jury has rightly decided that Dr. Jack Kevorkian, the death  
angel of the medical world, stepped over a bright, sparkling line 
when he injected a terminally ill patient with a poison that killed 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Until this case, what Kevorkian did was assist some 130 dying  
patients to commit suicide. In other words, he provided the drugs 
and environment for desperately sick people to end their lives. 
They took the final action. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kevorkian clearly committed an act of murder when he gave a  
lethal dose to Thomas Youk, 52, who suffered from Lou Gehrig's 
Disease. ... 
</P>
<P>
	It is clearly beyond the pale for a physician, acting without  
safeguards and with premeditation, to kill in the name of mercy. In 
this case, Kevorkian was an executioner -- not a doctor. 

</P>
<P>
	April 1  
</P>
<P>
	South County Journal, Kent, Wash., on Social Security:  
</P>
<P>
	The economic news is cheery and so the Clinton administration  
trumpets the prediction that the Social Security trust will not 
poop out until 2034. That's two years later than earlier predicted. 
But there's still need to worry. 
</P>
<P>
	The supposed trust fund is an accounting fiction. Lean on it and  
you lean on air. It is essentially a collection of IOUs. It has no 
assets. All the payroll tax surpluses that are owed back to Social 
Security -- which could have gone to pay down debt, making it easier 
to borrow the money when needed -- have actually been spent on other 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Read the fine print and understand the vocabulary in the  
administration's report and you find the real year of reckoning is 
2014. ... 
</P>
<P>
	This predicted year when Social Security income is no longer  
greater than Social Security expenditures is now put at a year 
later than previously, owing to the country's economic growth. But 
2014 is still so close to this problem -- and the amounts then due 
so great -- that action ought to be taken no later than this 
congressional session to begin accumulating real reserves in 
private, profit-producing accounts and thereby preventing 
unpleasant emergency measures later. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 31  
</P>
<P>
	The News-Journal, Daytona Beach, Fla., on baseball and Cuba:  
</P>
<P>
	If Ping-Pong diplomacy worked modestly to help restore normal  
relations between the United States and Communist China a quarter 
century ago, is it not conceivable that baseball diplomacy could 
play a similar role in improving U.S. relations with Communist 
Cuba? That would be a happy ending, but let's not get carried away 
by one game in Havana. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball is a common language. Its moves, strategy and tactics  
are fully understood by speakers of many tongues. Ideology 
blessedly is foreign to the game. ... 
</P>
<P>
	It is true the 50,000 fans in the stands when the Baltimore  
Orioles played the Cuban national team in Havana the other day were 
all invited by the government, some because they were Communist 
Party members and others as a reward for accomplishments. ... 
</P>
<P>
	But whether the action was before Fidel Castro at Estadio  
Latinoamericano or ordinary Cubans at a dusty old beisbol diamond 
elsewhere in tattered Havana, a good time was had by all. More good 
times could be in store for the Cuban and American people if their 
leaders ever conclude that better political relations serve their 
mutual interests. 

</P>
<P>
	April 7  
</P>
<P>
	Corriere della Sera, Milan, Italy on Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	(Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic is clever but follows a  
simple and predictable plan: He used the first phase of NATO air 
strikes to start the ethnic cleansing of a large part of the Kosovo 
population. He announced a unilateral cease-fire, once he completed 
much of this scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	His political and diplomatic aims are evident. NATO has refused  
his peace offer but Milosevic knows some European allies will ask 
for a halt in the air strikes. It's easy to predict that the his 
next move will be to widen this crack. ... 

</P>
<P>
	April 7  
</P>
<P>
	The Daily Telegraph, London, on Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	First came the offer to withdraw some Serbian forces from Kosovo  
if NATO stopped bombing Yugoslavia. Yesterday, a more subtle and 
confusing set of proposals emerged. ... Slobodan Milosevic, having 
achieved a furious momentum in his drive to rid Kosovo of 
non-Serbs, is now seeking to halt the momentum building on the 
allied side in an attempt to counter his brutality. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO immediately rejected Belgrade's first offer, made last  
month through Yevgeny Primakov, the Russian prime minister. 
Yesterday, the main alliance powers were commendably swift in 
turning down the second. When the bombing started, we were highly 
skeptical of the alliance's willingness to pursue military action 
to its logical conclusion: the definitive removal of Serbian 
security forces from the province. The past two weeks have seen a 
slight advance in the allies' ambitions, from providing relief from 
persecution to creating conditions for all the refugees to return. 
But their reluctance to define a proper political goal, the 
establishment of an independent Kosovo, leaves them vulnerable to 
Mr. Milosevic's blandishments. ... 

</P>
<P>
	April 6  
</P>
<P>
	The Times, London, on Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	As the numbers grow, so do fears and resentment in the  
precarious countries to which the Kosovans are fleeing. All three 
are among the most vulnerable in Europe, desperately poor, beset by 
their own ethnic and tribal conflicts and with shaky governments 
easily overthrown by populists exploiting the present crisis. ... 
</P>
<P>
	NATO insists that as the weather clears ... the Serb terror in  
Kosovo will be slowed and eventually halted. For many, it will be 
too late. Tony Blair was right to insist that the attacks must be 
stepped up. British Tornados based in Germany took part in the air 
raids for the first time at the weekend; two battalions of American 
Apache helicopters, designed to attack ground forces, will soon 
arrive in Tirana. The NATO aim remains consistent: to force the 
Serb troops out of Kosovo, allow the refugees to return and police 
their safety with a Nato peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	That aim, however, is still far from being achieved. It will  
take a lot more firepower, more flexible tactics and more time to 
break Serbian intransigence. And neither the refugees nor the host 
countries have time. Even after a ceasefire, few will return unless 
a sizeable military force clears the way and escorts them home. ... 

</P>
<P>
	April 6  
</P>
<P>
	Frankfurter Rundschau, Frankfurt, Germany, on NATO:  
</P>
<P>
	NATO didn't imagine its 50th birthday this way. The alliance  
that for decades earnestly maintained peace, finds itself not only 
in a war with Serbia, it is threatened with losing. ... The primary 
war goal of NATO -- to stop the murder and expulsion in Kosovo -- has 
not been achieved. In a few days Milosevic's troops and gangs will 
have completed their ethnic cleansing of Kosovo. Hundreds of 
thousands of Albanians are fleeing and the gigantic task to aid 
them has become the central point of the war, far more so than the 
air attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	A success for celebrator NATO can now only be measured on how  
quickly and in what dimension they succeed in giving back the 
Kosovars their homeland. ... 

</P>
<P>
	April 7  
</P>
<P>
	The Australian, Sydney, on Libya and Lockerbie:  
</P>
<P>
	The imprint of a charred aircraft skeleton over the houses and  
fields of the Scottish village of Lockerbie is an image not easily 
forgotten by those who saw it on their television screens more than 
10 years ago. ... 
</P>
<P>
	This week two men accused of the crime ... have arrived in The  
Netherlands from Libya to face extradition proceedings and then 
trial before a Scottish court built especially in The Netherlands. 
...
</P>
<P>
	Sanctions against Libya could have been eased long ago if the  
Lockerbie accused, indicted in 1991, had surrendered. Indeed, 
sanctions would never have been imposed if the Libyan government 
had not condoned and supported acts of terrorism against other 
states, a history that extends back well before the Lockerbie 
bombing. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The many costs of pursuing the criminals for 10 years ... are  
too high to be quantified but they have had to be paid. If this 
trial demonstrates that acts of terrorism will be punished, no 
matter how long it takes, the effort will have been worthwhile. 

</P>
<P>
	April 6  
</P>
<P>
	Neue Zuercher Zeitung, Zurich, Switzerland, on Libya and  
Lockerbie: 
</P>
<P>
	... What exactly persuaded Tripoli to give way is not clear. The  
readiness of the British and Americans to have the proceedings 
against the two alleged terrorists not in Scotland itself but in a 
Scottish court in the Netherlands was not enough to account for the 
Libyan change of heart. 
</P>
<P>
	There may be another, unwritten concession behind the handover:  
a promise from the British and Americans not to stretch the trial 
in the Netherlands into a general reckoning of the Libyan secret 
service and the Gadhafi regime. The clients of the two Libyans... 
will remain hidden. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a renunciation would be detrimental to the court's finding  
of the truth. And the call for justice from the relatives of the 
crash victims would only be fulfilled in part. No one could talk of 
anything more than a merely symbolic conclusion to the unfortunate 
Lockerbie affair. 

</P>
<P>
	April 5  
</P>
<P>
	The Irish Times, Dublin, on Angola:  
</P>
<P>
	This week, events in Angola may confirm that neither side in the  
long and bloody civil war can really hope to win. Through the 
weekend, the Unita rebels pushed closer to the strategically 
important northern city of Malanje, capturing most of its outlying 
villages and meeting no resistance from the army. The government, 
last Friday, issued a surprisingly blunt statement, acknowledging 
that Unita was on a roll but promising that it will soon peak and 
the government will then re-assert itself. Western diplomats in the 
capital, Luanda, are not so sure. ... 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 15:22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Israelis, Saudis Helping Kosovars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIRANA, Albania (AP) -- Taking time off from his chores on an  
Israeli communal farm, Oded Gal unloaded baby formula for Kosovo 
refugees onto a U.N. truck, waving a friendly hello at a Saudi 
relief team a few yards down the tarmac. 
</P>
<P>
	The scope of the refugees' suffering has brought together former  
enemies trying to lend a hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see this on TV, and you've got to do something,'' said  
Gal, a volunteer with Giving, a privately run Israeli relief group. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to the Kosovo refugee crisis, the Jewish Agency,  
once dedicated solely to Jewish rescue and immigration, has 
launched its first-ever relief operation in a region where 
significant numbers of Jews are not present. 
</P>
<P>
	In Jerusalem, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu announced that  
Israel would take in 100 Kosovar refugees, saying the Jewish state 
felt driven to take the step by its memories of the Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
	Jewish Agency chairman Sallai Meridor also recalled the  
Holocaust to explain the shift in his organization's policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have witnessed the horror of people forced out of their  
homes, people shipped on trains,'' Meridor told Albanian Foreign 
Minister Milo Paskal on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thanks for the human solidarity,'' Paskal replied. ``Albania  
is in difficult days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials say nearly a quarter-million Kosovo refugees now are  
in Albania, driven from their homes in the southern Serbian 
province. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jewish Agency brought in eight tons of relief supplies  
Tuesday, including tents, sleeping bags, baby formula and milk. 
Meridor said another 34 tons would arrive by the end of the week. 
</P>
<P>
	An Israeli army officer briefing soldiers headed for Macedonia  
to set up a field hospital reminded them of the significance of 
returning to lands their parents and grandparents had fled. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that Jews are more sensitive because of the  
Holocaust, I wouldn't say that,'' said Gal. ``But you see certain 
things and you understand the consequences. There are those who 
want to make people different; I want to show how similar we are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Seiden, a real estate developer from Livingston, N.J.,  
said his experience fundraising for Jewish causes led him to join 
this mission. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's reminiscent of what our parents went through,'' Seiden  
said. ``I feel obligated to help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Tirana's main swimming pool complex, crowded with refugees  
living in tents, a voice recited family names over the public 
address system, calling refugees to meet others looking for missing 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Search for Missing Relatives,'' said Jewish Agency  
official Avinoam Bar-Yosef, recalling a column that appeared daily 
in most Israeli newspapers for years after the Holocaust. ``This 
brings back memories.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crisis among the overwhelmingly Muslim Kosovo refugees has  
also drawn assistance from the Arab world. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuwait began a three-day airlift Tuesday, and Saudi Arabia also  
sent a plane packed with relief supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel and the Saudis are still technically at war and do not  
maintain diplomatic ties -- but that didn't stop friendly smiles on 
the Tirana tarmac. 
</P>
<P>
	In the refugee camp, an Albanian relief worker said his people  
appreciated the aid, whatever its origin. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know why Israel is doing this,'' said Paulin Vilajeti.  
``They suffered the exodus so many times. Today, that is the 
position of Kosovo.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 15:22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
