<DOCNO> APW19990407.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 05:45:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HP Names Executives of Four Units </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Hewlett-Packard Co. has named top  
executives for its four key business operations but is still 
looking for a new chief executive for the computing and imaging 
company it is spinning off next year. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Palo Alto, Calif., corporation announced that  
Carolyn Ticknor, 51, will be the Boise-based president and chief 
executive of the laserjet imaging systems unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Ann Livermore, 40, was named president and chief executive  
officer of the enterprise computing solutions unit, which includes 
computer systems, storage and software. 
</P>
<P>
	Duane Zitzner, 51, is the president and chief executive of the  
company's computer products unit, which includes the company's 
business and home personal computers, servers, workstations, 
storage devices and mobile appliances. 
</P>
<P>
	And Antonio Perez, 53, was named president and chief executive  
of the inkjet imaging solutions unit. 
</P>
<P>
	The four were former general managers and vice presidents of  
their units and will remain corporate vice presidents. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, Hewlett-Packard said it will make its $7.6  
billion-a-year test and measurement equipment operations into a 
separate company in 2000 in order to focus on its core computer and 
printer business. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining computing and imaging company, which will operate  
under the Hewlett-Packard name, accounted for $39.5 billion of the 
company's 1998 revenue of $47.1 billion. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
