<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yield Rises in Bond Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Yields on 30-year, inflation-indexed bonds  
rose in Wednesday's auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield was 3.899 percent, the highest on record. The bonds  
sold at 3.680 percent at the last auction on July 8 and 3.740 
percent at the first auction on April 15, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the government's 10th auction of inflation-indexed  
securities -- and the third at the 30-year maturity -- since it began 
selling them in January 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the yield, owners of inflation-indexed bonds  
receive an adjustment to principal twice a year. For instance, if 
inflation were 2 percent in a year, the principal of a $1,000 note 
would increase to $1,020. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of $7 billion in bonds were sold out of bids totaling  
$14.7 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
