<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Dolphins RB Spikes Faces Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Former Miami Dolphins running back  
Irving Spikes' legal troubles are mounting. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old Spikes was indicted last week in Fort  
Lauderdale, charged with cocaine conspiracy and possession with 
intent to distribute. Each federal count carries a minimum 
mandatory five-year prison sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Spikes was jailed last month in Gulfport, Miss., on federal drug  
and weapon charges, including selling cocaine to a teammate while 
still a player with the Dolphins. He awaits trial there. 
</P>
<P>
	In that indictment, Spikes also was charged with selling cocaine  
to a major drug dealer and participating in a shootout with the 
drug dealer outside the dealer's west Biloxi apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	Spikes played for the Dolphins from 1994 until 1998, when he was  
cut. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Mississippi indictment, FBI agent Jerome Lorrain  
testified that Spikes twice sold more than 4 pounds of cocaine to 
Dolphins teammate Derek Joiner and later sold him 4 pounds of fake 
cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	In the fake cocaine sale described by Lorrain, Spikes tried to  
convince Joiner that some wrapped sheetrock was cocaine. But when 
Joiner tried to inspect it, Spikes' partner pulled a gun and took 
$17,000 from the player. 
</P>
</TEXT>
