<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 18:12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Muser Defends Offerman Comment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Kansas City manager Tony Muser said he  
doesn't understand why people are ``making such a big deal'' out of 
his comments that Jose Offerman doesn't always hustle. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's obvious to a lot of people that Offie had periods when he  
didn't run the ball out,'' Muser said Wednesday prior to the 
Royals' game against Boston, the team Offerman left Kansas City to 
join. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not something that's dreamt up or anything. I lot of  
people saw that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, his third with the Royals and his first full year  
under Muser, Offerman had a breakthrough season with career-highs 
in batting average (.315), hits (191) home runs (7) and triples 
(13). 
</P>
<P>
	Offerman then bolted the cash-poor Royals and signed a  
four-year, $26 million free agent contract with the Red Sox. Muser 
made a few joking references to him during the Royals' winter 
awards dinner, saying, ``We'll get you, Offie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Offerman, after going 4-for-5 and leading the Red Sox past  
Kansas City 5-3 in the season opener, became angry when reminded 
that Muser had sometimes questioned his willingness to hustle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Muser can say say whatever he wants to say. I don't play for  
him anymore,'' Offerman said. ``I know I gave 100 percent every 
time for them. I hit .315 ... I hit 13 triples. What else am I 
supposed to do? That's stupid for him to say.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
