<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Asian Markets Continue To Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asia's three biggest stock markets, Tokyo, Hong  
Kong and Singapore, extended their rallies Wednesday, while most 
smaller markets slid back after recent gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's blue chips reached a nearly nine-month high while Hong  
Kong's key index soared to its highest level in a year and 
Singapore shares rose to 17-month highs, amid signs that Japan's 
recession could be easing. Investors are betting that improved 
prospects for Japan could help end Asia's drawn-out economic 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is just gathering confidence on the part of  
overseas investors, that Asia has seen the worst, that economic 
recoveries are getting underway and that things are generally under 
control,'' said Howard Gorges, director of South China Brokerage 
Co. Ltd., in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's blue-chip Hang Seng Index soared 4.9 percent, or  
541.89 points, to close at 11,614.87, the highest since it finished 
at 11,735.50 points on March 27, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng had rallied 1.2 percent on Thursday, the last  
trading day before the market closed for Easter and the Chinese 
grave-sweeping Ching Ming Festival. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were catching up with recent strong gains on Wall  
Street and the rest of Asia after the long break, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	They were optimistic that China is close to securing its entry  
to the World Trade Organization. Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji, who 
started his long-awaited U.S. visit Tuesday, said there had been a 
breakthrough on ongoing negotiations with the United States on 
farming issues, which would remove a major obstacle. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does seem almost certain that China will become a member  
during this year, and that of course will be good news for Hong 
Kong and China,'' Gorges said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, shares rose for the third straight day.  
</P>
<P>
	The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average climbed 74.79 points, or 0.45  
percent, closing at 16,554.50 points, its highest finish since July 
21, when the average closed at 16,556.69. 
</P>
<P>
	The average has gained 264.31 points in three days, including  
Tuesday's 144.93-point gain. 
</P>
<P>
	Miyoshi Okano, manager of the equity department with Cosmo  
Securities, said continued buying by U.S. investment funds led the 
rally. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the U.S. dollar slipped against the  
Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In late trading, the dollar bought 120.78 yen, down 0.28 yen  
from late Tuesday in Tokyo but above its late New York level of 
120.62 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In Singapore, the Straits Times Index added another 1 percent,  
or 16.17 points, to close at 1,606.15. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark index, which is at a 17-month high, has soared 4.8  
percent in the past three days. 
</P>
<P>
	In Bangkok, Thailand, the key SET index jumped 8.79 points, or  
2.5 percent, to 359.52. 
</P>
<P>
	In South Korea, stock prices rallied for the sixth consecutive  
day, as market liquidity increased due to recent low interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kospi index gained 6.63 points, or 1 percent, to 673.36  
points. It had gained 12 percent in the past six days. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares fell, with little news to move the  
market. The JSX Composite Index fell 0.398 point, or 0.1 percent, 
to 395.911. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Stocks fell only slightly amid continued concerns  
over the health of Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, who is 
suffering from lung infection. The Composite index shed 0.06 
percent, or 0.36 point, to 556.57. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks rose on the release of favorable  
inflation data and expectations that the central bank may once 
again reduce banks' reserve requirements. The PSE index rose 26.81 
points, or 1.3 percent, to 2,070.17. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares fell, despite the continuing surge in  
market heavyweight News Corp. The All Ordinaries index closed at 
3,029.6, down 3.3 points, or 0.1 percent, from Tuesday's all-time 
high close of 3,032.9. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Taiwan shares fell in light volume, indicating investors  
are still waiting for more companies to release their March sales 
figures. The Weighted Price Index fell 28.10 points, or 0.39 
percent, to 7,135.89. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares fell, with the NZSE-40 capital  
index shed 1.4 percent, or 30.24 points, to 2,104.94. 

</P>
</TEXT>
