<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns Still Mulling No. 1 Pick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The long-awaited Ricky Williams workout  
answered a few questions for the Browns. But it failed to clear up 
the biggest one: Who to take with the No. 1 pick? 
</P>
<P>
	Williams turned Cleveland's draft pick derby into a three-way  
dead heat on Tuesday with an impressive private workout for the 
Browns and nearly every other NFL team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's now a three-man race,'' Cleveland coach Chris Palmer said  
after watching Williams get tested for two hours at the University 
of San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	The other players rated at the top of Cleveland's draft board  
are Oregon quarterback Akili Smith and Kentucky QB Tim Couch, 
who'll have a second chance to impress the Browns with another 
workout this Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	When Williams showed up 20 pounds overweight at the NFL scouting  
combines in February, there was speculation he might drop out of 
contention to be the first player selected in the April 17 draft. 
</P>
<P>
	But Williams dropped the weight -- he's at 224 -- and although his  
40-yard dash times Tuesday didn't drop any jaws, he has made the 
Browns' decision what to do with their No. 1 overall pick more 
difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer said the Browns are likely to use every second they're  
allotted before deciding what to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will go right into Saturday (April 17) morning,'' Palmer  
said, ``until minutes before the draft opens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams declined to work out at the combine in February, partly  
because he gained the weight on the banquet circuit after winning 
the Heisman Trophy following a record-setting senior season at 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	He clocked anywhere from a 4.6 to 4.72 on stopwatches running  
into the wind, and 4.4 to 4.52 wind-aided, Palmer said of Tuesday's 
workout. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, whom Palmer compared in body type to Earl Campbell,  
also bench pressed 225 pounds 22 times during the strength portion 
of his workout and showed he had good hands. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's anything he did in the workout that  
changed our mind on him one way or another,'' said Palmer. 
``Obviously, we thought he did excellent here. We're still in a 
toss-up as who will be the No. 1 pick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Palmer joked that if Williams' 40 time was in the 4.3  
range, he might as well be inducted into the Pro Football Hall of 
Fame now. 
</P>
<P>
	``He ran the way we expected him to after seeing him on film,''  
Palmer said. ``There is football speed and there is track speed. 
When you watch him on film, he runs away from people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And what about Canton?  
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's definitely a player who has a chance to go to  
Canton,'' Palmer said. ``And I think he's a player who's worthy of 
the first pick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the Browns' draft day dilemma is the possibility a  
team 
</P>
<P>
	wanting Williams or Couch or Smith bad enough, could make  
Cleveland a deal it can't refuse. 
</P>
<P>
	New Orleans coach Mike Ditka has already offered all his team's  
picks for the chance to move up and get Williams. Palmer spoke with 
Saints general manager Bill Kuharich at Williams' workout, and said 
he expects to hear from New Orleans again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
