<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'National Desk' Discusses Feminism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The latest edition of PBS' ``The National  
Desk,'' a series that brings a provocative conservatism to 
television, has women on its mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, is feminism dangerous to the well-being of boys?  
Do women in combat roles compromise the military? And has Title IX 
struck out as a way to level the athletic playing field for male 
and female students? 
</P>
<P>
	Let the shouting begin. The trio of ``National Desk'' programs  
is designed to foster debate with a blunt approach that, depending 
on one's perspective, can be invigorating, infuriating or both. 
</P>
<P>
	``The War on Boys,'' 9 p.m. EDT Friday, April 9 (check local PBS  
listings), opens the series. It is followed by ``Politics and 
Warriors: Women in the Military,'' Friday, April 16, and ``Title IX 
and Women in Sports: What's Wrong With This Picture,'' Friday, 
April 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Political commentator Fred Barnes is host of the first chapter,  
which suggests that a unisex society that refuses to distinguish 
between men and women creates an unhealthy atmosphere for children 
-- that is, boys. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to be taught that the distinction between the genders  
is not prejudice. It's not negative. It's not bad for them. It's 
just recognizing reality,'' says psychologist Diane Medved. 
</P>
<P>
	Boys are more aggressive and less emotionally open, according to  
experts quoted in the program. One cites toy company research in 
which children were brought in to play with a doll house and its 
contents. 
</P>
<P>
	The girls played nicely; the boys tucked a baby doll into its  
buggy and catapulted it from the roof of the house. That's nature, 
not nurture, according to ``The War on Boys.'' And messing with 
nature has severe consequences. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to subdue boys, they are overmedicated with drugs  
intended for attention deficit disorder. They are derided for 
naturally masculine behavior. And, worse yet, they are snubbed 
academically while girls are favored, the program argues. 
</P>
<P>
	The alleged villain in the piece is a 1992 study from the  
American Association of University Women that found that girls 
suffered from low self-esteem and were being shortchanged by the 
educational system, lagging behind boys in subjects such as math. 
</P>
<P>
	But it is boys, the program insists, who are truly at danger,  
suffering from high suicide rates and getting short shrift in 
schools designed for the learning habits of girls and controlled by 
women teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	(Conspicuously ignored by the program: equally worrisome  
behavioral problems among female adolescents, including anorexia 
and bulimia eating disorders.) 
</P>
<P>
	The next episode, ``Politics and Warriors,'' contends that our  
national defense is being weakened because women are getting 
military career opportunities for which they are physically 
unsuited. MSNBC's Laura Ingraham is the host. 
</P>
<P>
	``Common sense should tell us when we use the military as a  
laboratory of social engineering we risk compromising and 
undermining the readiness, cohesiveness, the very effectiveness of 
our armed forces,'' Ingraham says. 
</P>
<P>
	A climate of ``fem fear'' has been created among military  
leaders and others in government who bow to feminist demands to 
protect their jobs, claims Elaine Donnelly, president of the 
civilian Center for Military Readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	Is America dominated by self-serving women? The high-ranking  
female officers we hear from in the documentary seem to have no 
other agenda in mind than to serve their country as best they can. 
</P>
<P>
	It is unsettling to see footage of women soldiers struggling to  
complete basic training exercises and to consider how they would 
fare in a ground war. Whether a picture is worth a thousand words 
on this complex topic, however, is open to question. 
</P>
<P>
	The final hour, ``Title IX and Women in Sports,'' is helmed by  
broadcaster and columnist Larry Elder who, like Ingraham and 
Barnes, pulls no punches when it comes to the issue at hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Elder believes the civil rights legislation is well-meaning in  
spirit but rotten in execution. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Congress passed Title IX, which guaranteed equal  
opportunity for females in high school and college sports, the 
number of girls competing in high school sports has grown at least 
eightfold. Women now get about 37 percent of all athletic college 
scholarship money. 
</P>
<P>
	But athletic directors detail what seems to be a Catch-22  
situation: To give women more, they have to give men less. So 
Syracuse University moves to cut men's wrestling, the University of 
California at Los Angeles does the same with several programs and 
male students are unfairly penalized, say Title IX detractors. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonsense, respond female athletes and the law's supporters  
interviewed on the program. They argue that colleges can find a way 
to serve both men and women if they try, especially if they stop 
lavish overspending on high-profile football programs. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a real strength of ``National Desk.'' Although its hosts  
and many of its talking heads tend to line up on the right, the 
program does give ample time to those in disagreement. 
</P>
<P>
	For viewers and society, of course, the debate is wide open --  
and unending. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	HOORAY FOR HOLLYWOOD HOMES: We're invited when Home &AMP; Garden  
Television visits the homes of Hollywood insiders. Writer-producer 
Stephen J. Cannell opens up his 6-acre Pasadena estate and the 
unconventional style of ``Melrose Place'' set designer Deborah 
Siegel Cosentino's eight-room house is on display. There are three 
other stops on ``Hollywood Homes,'' which debuts 9 p.m. EDT Sunday, 
April 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org  
</P>
</TEXT>
