<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 22:22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bad Breadth / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Is bad breadth a sign of a more serious ailment?  
Wall Streeters are asking that question as gains in the popular 
averages are limited to fewer and fewer companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In popular thinking, the well-known averages such as the Dow  
Jones industrials and Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 reflect the market as a 
whole, but increasingly the evidence shows they don't. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the 15 largest stocks in the S&AMP;P 500 accounted for  
more than half the index's 28.57 percent gain. And the average New 
York Stock Exchange issue actually declined as the market rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Such evidence is sharply at odds with popular impressions that a  
new era of abundance has been reached for stocks as a whole. And it 
has created questions about some popular theories of investing. 
</P>
<P>
	One such question involves diversification, which is almost  
routinely recommended by theorists who otherwise have little in 
common. A diverse portfolio, it is said, provides protection. 
</P>
<P>
	The experience, however, is different. Of late, you'd have done  
better investing in a concentrated rather than diverse portfolio. 
</P>
<P>
	You might choose from a list of very large companies, or growth  
or technology companies, for example, and then only on a few rather 
than many. On some days, when averages rise, most stocks fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The narrowness of the market has also provoked doubts about the  
chances of small-capitalization stocks to keep pace. Despite 
optimistic forecasts, many good small stocks seem stuck in the 
doldrums. 
</P>
<P>
	Explanations for the lack of breadth are still tentative, and it  
is, of course, not beyond possibility that there could be a sudden 
or gradual shift to a more broadly based, less restrictive market. 
</P>
<P>
	For the time being, however, one reasonable theory is that large  
companies are more able than smaller companies to perform well in a 
competitive world economy -- able to earn profits by cutting costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Such an analysis, says economist Edward Yardeni of Deutsche Bank  
Securities, isn't a happy one for small companies. ``They don't 
have as much access to global markets,'' he says. ``They don't have 
resources to innovate and to leverage innovations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Preston Athey, manager of the T. Rowe Price Small-Cap Value  
Fund, disagrees. To believe that large-cap and Internet stocks are 
the only investments, he says, flies in the face of experience. 
</P>
<P>
	He concedes that ``what we have today are the lowest valuations  
for small-caps (relative to large caps) for as far back as we can 
go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he also believes that ``eventually, investors will have to  
look again at more nimble and innovative small companies to find 
rapid earnings growth or undiscovered bargains.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While that might be so, you have to wonder if those nimble small  
companies have enough shares outstanding to accept the huge buy and 
sell orders of large institutions, which dominate the market. 
</P>
<P>
	And if the institutions that move the market are limited by law  
to the amount of shares they can own in individual small companies, 
how will the small-caps rise? 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 10:45:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bruce, E Streeters Together Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For most of the world, it is THE tour of the  
year: Bruce Springsteen's much-anticipated reunion with his E 
Street Band, their first extended performances together in a 
decade. 
</P>
<P>
	For the 49-year-old Springsteen, whose ties with the band reach  
across three decades to afternoons playing Monopoly and nights 
playing long-lost Jersey clubs, the tour is more about the most 
important friendships of his life. 
</P>
<P>
	``How many people know people they knew in their teens, and in  
their late 40s they're still sharing that closeness?'' Springsteen 
asked recently, just after tour rehearsals began. ``It's unusual. 
... I knew Steven when I was 16, and I'll know him when we're 86. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're only at the halfway point.''  
</P>
<P>
	Steven is guitarist Steven Van Zandt, one of the Boss' old  
Asbury Park, N.J., cronies, a friend who opened his home to 
Springsteen 30 years ago when the Boss' parents moved to 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	Saxophonist Clarence Clemons, bassist Garry Tallent and  
keyboardist Danny Federici have known Springsteen roughly as long; 
they played the shore's bars and beach clubs with Springsteen 
before anybody west of the Garden State Parkway ever heard the E 
Street Band. 
</P>
<P>
	Drummer Max Weinberg and pianist Roy Bittan joined the band in  
time for 1975's ``Born to Run.'' The ``new'' members came aboard in 
1984: guitarist Nils Lofgren replaced Van Zandt, and singer Patti 
Scialfa -- now Springsteen's wife and mother of their three children 
-- was added as a backup singer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone wants to know how I feel about the band,''  
Springsteen said to an appreciative crowd at his Rock and Roll Hall 
of Fame induction. ``Hell, I married one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While a public 1989 divorce with the other E Streeters led to  
some hard feelings, time soon healed any rifts. 
</P>
<P>
	The band reassembled in 1995 to record four songs for a greatest  
hits package; a video capturing those sessions was also released. 
Later that year, they played the Hall of Fame concert in Cleveland, 
backing both Springsteen and Jerry Lee Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	When Springsteen called again four years later, the band quickly  
re-formed -- and their bandleader couldn't be happier. 
</P>
<P>
	``After all that time not playing together, to come back like  
this is a good thing,'' Springsteen said. ``Everybody's playing 
better than when they left. Everybody did different things during 
that time, and people came back with broader perspectives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were solo careers: Van Zandt, Clemons, Lofgren and  
Federici all released albums to varying degrees of success (none 
approaching Springsteen's success). Bittan did session work, and 
toured with Springsteen's new band in 1992-93. Tallent became a 
well-known Nashville record producer. 
</P>
<P>
	Television called, too: Weinberg was hired as the bandleader for  
``Late Night With Conan O'Brien,'' and Van Zandt recently made his 
acting debut as mobbed-up strip club owner Silvio Dante on HBO's 
acclaimed series ``The Sopranos.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But all will be on-stage when the tour officially kicks off  
April 9 in Barcelona, Spain. Why? Sure, there's a big payday. But 
there are other, more ethereal factors. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Marsh, in his 1979 Springsteen biography ``Born to Run,''  
wrote that ``the original Asbury Park musicians have bonds 
unfathomed -- and unbreakable -- by outsiders.'' That was 20 years 
ago, before the bonds grew tighter, before the friends shared 
weddings, christenings, worldwide success. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an unusual thing,'' Springsteen said of the band's ties.  
``It's hard to explain. It's a very small group that's shared some 
very, very intense experiences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first week of practice found the band picking up as if they  
had never put down their instruments. They ripped through 40 songs 
that first week; Van Zandt has said that he expects the band to 
know more than 150 songs when they hit the road. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure how many we'll learn,'' Springsteen said with a  
laugh. ``But I'm sure we'll play 'em all by the time we're done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springsteen said the band is playing songs ``from the whole body  
of my work,'' meaning concertgoers can expect to hear anything from 
``Spirit in the Night'' to electric versions of songs from ``The 
Ghost of Tom Joad.'' (A March rehearsal show in Asbury Park's 
Convention Hall included both.) 
</P>
<P>
	Springsteen's concerts have long been chock-full of surprises,  
from cover tunes (anything from Gary U.S. Bonds' ``Quarter to 
Three'' to Steppenwolf's ``Born to Be Wild'') to unreleased songs 
(the rehearsal included one titled ``Land of Hope and Dreams'') to 
extended jams (just about anything). 
</P>
<P>
	One thing that has pleased Springsteen about the reunion: His  
older music held up well in rehearsals. 
</P>
<P>
	``The music resonates,'' Springsteen says. ``It takes the years  
real well. It's exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The excitement continues across Europe -- including Munich,  
Zurich, London, Dublin and Paris -- before that leg wraps up in 
Madrid through at least early June, with the first U.S. dates in 
mid-July and the last near the end of September. 
</P>
<P>
	Although playing with the band is a major attraction,  
Springsteen has acknowledged that his decision to tour with the E 
Streeters is in part a response to clamoring from his loyal fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do what's interesting, what's best at the moment,''  
Springsteen said when his box set ``Tracks'' was released. ``But 
the audience factors in, sure. I've had a long ongoing dialogue 
with my audience, and a dialogue goes two ways. 
</P>
<P>
	``They talk to me, and I talk to them.''  
</P>
<P>
	For many Springsteen fans, their ties with the Boss go back a  
quarter-century, too -- almost as long as the band. This year, it's 
Springsteen's turn to talk. And his audience can't wait to listen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
