<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Customs To Study Search Complaints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Customs Commissioner Raymond Kelly plans to  
announce the creation of an independent review panel Thursday to 
evaluate complaints of racial bias by inspectors who search airline 
passengers for drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Customs Service is facing at least a dozen lawsuits  
over strip searches, including an effort by almost 100 black women 
to file a class-action suit in Chicago alleging they were singled 
out because of their race and gender. 
</P>
<P>
	Customs officers use strip searches, body cavity searches and  
X-rays to catch smugglers who hide cocaine or heroin inside their 
clothes or swallow packets of the drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Complaints and news reports about strip searches at Atlanta's  
Hartsfield International Airport led Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., to 
request a formal Treasury Department investigation of what he 
called ``a systematic and deliberate pattern of profiling African 
Americans'' and stopping them for searches. 
</P>
<P>
	Customs spokesman Dennis Murphy declined Wednesday to give  
details about the makeup of the commission, which Kelly planned to 
announce at a news conference Thursday with Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Murphy described the idea generally as, ``Let's get somebody to  
come in and look at our procedures to make sure what we are doing 
here is not biased.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only 50,000 of the 69 million international air travelers who  
passed through Customs in 1997 were subjected to some level of body 
search, most of them simple pat-downs, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixty percent of those subjected to body searches or X-rays were  
black or Hispanic, Customs statistics show. Drugs were found on 31 
percent of the blacks searched, 33 percent of Hispanics and 26 
percent of whites. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly, who took office last August, has already taken several  
steps to respond to complaints that body searches were too 
traumatic for passengers who are innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	They include requiring sensitivity training for inspectors,  
testing new body-imaging technology to replace some pat-down 
searches, and plans to add X-ray machines at airports so suspects 
won't have to be taken to hospitals in handcuffs for the procedure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
