<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Final Opener at Candlestick Point </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- It will be the final home opener for the  
Giants at their wind-swept ballpark at Candlestick Point, and the 
weather forecast is appropriate -- lots of rain is expected for 
Thursday's game against the San Diego Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	In the four decades since Vice President Richard Nixon presided  
over opening-day ceremonies for Candlestick Park in 1960 and 
proclaimed it ``the finest ballpark in America,'' the stadium built 
on landfill has caused nightmares for pitchers, hitters and -- 
especially -- fielders. 
</P>
<P>
	Popups turn into adventures. Pitchers have trouble keeping their  
fingers warm during summer day games. Hitters blast shots to left, 
only to see the wind turn them into fly balls to the center 
fielder. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your ball moves a ton out there and you can't judge the break  
on your breaking ball. It's hard to throw a strike,'' said Giants 
left-hander Shawn Estes, who is scheduled to start for San 
Francisco against San Diego's Stan Spencer -- who went to college at 
nearby Stanford. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been plenty of weird happenings at the ballpark,  
which will be replaced next year by Pacific Bell Park in downtown 
San Francisco: 
</P>
<P>
	-- A gust of wind blew Stu Miller off the mound during the 1961  
All-Star Game. 
</P>
<P>
	-- A game was delayed in 1964 after Los Angeles Dodgers center  
fielder Willie Davis lost a ball in the fog. 
</P>
<P>
	-- In 1993, a game against the Atlanta Braves was delayed for  
several minutes as a raccoon was chased off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	-- San Francisco's Bobby Murcer heated his bat in the clubhouse  
sauna before some plate appearances, and Pittsburgh coach George 
Sisler wrapped his legs with newspaper before putting on his 
uniform pants on one particularly cold night. 
</P>
<P>
	Opening day this year will feature former Giants slugger Orlando  
Cepeda, who was selected for the Hall of Fame last month, throwing 
out the ceremonial first pitch. The Giants are promoting it as the 
first day of a season-long ``Going Away Party'' for their old 
ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	The Giants come into the game having swept a three-game series  
in Cincinnati, winning each of the games by rallying in the eighth 
inning. On Wednesday, they scored seven runs in the eighth to win 
8-3 after being no-hit for six innings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
