<HEADLINE> Mazda, Mitsubishi May Ally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese automakers Mazda Motor Co. and Mitsubishi  
Motor Co. are discussing establishing a broad business and 
technological alliance, a newspaper reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks have already resulted in an agreement for Mazda to  
supply commercial vans to Mitsubishi, the Nihon Keizai business 
daily said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies released statements saying they had no comment on  
the report. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies plan to expand cooperation gradually with the  
possibility of involving Ford Motor Co., Mazda's largest 
shareholder, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nihon Keizai said that under the deal, Mitsubishi would halt  
production of commercial versions of its slumping Delica van model, 
and instead sell Mazda's Bongo vans under the Delica name. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies are considering the possibility of Mazda selling  
Mitsubishi minicars, thus replacing Suzuki Motor Corp. as its 
supplier of minicars, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies also are discussing an arrangement under which  
Mitsubishi would supply Mazda with its fuel-efficient engines and 
related technology, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
