<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dow Closes at New High: 10,085.31  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average soared in the  
last hour of trading today and hit a new high as investors, nervous 
about upcoming earnings reports, sought the relative safety of 
blue-chip stocks. The Dow was up 121.82 points at 10,085.31, its 
third close above 10,000. Broader stock indicators were mixed, 
reflecting the fact that investors are for the time being turning 
away from unpredictable technology stocks and moving their money to 
blue-chips that are seen as surer bets. The Nasdaq composite index, 
heavily weighted in technology issues, fell 18.81 to 2,544.36, and 
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 8.86 to 1,326.75. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,085.31 + 121.82
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1381  Declines 1600  Unchgd  567
NYSE Volume:         792,912,490
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online156      - 11 1/2
S&AMP;P 500:         1,326.75  + 8.86
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          717.30  +  2.09
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,544.36  - 18.81
Gold(final) -    $280.30    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.

</P>
<P>
	Alcoa Leads Blue Chip Rise  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened strongly today as aluminum maker  
Alcoa released first-quarter earnings that soundly beat analysts' 
expectations. Alcoa, a component of the Dow, was up 2 13/16 to 43 7/8 
for the day. AT&AMP;T, another Dow stock, was up 4 13/16 at 84 15/16. 
The financial sector was mostly higher as analysts said banks and 
brokerages have hinted they will report strong earnings when they 
begin releasing first-quarter results next week. Chase Manhattan 
rose 5 1/8 to 84 3/8, and Merrill Lynch rose 5 1/8 to 96 1/4. A strong sales 
report from Ford Motor sent its shares up 2 1/2 to 60 3/4. Software maker 
Novell, meanwhile, slipped 1 1/8 to 22 15/16, and Sun Microsystems 
fell 1 7/8 to 138 3/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Business Paper To Debut  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Wall Street Journal, The Financial Times of  
London and the Moscow Times announced plans today to launch a 
Russian-language business newspaper for the Russian market. The 
yet-to-be-named publication is to debut in August, publishing 
Tuesday through Saturday. A staff of 20 Russian reporters and 
editors will staff the newspaper, which also will draw content, 
translated into Russian, from The Financial Times and The Wall 
Street Journal. The newspaper will be owned one-third each by Dow 
Jones &AMP; Company, publisher of The Wall Street Journal; Pearson PLC, 
publisher of The Financial Times; and Independent Media, publisher 
of The Moscow Times and the Russian editions of Cosmopolitan, Good 
Housekeeping, and Men's Health magazines. 

</P>
<P>
	Engineering Animation's Stock Drops  
</P>
<P>
	AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Shares of Engineering Animation Inc. plunged  
today after the company projected lower-than-expected profits and 
revenue for the first quarter. The producer of software for 
three-dimentional designing and animation cited a failure to close 
a half dozen contracts with large North American companies. Its 
stock was down 18 1/4, or 45.7 percent, at 21 11/16 on the Nasdaq 
Stock Market following the earnings warning last evening and an 
apologetic conference call today with analysts, investors and 
reporters. 

</P>
<P>
	American, Pilots Resume Talks  
</P>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- AMR Corp., parent company to American  
Airlines, resumed mediated talks with the carrier's pilots union to 
work on resolving a dispute over the acquisition of Reno Air. At 
issue is the integration of Reno into American and when Reno's 
pilots will be upgraded to American's pay levels. In February, 
about 6,600 flights were canceled over a 10-day stretch as 
thousands of American pilots, frustrated with the talks, called in 
sick. 

</P>
<P>
	EU To Comply With WTO Banana Ruling  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union said today it will  
abide by the decision of the World Trade Organization supporting 
U.S. claims that EU banana import rules violate WTO regulations. 
The WTO yesterday authorized the United States to impose $191 
million in 100 percent tariffs on European goods -- anything from 
sweaters to handbags and coffee makers. The amount of tariffs 
authorized was one-third of the U.S. demand of $520 million. The 
United States will be able to choose from a list of products that 
will get the tariffs. During the six-year battle, the United States 
has contended that EU rules unfairly discriminate against bananas 
grown by U.S. companies to favor bananas grown by former European 
colonies. 

</P>
<P>
	DuPont Allies With Health Web Site  
</P>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- DuPont Co. is entering an alliance with  
WebMD Inc., an Internet site, as part of its plan to improve its 
life sciences business, the company announced today. WebMD will 
make DuPont the exclusive provider of information on its 
subscription physician service and free consumer site about 
prescription drugs, over-the-counter medicines, nutritional 
supplements and medical foods. WebMD was started in October and 
offers Internet services for physicians, including a medical 
library, insurance verification and referral authorizations. 

</P>
<P>
	China Telecom Broken Up Into 4 Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China is breaking up the government's  
telecommunications monopoly into four specialized companies, a move 
that comes as U.S. and Chinese negotiators hold down-to-the-wire 
talks on China's bid to join the World Trade Organization. The 
long-awaited decision on the dismemberment of China Telecom would 
potentially open up a $28 billion market to foreign competition. 
China Telecom's tight grip on 95 percent of that market has been a 
major stumbling block in the WTO negotiations. Before setting out 
on his current U.S. visit, Premier Zhu Rongji reportedly said China 
would allow foreigners to take up to 30 percent stakes in 
telecommunications companies. 

</P>
<P>
	Alcoa Reports Modest Income Growth  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Alcoa's earnings rose 5 percent for the first  
quarter, partly due to acquisitions and production efficiencies 
that offset falling aluminum prices. The results reported today 
beat Wall Street expectations. The world's biggest aluminum 
producer earned $221.1 million, or 60 cents a share, in the first 
three months of 1999 compared to $209.9 million, or 62 cents a 
share, a year ago. The per-share income declined because Alcoa 
increased the number of its common shares outstanding by 31 million 
to 367 million shares with its purchase of Alumax last July. 

</P>
<P>
	GM's US Sales Down; Others Higher  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. blamed a lean inventory of  
its hottest-selling vehicle, the full-size Chevrolet Silverado 
pickup, for a March sales performance that lagged behind most of 
its competitors. GM said its U.S. sales were off 2 percent from a 
year ago -- lower than analysts had expected. While GM's car sales 
increased 1 percent, sales of light trucks were off 6 percent 
compared with the robust truck sales of March 1998. In the past 
week, Ford Motor Co. reported its March U.S. sales were up 14 
percent and DaimlerChrysler AG said its Chrysler unit posted a 17 
percent improvement. Most major foreign automakers also reported 
strong gains. 

</P>
<P>
	British Airways To Fly to Libya  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British Airways plans to start flying to Libya now  
that the United Nations has suspended sanctions against that 
country, which on Monday handed over two Libyans suspected of 
blowing up a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988. The 
flights between London and Tripoli, the Libyan capital, are to 
begin later this month. 

</P>
<P>
	Prince Andrew Starts Web Site 'Zine  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Want a peek at the royal art collection? Need to  
ask the queen a quick question? Check out Prince Andrew's new 'zine 
on the royal Web site. The prince launched Royal Insight on 
Wednesday from a cyber-cafe near Buckingham Palace. In contrast to 
the main site, which includes mostly reference material, Royal 
Insight will focus on the day-to-day activities of the royal 
family, with an emphasis on photographs. 

</P>
