<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BNP To Continue Bank Takeover Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Banque Nationale de Paris said Wednesday it would  
press ahead with a takeover bid for French banks Paribas and 
Societe Generale, despite their clear opposition to the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``The project is too important to give up now,'' BNP Chief  
Executive Michel Pebereau told Europe-1 radio. 
</P>
<P>
	The boards of Societe Generale and Paribas voted Tuesday to  
reject the BNP takeover bid, reiterating their confidence in plans 
for their own merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale said the premium offered by BNP would ``either  
be very small, or even negative,'' making it unattractive for 
Societe Generale shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale and Paribas were completing a $17.2 billion  
friendly merger of their own when BNP stunned the European 
financial world March 9 with an unsolicited $37 billion takeover 
bid for both banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-way merger put forward by BNP would create a $1  
trillion, world-leading banking group. It comes as European banks 
are joining forces to better compete in a market transformed by the 
region's new common currency, the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Societe Generale and Parabas say they prefer to pursue  
their own two-way merger -- SG Paribas -- which they believe has 
greater shareholder value. 
</P>
<P>
	Pebereau said Wednesday that BNP's three-way merger would bring  
benefits ``for workers, customers and shareholders.'' He said the 
matter might not be resolved for another three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
