<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Pounded by NATO Bombs  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav television says six  
missiles have struck a town south of Belgrade early Thursday as 
NATO continues its bombing campaign. Large explosions are also 
reported in an industrial town north of the capital. In Belgrade 
itself, two loud blasts shook the city's center. A nearby resident 
says an army building was hit. Meanwhile, Yugoslav authorities have 
sealed off Kosovo's main border crossings, preventing ethnic 
Albanians from leaving as the wave of refugees approached the 
half-million mark. 

</P>
<P>
	Cypriot Seeks Release of US Servicemen  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. officials indicated that NATO bombing of  
Belgrade would cease long enough Thursday to allow a Cypriot leader 
to fly in with the hope of bringing back the three U.S. soldiers 
held by Yugoslavia. Earlier, a pentagon spokesman said NATO would 
not stop its current operations because of the effort by Cypriot 
parliament leader Spyros Kyprianou to gain the release of the 
servicemen. But he said, ``We have total control of the operations 
and certainly if it's necessary to have an aircraft fly into an 
area or out of an area at any time, that could be arranged.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Pushes Equal Pay for Women  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton renewed his call Wednesday  
for equal pay for working women, saying the country has ``the 
opportunity of a generation'' to correct the inequity during good 
economic times. Clinton said Congress should take advantage of the 
nation's low unemployment and booming economy and pass the Paycheck 
Fairness Act introduced last month. The president's Council of 
Economic Advisers reported last year that women earn about 75 cents 
for every dollar a man earns, a narrower gap than in 1963, when 
President Kennedy signed the original Equal Pay Act. Then, women 
workers earned 58 cents for every dollar paid to male workers. 

</P>
<P>
	McDougal Closing Arguments Heard  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The trial of President Clinton's former  
business partner, Susan McDougal, neared its close Wednesday with 
her lawyer comparing Kenneth Starr's tactics to the Third Reich. 
Jury deliberations were expected to begin Thursday. Throughout the 
five-week trial, McDougal's defense has been based on attacking the 
independent counsel's office. McDougal, charged with twice refusing 
to answer questions before a federal grand jury, testified that she 
feared prosecutors would charge her with perjury if she told the 
truth and did not implicate the Clintons. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Premier, Clinton To Meet  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji was meeting  
President Clinton Wednesday night in the White House residence for 
an informal chat. Zhu arrived here Wednesday for two days of talks 
on security issues, trade, Taiwan and other subjects. He is 
expected to register China's differences with the United States on 
NATO's air war in Yugoslavia. Zhu also hopes to close a deal with 
the Clinton administration to allow Beijing to join the World Trade 
Organization. 

</P>
<P>
	LA Mayor: Our Schools Have Failed  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mayor Richard Riordan declared the nation's  
second-largest public school system a ``total failure'' and blamed 
its leadership Wednesday, a week before an important school board 
election. ``Two out of three kids cannot read at grade level by the 
end of third grade,'' the mayor said in his annual 
state-of-the-city address. The mayor faulted the board of the Los 
Angeles Unified School District for stressing ``feel-good'' 
subjects over basic math and reading skills. 

</P>
<P>
	China Telephone Market May Open Up  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China announced the breakup Wednesday of the  
government's telecommunications monopoly into four specialized 
companies, a move that comes as U.S. and Chinese negotiators hold 
down-to-the-wire talks on China's bid to join the World Trade 
Organization. The long-awaited decision on the dismemberment of 
China Telecom would potentially open up a $28 billion market to 
foreign competition. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Open Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks opened mixed on Thursday. The  
Nikkei Stock Average fell 2 points to 16,552.50 early on. In New 
York Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 121.82 points 
to close at 10,085.31. That eclipsed the previous high of 10,007.33 
hit Monday. 

</P>
<P>
	Suns Snap Timberwolves' Win Streak  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Cliff Robinson had 27 points, five steals and  
five blocked shots Wednesday night as the Phoenix Suns survived a 
cold-shooting second half to hold off Minnesota 90-82, snapping the 
Timberwolves' four-game winning streak. Robinson, who had 19 points 
in the first half, also guarded Kevin Garnett all night. Garnett 
scored 19 points, but only two in the fourth quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
