<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Program Calculates Mutual Fund Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- How much will a 1 percent annual fee reduce  
the final account balance in a mutual fund investment over a 
20-year period? 
</P>
<P>
	A new computer program developed by federal regulators will help  
mutual fund investors find the answer. (It's 18 percent). 
</P>
<P>
	The Securities and Exchange Commission, led by Chairman Arthur  
Levitt, has been pushing the mutual fund industry for improved 
disclosure of fund fees and investment risks. 
</P>
<P>
	The program unveiled Tuesday ``takes some of the mystery out of  
mutual funds by enabling investors to evaluate and compare costs,'' 
Levitt said at a news conference. ``And it lets investors see how 
costs add up in dollars and cents over time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The mutual fund cost calculator will allow investors to examine  
the costs of funds and compare different funds, much like unit 
pricing helps shoppers compare prices of different sizes of cereal 
boxes on supermarket shelves. 
</P>
<P>
	The calculator is available on the SEC's Web site at www.sec.gov  
and through the Web site of the Investment Company Institute, the 
mutual fund industry's trade group, at www.ici.org. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt said he hoped the new program ``will spur the fund  
industry ... to come up with better ways to explain fund costs to 
investors and better tools to help investors compare fund costs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Investment Company Institute called the calculator ``a  
valuable new resource to help investors understand how fees and 
expenses affect their investments and returns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some 77 million Americans now invest in mutual funds, whose  
total assets exceeded $5.5 trillion at the end of last year, up 
from around $1 trillion in 1990. The earnings are often counted on 
for retirement, meeting college bills or other major expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the SEC's research shows that less than half of mutual fund  
investors know that expenses are deducted on an ongoing basis. Only 
8 percent of the investors surveyed said they completely understand 
the fees charged by their funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutual fund prospectuses include tables showing the fees and  
expenses of each fund. But investors haven't been able to use the 
information effectively, the regulators say. 
</P>
<P>
	The new calculator is designed to answer questions such as: I  
plan to retire in 20 years. Am I better off buying a no-load fund 
with annual expenses of 1.5 percent or a fund with a front-end 
sales charge of 3.5 percent and annual expenses of 0.9 percent? And 
what if I decide to retire in 15 years rather than 20? 
</P>
<P>
	No-load funds do not charge sales commissions and keep other  
fees low, but they do charge some fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The calculator ``sounds like a Godsend for investors who are  
pulling their hair out trying to calculate all these costs,'' said 
Marc Beauchamp, spokesman for the North American Securities 
Administrators Association, which represents state securities 
regulators. ``They shouldn't need to know advanced math to figure 
out their mutual fund costs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC advised investors that fees are not the only factor they  
should consider when choosing a mutual fund. After reading the 
prospectus document and the fund's annual report, the agency said, 
investors also should assess: 
</P>
<P>
	--The number of years needed to reach an investment goal.  
</P>
<P>
	--The types of stocks, bonds or other securities that the fund  
buys. 
</P>
<P>
	--The investment risks of the fund.  
</P>
<P>
	--The fit between the fund and their other investments.  
</P>
<P>
	--The fund company or portfolio manager who runs the fund.  
</P>
<P>
	--The fund's performance record.  
</P>
<P>
	--The types of services offered by the fund company.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
