<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tonight's Big Game Is Worth $190M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Lottery players have heard it before: A 747 is  
more likely to land on your head as aliens raid your fridge than 
the Big Game is to dump millions in your bank account. 
</P>
<P>
	``So what?'' is the common cash register rejoinder.  
</P>
<P>
	Lotteries are about daydreaming, not probability, and plenty of  
people were contemplating the $190 million Big Game jackpot to be 
drawn Tuesday night, despite the 76.3 million-to-1 odds against 
winning it. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has claimed the jackpot since Feb. 2, meaning that plenty  
of folks are dropping lots of cash for a chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Lottery officials in the six Big Game states -- Georgia,  
Illinois, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan and Virginia -- were to 
determine whether to increase the jackpot again, said Maryland 
Lottery Director Buddy Roogow. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in uncharted territory here so it's difficult for us to  
be absolutely certain of what the jackpot will be,'' said Rebecca 
Paul, president of the Georgia Lottery Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	In Georgia, the state that sells the most Big Game tickets,  
players forked over $317,391 from 1 p.m. to 2 p.m. Monday, more 
than double the $120,695 spent in the same period a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	In the seven days ending at midnight Saturday, the Georgia  
Lottery saw its best sales week -- $72 million, $20 million more 
than the previous record in June 1993, the lottery's first week. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland retailers were zipping through 45 lottery transactions  
per second at one point Monday morning, with an average sale of 
$2.50, Roogow said. 
</P>
<P>
	None of this entertainment-by-numbers impresses mathematicians,  
who say that most people don't really understand the enormity of 
lottery odds and probably wouldn't play if they did. 
</P>
<P>
	``People seem to be oblivious to obvious risk,'' grumbles John  
Allen Paulos, a prominent Temple University mathematics professor 
and author of five books that examine numbers from a lay person's 
perspective. 
</P>
<P>
	Non-gamblers like Paulos have honed the litany of all the bad  
stuff more likely to befall you than lottery millions, such as 
lightning strikes, heart attacks, plane crashes, meteorites and 
falling trees. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have a better chance of going to the moon'' than winning,  
said Tyler Jarvis, an assistant math professor at Brigham Young 
University who was provoked to write ``Gambling: What are the 
Odds?'' two years ago at Mississippi State when his undergraduate 
math students became enamored of casino gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	``By any normal human standards, the odds are zero,'' Jarvis  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Janusz Mrozek, an assistant economics professor at Georgia Tech,  
said he ``invests'' $5 to $10 in the Big Game if the cash payout -- 
about $100 million for today's drawing -- equals the odds of 
winning. 
</P>
<P>
	But like all the other academics, Mrozek said the huge odds  
render his practical chances of winning zero. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really like to play, in a sense, unless the payout is  
in some psychologic sense comparable to the odds,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But huge jackpots have their own special lure, Mrozek said, and  
Paulos conceded that spending a buck in the lottery might provide a 
``dollar of anticipation'' if nothing else. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
