<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 05:45:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S&AMP;L Figure Sued by Mother </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A former savings and loan president who served  
nearly eight years in prison for stealing millions from the thrift 
before it collapsed is in trouble again -- this time accused of 
fraud by his 87-year-old mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland authorities have begun an investigation into Nettie  
Levitt-Gilbert's claims, filed in a Florida court, that her son, 
Jeffrey A. Levitt, used her credit cards to bamboozle her in a 
stock scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	If Mrs. Levitt-Gilbert's claims are true, they could constitute  
a violation of her son's parole. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt was released from prison in 1993 after serving almost  
eight years of a 30-year sentence for embezzling $14.6 million from 
his thrift, Old Court Savings &AMP; Loan. Old Court collapsed in May 
1985, touching off a crisis in the then-privately insured Maryland 
thrift industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he's convicted of credit card fraud, there is a possibility  
of his return to Maryland to finish his sentence,'' said Leonard A. 
Sipes Jr. of the state Division of Correction. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt, 56, who now works as a cigar salesman in Boynton Beach,  
Fla., denied his mother's allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I swear to God I didn't do anything illegal,'' he said in  
today's editions of The (Baltimore) Sun. ``I wouldn't steal a 
nickel from my mother.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His attorney, Jonathan Bloom, called the allegations ridiculous.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a stupid lawsuit, and we're going to win,'' Bloom said.  
``The case is in my joke file.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
