<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Exchange Index Climbs / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's benchmark stock index climbed to its  
highest level in nearly nine months today, spurred by continued 
buying by foreign investors. The U.S. dollar fell against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.78 yen at late afternoon, down 0.28 yen  
from late Tuesday in Tokyo but above its late New York level of 
120.62 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 74.79 points, or 0.45  
percent, closing at 16,554.50 points, its highest close since July 
21, when the average closed at 16,556.69. The average has now 
gained for the third straight day, fetching 264.31 points in three 
days, including Tuesday's 144.93-point gain, or 0.89 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei average moved into positive territory toward the  
closing bell with gains in high technology issues, including Sony 
and Toshiba. 
</P>
<P>
	Miyoshi Okano, manager of the equity department with Cosmo  
Securities, said continued buying by U.S. investment funds led the 
way as they considered Japanese stocks still priced relatively low, 
compared to their U.S. and European counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 709  
million shares, up from Tuesday's 568 million shares. Advancers 
outnumbered declines 762 to 466, with 98 issues unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 2.03 points, or 0.15 percent, to 1,324.64. The 
TOPIX closed up 15.44 points, or 1.18 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar slipped against the yen after  
the euro strengthened as Yugoslavia announced a unilateral 
cease-fire in its battle against Kosovo rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslav action was rejected by Western leaders, who said  
the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia would continue. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar, often regarded as a haven in times of international  
unrest, had been rising against the euro since the bombing began on 
March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	In today's trading, the dollar ranged between 120.43 yen and  
121.20 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo trading, the euro bought $1.0775, up from its late  
Tuesday rate in Tokyo of $1.0715. The euro also bought 130.20 yen, 
up from 130.19 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 211 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.675 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.795 percent, 
driving its price up to 101.08 yen from 100.04 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
