<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Gallery Gets Sculpture Garden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It's designed to be a quiet, shady place where  
tourists can relax and enjoy art. But visitors to the new sculpture 
garden of the National Gallery of Art may find the only vacant 
bench next to a 24-foot spider. 
</P>
<P>
	Not to worry, says the gallery: The spider is a ``looming and  
powerful protectress, who is also nurturing and vulnerable.'' The 
spider is cast in bronze, the work of 87-year-old French-American 
sculptor Louise Bourgeois. 
</P>
<P>
	The new tree-shaded garden -- a dream 33 years in the making -- is  
due to open May 23, joining the string of parks, museums and 
memorials along the big, grassy Mall in the center of the nation's 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	The new sculpture garden sits just across a street from the  
gallery's old West Building, directly across the Mall from the 
sculpture garden of the Hirshhorn Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hirshhorn specializes in modern art but has more familiar  
statues of human forms in its sculpture garden, while the National 
Gallery's garden has opted for some more-recent and astonishing 
pieces. 
</P>
<P>
	The new 6.1-acre space was reserved for a garden long ago, but  
continually hit snags along the way. Flowered walks with ample 
benches have been laid out by Philadelphia landscape artist Laurie 
Olin around a circular pool. There are 314 new shrubs and trees, 
some 35 feet high. 
</P>
<P>
	In winter, the pool will continue to be an ice-skating rink. A  
new, upgraded cafe and restaurant will have tables both indoors and 
outdoors beginning this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The skating rink was put in first, but then someone thought it  
wasn't dignified to combine art with a skating rink, and we 
couldn't get money from Congress to do the garden,'' said J. Carter 
Brown, chairman of Washington's Fine Arts Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the director of the National Gallery, Earl A. Powell III,  
has received permission from the Morris and Gwendolyn Cafritz 
Foundation to use $10 million from its grants to develop the 
garden. The foundation is also buying seven of the 10 new 
sculptures that will stand with nearly a dozen others from the 
gallery's collection among the trees, shrubs and flowers. 
</P>
<P>
	Upkeep will be covered by the gallery's regular appropriation  
from Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown predicted that a shaded, comfortable space will attract  
sun-weary tourists in summer and tired skaters in winter, 
introducing them to a kind of art they may never have seen. 
</P>
<P>
	Less ominous than the spider but almost as big will be a  
brand-new statue, a 19-foot ``Typewriter Eraser, Class X.'' It's by 
Claes Oldenburg, a Swedish-born American who thinks big, and his 
wife, Cooje van Bruggen, an American born in the Netherlands. In 
the days before computers, typists used an eraser a few inches long 
to correct errors. The Oldenburgs are known for gigantic figures of 
ordinary objects, such as lipsticks and hamburgers. 
</P>
<P>
	More conventional and poignant will be 30 3-foot bronzes called  
``Puellae'' (Girls) by Polish artist Magdalena Abakanowicz. They 
refer to a story she heard from World War II, about a group of 
children found frozen to death in cattle cars as they were being 
brought to Germany from Poland. 
</P>
<P>
	The gallery's indoor collection will contribute a red horse made  
of painted sheet metal by American engineer-sculptor Alexander 
Calder, who invented the mobile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
