<DOCNO> APW19990407.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 06:06:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Chinese Premier Begins U.S. Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Anticipating his trip would be diplomatically  
sticky, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji sought pointers from the U.S. 
ambassador to China before leaving on his tour of the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he got this advice from Ambassador James R. Sasser: ``In  
such an adverse situation `always keep a smiling face.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu, the first Chinese premier to visit the United States in 15  
years, appeared to be heeding that suggestion on the first day of 
his nine-day, six-city tour, mixing humor with serious issues in 
speeches in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	In a reference to recent allegations that China spied on the  
United States and stole nuclear weapons technology, he offered this 
warning to anyone visiting his country: ``Please remember when you 
return to China, don't bring any materials so you can avoid being 
investigated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that he had been asked how the 50th anniversary of the  
People's Republic of China would be celebrated, Zhu also said that 
his country might consider parading its military equipment with 
signs saying ``Made in China and Developed with Chinese 
Technology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a banquet Tuesday night, Zhu assured the mostly  
Chinese-American audience that the trade deficit, human rights 
violations and other controversial issues won't strain U.S.-China 
relations. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the questions and problems between China and the United  
States ... are no more than an episode in the longer history of the 
friendly relations and the cooperation between China and the United 
States,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, his arrival was met with vocal  
demonstrations by 50 people advocating a free Tibet and an 
independent Taiwan. 
</P>
<P>
	Protesters waved banners and chanted ``Free Tibet before free  
trade'' in the rain outside the Century Plaza Hotel, where Zhu 
addressed a luncheon hosted by Mayor Richard Riordan. 
</P>
<P>
	The 70-year-old premier, speaking through a translator, said  
California Gov. Gray Davis raised the issue of human rights, but 
that they did not have time for adequate discussion. Davis' office 
said they met for 25 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu also said the United States and China reached a key  
agreement on agricultural trade, but U.S. Special Trade 
Representative Peter Scher in Washington said no deal had been 
reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu said China agreed to lift bans on citrus from four U.S.  
states and wheat from seven states, a deal that could boost China's 
effort to gain U.S. support for membership in the World Trade 
Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu was scheduled to leave Los Angeles today to continue his  
nine-day visit that includes stops in Washington, Denver, Chicago, 
New York and Boston. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
