<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Ernest Shackleton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- When explorer Sir Ernest Shackleton and his  
crew returned to England after spending nearly two years stranded 
on the Antarctic seas, there was little fanfare. 
</P>
<P>
	It was 1917, and Shackleton and his crew had failed to do what  
they set out to do -- cross the Antarctic continent on foot. World 
War I had broken out the week Shackleton left England, and people 
were too busy mourning their dead to care about his story of 
enduring hardship. There were no heroes other than war heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, eight decades later, writer Caroline Alexander tells  
Shackleton's story in ``The Endurance,'' a book named after his 
ship, using diaries and interviews with family members to tell the 
tale of the 28 men who spent 20 months on an ice floe and were 
stuck on a barren island, their trans-Antartica hike doomed. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander also is curator of an exhibit on the ordeal at the  
American Museum of Natural History in New York City beginning April 
10, and is working on a documentary film for NOVA and Boston's 
WGBH-TV. 
</P>
<P>
	Shackleton's expedition began in 1914. He saw his trip as the  
last great polar exploration because other men already had reached 
both poles. He named his ship Endurance after his family motto, 
``By endurance we conquer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ship and crew were supposed to drop off a shore party of  
officers and scientists and return after the winter to pick them up 
on the other side of Antarctica. Instead, the Endurance became an 
icebound home to all 28 men, 69 sled dogs and the ship's mascot, a 
cat they called Mrs. Chippy. 
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 24, 1915, only a day's journey from its destination, the  
ship became stuck in ice. It was too far from civilization to 
establish radio contact, even with remote whaling stations in the 
South Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander tells how the men made the best of it by building new  
living quarters in the warm parts of the ship and sharing the shore 
party's provisions. They used melted ice for tea, cocoa and 
washing. They walked and exercised the dogs on the thick ice, which 
gradually moved the ship hundreds of miles away from its 
destination. They entertained themselves with songs and skits and 
by playing with the dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	The men survived for almost a year as the ever-shifting ice pack  
slowly crushed the ship's hull, and with it, hopes for the 
expedition. 
</P>
<P>
	The groaning ice began to tighten around the hull in April,  
making it vibrate. In midwinter the plates of ice grinding together 
sounded like distant artillery. The pressure piled huge blocks of 
ice on top of one another. 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of July, men stood watch at night in case the ship  
had to be abandoned quickly. Blizzards tossed the Endurance back 
and forth in its icy trap. The temperature fell to minus 24 
degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``What the ice gets, the ice keeps,'' Capt. Frank Worsely quoted  
Shackleton as saying to him. 
</P>
<P>
	In October, the temperature rose to nearly 30 degrees and the  
ship broke free of the ice. But after drifting only about 100 yards 
it became stuck again. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he discovered that the ice had wrenched the stern post and  
the ship was leaking. Men on board pumped for hours, while men on 
the ice dug trenches to ease the pressure. Then they heard rushing 
water and the gunlike popping of beams cracking. On Oct. 26, 
Shackleton ordered them to abandon ship. 
</P>
<P>
	The men planned to walk with lifeboats until they found open  
water to launch them, But made less than a mile a day in the minus 
15 degree cold. Finally, they backtracked and set up camp close to 
the ship. 
</P>
<P>
	On Nov. 21, as the temperatures rose, the crumpled hull of the  
Endurance went down, bow first. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a queer silence over the camp,'' one man wrote in  
his diary. ``As for me, there was an odd lump in my throat and I 
found it hard to swallow. We were now very lonely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The men had salvaged more than 3 tons of provisions. They drank  
tea and ate pieces of dough called ``bannocks'' with penguin and 
seal meat. They used the blubber and skin for fuel when their 
gasoline ran out. The hunted, told stories, kept diaries. 
</P>
<P>
	As the temperatures rose, the men finally found enough open  
water to launch their lifeboats. They sailed for more than 36 
sleepless hours, battling storms, cold, exhaustion, frostbite and 
madness. They landed on barren Elephant Island, home only to 
penguins. From there, Shackleton and a small crew sailed a lifeboat 
800 miles to a Norwegian whaling station in the South Atlantic. 
After months of searching for a suitable boat, a Chilean tugboat 
returned to rescue the rest of his men. 
</P>
<P>
	Shackleton telegraphed long stories of his journey to the Daily  
Chronicle in London. But with the war raging, the story was largely 
ignored. 
</P>
<P>
	``People were just not interested in self-imposed disasters when  
millions of young men in Europe were being destroyed in the 
trenches,'' Alexander explained in an interview from her farm on 
Squam Lake in New Hampshire. Moreover, Shackleton's voyage was 
overshadowed by explorer Robert Falcon Scott's race to the South 
Pole years earlier. Shackleton had worked for Scott on an earlier 
expedition and hated it, vowing never to work under him again. 
Scott and his party reached the pole, only to find that Norwegian 
Roald Amundsen had beaten them there. Scott and his men died of 
hunger on their return journey. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander uses stark photos taken by Australian photographer  
James Francis Hurley to tell the story of the Endurance. 
</P>
<P>
	The diaries on which she draws give readers a glimpse of the  
relationships among the men and with their animals, and their 
ingenuity in battling hunger, frostbite, disease and mental 
illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, 42, was born in Gainesville, Fla., to English  
parents. She has lived in the Netherlands, Africa, Italy, the West 
Indies and England, where she went to college. She has a doctorate 
in classics from Columbia University. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Endurance,'' her fourth book, was first written from the  
viewpoint of Mrs. Chippy, the cat. But when she came across 
photographer Hurley's spectacular pictures, she decided to start 
anew from the men's point of view. 
</P>
<P>
	She was especially struck by their strong affection for their  
animals, expressed in countless diary entries, photos and even 
sketches. Once home, the men told of being devastated when they had 
to shoot the dogs and Mrs. Chippy for food and lack of space in the 
lifeboats. 
</P>
<P>
	In particular, she praised Shackleton's leadership and  
indomitable optimism. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ultimately, it's his story. It's his leadership that made this  
possible,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have done it,'' Shackleton wrote to his wife. ``Not a life  
lost and we have been through Hell.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
