<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Warns of Icy China Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- His China policy under attack, President  
Clinton warned Wednesday that a souring of relations resulting from 
a ``campaign-driven cold war'' with China could erase the gains 
that he claimed for his policy of engagement with Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton commented in an address on China policy before Chinese  
Premier Zhu Rongji arrived here for two days of talks on security 
issues, trade, Taiwan and other subjects. 
</P>
<P>
	In advance of Zhu's arrival, some Republicans have been seizing  
on alleged nuclear spying by China at secret U.S. facilities as 
well as fresh charges that the chief of China's military 
intelligence directed $300,000 to Clinton's re-election campaign in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the next presidential election approaches, we cannot allow  
a healthy argument to lead us toward a campaign-driven cold war 
with China, for that would have tragic consequences,'' Clinton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them, he said, would be ``an end to diplomatic contacts  
that have produced tangible gains for our people, a climate of 
mistrust that hurts Chinese-Americans and undermines the exchanges 
that are opening China to the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only beneficiaries, he added, would be ``the most rigid  
backward-looking elements in China itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu, whose six-city U.S. tour began Tuesday in Los Angeles, has  
acknowledged that serious differences could arise in his visit. 
</P>
<P>
	Describing himself in a pre-departure Wall Street Journal  
interview as ``an ordinary Chinese with a bad temper,'' Zhu said, 
``When I go to the U.S., it's very possible I'll have arguments 
with you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is expected to register China's differences with the United  
States on NATO's air war in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	One unresolved issue is China's bid to join the World Trade  
Organization, which would open China's vast markets to American 
exports. U.S. and Chinese negotiators have spent long hours this 
week attempting to work out the final details in time for Zhu's 
visit. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said Wednesday he  
opposes U.S. attempts to help China join the WTO. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rewarding China with WTO membership shows how desperate this  
administration is for an agreement -- any agreement -- during the 
visit of China's prime minister,'' Lott said. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials declined to discuss the substance of the  
allegations concerning campaign finance and nuclear spying, citing 
ongoing investigations of both issues. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the House Government  
Reform and Oversight Committee, called on Clinton to insist China 
provide U.S. investigators bank records that ``would demonstrate 
the origins of the millions of dollars that flowed'' from China to 
the Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said American engagement with Beijing has yielded  
security benefits for the United States on a range of foreign 
policy hotspots from northeast Asia to the Middle East. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other advances, Clinton said U.S. ties with China helped  
the administration negotiate a nuclear freeze with North Korea five 
years ago and persuade China to stop selling weapons-related 
nuclear materials to Pakistan and Iran. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, apparently intent on not inflaming Zhu on the eve of  
his White House visit, softened the administration's rhetoric on 
human rights and offered only passing mention of Tibet in his 
speech. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton praised the advances in the rights situation in China  
over the past decade and said it is in China's own interest to 
establish a more open society. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because wealth is generated by ideas today, China will be less  
likely to succeed if its people cannot exchange information 
freely,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``China also will be less likely to succeed if it does not build  
the legal and political foundation to compete for global capital; 
less likely to succeed if its political system does not gain the 
legitimacy that comes from democratic choice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., and Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif.,  
urged Clinton to use Zhu's visit to step up pressure on China to 
respect human rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Pelosi said Clinton publicly should request the release of the  
hundreds of political prisoners still held since from the Tiananmen 
Square crackdown in 1989 and ask Beijing to review all cases 
involving political prisoners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
