<HEADLINE> AP Names Washington Assistant Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- John Solomon, who has directed the AP's  
investigative reporting in the nation's capital for the past five 
years, has been named an assistant chief of bureau in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointment was announced today by Chief of Bureau Sandy  
Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon has served since 1994 as editor of the special  
assignment team that anchored the AP's coverage of the 
Clinton-Lewinsky investigation and impeachment crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	He joins two other assistant bureau chiefs in Washington: Mike  
Feinsilber is responsible for Washington's news report and Fred 
Sweets is in charge of photo coverage. Solomon will be responsible 
for administration of AP's largest bureau. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon joined the AP in Milwaukee in 1987 and became news  
editor there in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the Washington staff in 1992 and wrote an  
award-winning series of stories on Ross Perot's secret dealings 
with President Nixon. In 1993, he was named a news editor in 
Washington and a year later was appointed special assignment 
editor. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon, 32, is from Monroe, Conn., and is a graduate of  
Marquette University. 
</P>
</TEXT>
