<HEADLINE> Spahn To Throw Brewers' First Pitch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Hall of Famer Warren Spahn will return to the  
mound at County Stadium to throw out the ceremonial first pitch 
during the Milwaukee Brewers' last opening day game at the 
ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers are scheduled to play the Chicago Cubs on April 16  
to open their last season at County Stadium. The stadium is being 
replaced by Miller Park, which is expected to open next spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Spahn, 78, threw the first pitch ever in a regular season game  
at County Stadium in 1953 against the Cincinnati Reds. He played 
for the Milwaukee Braves from 1953 to 1964 and helped lead the team 
to the World Series title in 1957. 
</P>
<P>
	Spahn also threw two no-hitters at County Stadium and is the  
winningest left-handed pitcher ever, with 363 victories over 21 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Spahn's teammates during the Braves' glory years included Eddie  
Mathews and Hank Aaron. 
</P>
</TEXT>
