<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Long Bonds Rise, Short Bonds Fall / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Long-term bond prices rose Tuesday, but  
short-term Treasuries were lower as traders looked for direction on 
the course of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1/4 point,  
or $2.50 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, fell to 5.50 percent from 5.52 percent Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds were mixed as traders awaited the next clues on inflation,  
which will appear in Friday's producer price index report. 
</P>
<P>
	Until then, investors have little information to suggest the  
economy is heating up enough to cause the Federal Reserve to raise 
interest rates. Higher rates would hurt the value of existing 
bonds, which pay a fixed rate of return. 
</P>
<P>
	But a recent spurt in oil prices has stirred some inflationary  
fears. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations for subdued inflation and steady Fed policy have  
helped long-term bonds more than short-term maturities. 
</P>
<P>
	Government bonds recently have gained as investors sought a  
haven for their funds during the NATO-led airstrikes on Yugoslavia 
on worries that escalating strife in the Balkans would upset stock 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Wall Street remains as ebullient as ever. The Dow Jones  
industrial average rose 121.82 to 10,085.31 on Wednesday, another 
record, 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader bond market, prices of short-term and  
intermediate Treasury securities were unchanged to down 1/16 point, 
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.39 percent as the  
discount was 4.28, unchanged from Tuesday. Six-month yields were 
4.52 percent, as the discount rose 0.01 percentage point from late 
Tuesday to 4.36. One-year yields were 4.66 percent as the discount 
rose by 0.02 percentage point to 4.44 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.38 percent from 4.50 percent late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose to 124 7/16 from 124 3/8 . The average 
yield to maturity was unchanged at 5.22 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
