<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 08:35:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Narrowly Mixed; Dow Up 29.41 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were narrowly mixed today after aluminum  
maker Alcoa released first-quarter earnings that soundly beat 
analysts' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 29.41 at 9,992.90. Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent sessions, the fortunes of the Dow have turned on early  
indications of companies' first-quarter earnings. On Tuesday, 
Gillette's announcement that it expects to miss analyst estimates 
by one penny depressed consumer stocks and sent Gillette down 7 3/4. 
The Dow slipped 43.84 Tuesday to close at 9,963.49. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, traders were cautious although Alcoa gave them an upbeat  
earnings report. The metals company, a component of the Dow, said 
it earned 60 cents a share in the first quarter, while analysts 
surveyed by First Call Corp. had expected earnings of 54 cents a 
share. Alcoa shares rose 13/16 to 41 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were anticipating an after-hours earnings release from  
Yahoo!, which was also expected to beat estimates. Its shares rose 
11/16 to 215 9/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Revlon rose 2 13/16 to 22 13/16 after the cosmetics maker said  
it is considering the sale of one or more of its businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. stock market drew strength today from overseas trading.  
European markets were strong for a second consecutive session. 
Japan's Nikkei index increased a solid 0.5 percent, and Hong Kong's 
Hang Seng soared 5 percent after a long holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 8.54 at 1,326.43, and the  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was up 2.77 at 2,565.94. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues were ahead of advancers by a very slim margin  
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 249.6 million 
shares, ahead of Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 1.93 at 614.25, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 0.85 at 716.06. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 15:22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Prosecutor Attacks Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's top prosecutor sought parliamentary  
support Wednesday in his personal battle with Boris Yeltsin, saying 
his suspension by the president was an attempt to conceal 
corruption in the Kremlin. 
</P>
<P>
	``Never before have corrupt officials cast such a brazen  
challenge to the law,'' Prosecutor General Yuri Skuratov said in a 
speech before parliament's lower house, the State Duma. ``Their 
goal is obvious -- to remove the inconvenient prosecutor general 
using all means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Skuratov was invited to speak before the Duma by Communists and  
other hard-liners who hoped he would give them fresh ammunition to 
use against Yeltsin before an impeachment debate begins April 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Skuratov tried to rally support before the upper house of  
parliament again considers his resignation, which he submitted 
Tuesday. He said he was willing to stay if lawmakers support him. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin and Skuratov have been locked in battle for months.  
Yeltsin tried to fire him in February, but the upper house refused 
to back Yeltsin's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Right after that, state television ran a video that showed a man  
who appeared to be Skuratov having sex with two women identified as 
prostitutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin suspended Skuratov last Friday, saying investigators  
were checking whether criminal suspects provided Skuratov with 
prostitutes in exchange for stalling investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	Skuratov fought back Wednesday, telling the lower house of  
parliament that Yeltsin's action was a ``flagrant violation of the 
law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He refused to name any of the allegedly corrupt officials he has  
accused of plotting against him, but threatened to reveal all 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they resort to even more flagrant lawless steps against me  
and I have no other choice, I may bring out the heavy artillery,'' 
he told the Interfax news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Skuratov's probe has focused on alleged bribery involving  
government officials who gave large construction contracts to the 
Swiss company Mabetex. No one has been charged, and Kremlin 
officials and Mabetex have denied any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite general support from communists and their allies  
Wednesday, Skuratov faced hostile questions relating to the steamy 
videotape. He refused to confirm or deny whether he was the man in 
the video. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can't tell us the truth like a real man. He is a coward!''  
shouted ultranationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Skuratov also rebuffed accusations that he hasn't properly  
fought corruption and other crime since his appointment in 1995. He 
pointed out several high-profile cases and took credit for warrants 
issued Tuesday for the arrest of Russian tycoons Boris Berezovsky 
and Alexander Smolensky. 
</P>
<P>
	Berezovsky said in Paris that he plans to return to Moscow next  
week to face his accusers. He accused Prime Minister Yevgevy 
Primakov -- with whom Berezovsky has been battling for months -- of 
being behind the money-laundering charges and trying to turn back 
economic reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigator Nikolai Volkov of the Prosecutor General's office  
told Russia's NTV television Wednesday that Berezovsky was behind 
the illegal transfer of $250 million from Russia's largest airline 
Aeroflot to the Swiss company Andava. Berezovsky denies any 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:33:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wanted in D.C.: Tree-Eating Beaver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The hunt is on for a beaver that's toppling  
cherry trees near the Jefferson Memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Park Service began preparing traps Wednesday to  
catch the sharp-toothed rodent who's chewed his way through nine 
trees in less than a week, said spokesman Earle Kittleman. The 
beaver has damaged four others that officials don't expect to 
survive, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials bemoaned that he's chosen the middle of the capital's  
annual Cherry Blossom Festival for his destructive campaign. The 
festival celebrates the gift of 3,000 trees from Japan in 1912. The 
trees, which ring the Tidal Basin near the national Mall, flower 
for just two weeks each year and have been at their peak since 
Easter. 
</P>
<P>
	``And here comes this beaver who is certainly upstaging us  
all,'' Kittleman said. ``We're a bit chagrined, to say the least.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While there may be more than one culprit, officials believe it's  
a solo job, Kittleman said. Tourists and a Park Service naturalist, 
Julia Long, have spotted the flat-tailed varmint floating in the 
Potomac River, but they've only seen one, Kittleman said. 
</P>
<P>
	He's been a busy fellow, said officials, noting that bite marks  
and other damage to some 30 trees have appeared since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that the critter is actually felling trees, the Park Service  
is determined to trap him, but Kittleman said no one wishes him 
ill: ``We want to get him back into an area where he can do his 
natural thing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
