<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US To Impose Tariffs in Banana Spat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States has been given the go-ahead  
to impose penalty tariffs on $191.4 million worth of European 
imports annually, getting to choose from a list that includes 
Scottish cashmere sweaters, fancy French handbags and German coffee 
makers. 
</P>
<P>
	The 100 percent tariffs, which are designed to eliminate the  
targeted products from U.S. stores, were awarded by the World Trade 
Organization on Tuesday as a fallout from a nasty trade war between 
the United States and Europe over bananas. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO ruled that U.S. banana companies were suffering $191.4  
million in lost sales annually because of unfair European 
restrictions that favor bananas grown in former European colonies 
in the Caribbean and Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	While this represented a reduction of nearly two-thirds from the  
original U.S. damage claim of $520 million, the Clinton 
administration said the smaller figure was still the largest damage 
award ever approved by the WTO, the Geneva-based organization that 
sets the rules for world trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``This decision is an important victory for the WTO dispute  
settlement process and sends a clear message that the WTO cannot be 
used to engage in endless litigation,'' U.S. Trade Representative 
Charlene Barshefsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	EU officials said today that they would consult with member  
countries before deciding whether to appeal the WTO ruling. 
Officials said under WTO procedures, the United States has 10 days 
to submit a revised target list of products and during this time 
the EU has the option of appealing the ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``We reserve the right to appeal,'' EU official Simon Fraser  
told reporters in Brussels. But he said the 15-nation EU had ``no 
intention of dragging this out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barshefsky said the final list of targeted products would be  
selected from the original target list and would be published 
within the next few days in the Federal Register. 
</P>
<P>
	EU officials have charged political motivations were behind the  
U.S. determination to start a trade war over a product that 
accounts for a minuscule amount of trade between the world's two 
biggest trading partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Two American companies, Chiquita Brands International and Dole  
Food Co., grow their bananas on plantations in South America. Carl 
Lindner, the head of Chiquita, has been a major campaign 
contributor to both Democrats and Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Clinton administration insisted that it has been  
fighting to uphold the principal that countries that lose cases 
before the WTO must either eliminate their unfair barriers or face 
economic penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Scher, America's top negotiator on agriculture matters,  
said the United States had prevailed on every major point in 
contention. EU officials said late Tuesday they were still studying 
the 150-plus-page WTO ruling and would have no immediate comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States began requiring importers to post 100 percent  
bonds on March 3 on the larger $520 million list of products but 
said it would reduce the ultimate penalties once the WTO ruled on 
the appropriate level of damages. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, EU Trade minister Leon Brittan charged that the  
United States was acting in an ``unacceptable and unlawful'' manner 
in requiring importers to post bonds before the WTO arbitration 
decision was made. 
</P>
<P>
	Scher said the banana ruling set an important precedent for a  
second trade fight the United States is waging with Europe over its 
ban on American beef containing growth hormones. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has published a separate list  
covering more than $900 million in imports and will hold a hearing 
on April 21 to receive public comments on what products should be 
targeted in the beef dispute. American cattle producers contend 
they are losing $500 million annually because of the hormone ban. 
</P>
<P>
	The original $520 million sanction list in the banana fight  
covered Louis Vitton handbags from France, sweet biscuits from 
Britain, Parma ham and pecorino cheese from Italy, German coffee 
makers and less fancy imports ranging from plastic packaging 
material to electric batteries. 
</P>
<P>
	The $900 million preliminary target list in the beef dispute  
included truffles and foie gras, Evian and Perrier mineral waters, 
Danish ham and Belgian chocolates. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 10:45:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Def Jam Founder Branches Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- While watching unedited footage from his new  
urban entertainment TV show, ``Russell Simmons' Oneworld Music 
Beat,'' a grimace suddenly appears on Russell Simmons' face. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not the show's content that has the rap mogul frustrated.  
Instead, it's the techno pop accompanying a segment on comedian 
Chris Rock that has crawled under Simmons' skin. 
</P>
<P>
	``That music is like anti-hip hop,'' complains the founder of  
Def Jam Records to a group of executives at the midtown offices of 
Warner Bros., which is distributing the show. ``Can't we get the 
Slick Rick music? We own that already. I much prefer to use that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though it has already been on for several months, Simmons is  
still trying to smooth out glitches in ``Oneworld,'' his latest 
attempt to bring the hip-hop culture to the masses. 
</P>
<P>
	With his new wife, model Kimora Lee, as host, the syndicated  
hourlong show, which usually airs late at night, offers profiles of 
artists like Mase and Lauryn Hill, along with the latest hip-hop 
news, trends and celebrity interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're going to make it a much, much better show. It's  
going to be like a magazine show that really is quoted, whether 
it's in colleges, campuses, or in any clubs,'' he predicts. 
``That's what I intend, to make like a really important source of 
information about the community, because the culture has grown so 
much that there is a big void there that we are filling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Simmons, it's a mission that has lasted most of his adult  
life. Long before Sean ``Puffy'' Combs became rap's best-known 
promoter, Simmons helped hip-hop grow from a cult following 20 
years ago to a mainstream phenomenon. 
</P>
<P>
	But he is more than a behind-the-scenes industry executive. He's  
also a celebrity in his own right, his name popping up in gossip 
columns alongside Hollywood stars and society swells. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's unbelievably charismatic, is not afraid to talk and  
promote anybody, and lives in a bunch of different worlds,'' said 
Def Jam President Lyor Cohen. ``He is probably rap's greatest 
ambassador because he feels so comfortable in traveling in 
different worlds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons, 41, grew up in the Hollis section of the New York City  
borough of Queens. His mother was a social worker and his father 
taught history at Pace University. One of his two brothers is Run 
of the rap group Run DMC, one of the first acts Simmons helped to 
make famous. His older brother Danny is a painter who runs the Rush 
Philanthropic Arts Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	Before rap's birth, the young Russell vibed to the edgy rhythm  
and blues of producers like Gamble &AMP; Huff and their Philadelphia 
sound. 
</P>
<P>
	``The black pop stuff, mostly I didn't care for that,'' he said.  
``A lot of the records that became rap beats later were the kind of 
records that I liked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He dropped out of the City College of New York just four credits  
shy of graduating and became a party promoter after his interest 
was sparked by a visit to a local club. He worked his way up to 
promoting and managing such acts as Kurtis Blow and Run DMC, and 
went on to help create Def Jam Records, the most influential label 
devoted to rap. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, as head of Rush Communications, he started ``Def Comedy  
Jam,'' television shows and tours that introduced comedy audiences 
to a new style of comedy, brash and urban, and launched the careers 
of Martin Lawrence and others. He also expanded into advertising, 
film and fashion. Phat Farm is one of the priciest and most 
sought-after labels. 
</P>
<P>
	Even during an interview, constant interruptions keep Simmons'  
attention jumping about. 
</P>
<P>
	Combs phones and wants to be outfitted in the latest Phat Farm  
goods (``Keep him under $3,000,'' Simmons says in a telephone call 
to his store); hot Def Jam rapper Redman stops in to talk about his 
latest CD; then Simmons gets confirmation of a major deal for his 
advertising company. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have a structured schedule. I work for everybody,'' he  
says. ``I work for the presidents of all the different companies. I 
do what they need. ... I help to promote a positive corporate 
culture and I give direction to a lot of people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Def Jam label is now enjoying perhaps its biggest success in  
years, with record-breaking and million selling albums from DMX, 
Foxy Brown, Jay-Z, Method Man and others. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet it hasn't always been smooth sailing for the company. Def  
Jam languished when California rap started making waves in the 
early 1990s, says Nelson George, author of ``Hip-Hop America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It had a definite down period for a couple of years where it  
lost its direction, and when the L.A. thing really came in, Def Jam 
suffered. They weren't able to react very well,'' said George, a 
longtime friend of Simmons. 
</P>
<P>
	But Simmons scoffs at parallels to other rap labels.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're the biggest rap label in the business. ... Our release  
schedule speaks for itself and our sales speak for themselves,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Def Jam's success is part of the continuing strength and growth  
of the hip-hop industry, which is finally gaining some respect 
among those who dismissed it as a fad. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauryn Hill of the Fugees recently won five Grammys for her  
critically acclaimed and best-selling album, ``The Miseducation of 
Lauryn Hill,'' while rappers Master P and Puff Daddy are among the 
highest-earning entertainers in the music business. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons grows tired of hearing people express surprise that rap  
is still topping the charts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been here 20 years, rap. And every year, it's the same  
thing -- 'Are we going to peak this year?''' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are all kinds of attitudes in hip-hop that are being  
represented and promoted. More likely, what we hear about is the 
negative, because that's what some people think is newsworthy, but 
it's certainly not what sells. What sells is a mixture, a good, 
honest mixture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Def Jam is so successful that Simmons has negotiated a deal to  
sell his 40 percent stake in the company to Seagram's Universal 
Music Group, its current distributor, for a price that could net 
him $100 million. He said he would still have a role in the company 
as chairman, and Universal's Mercury/Island Records would become 
part of Def Jam. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes perfect sense for me,'' he said. ``I need a bigger  
presence in music and I would get a bigger presence in music 
because of this merger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons is already working with Mercury/Island artists Dru Hill,  
and, more interestingly, Lionel Richie -- pairing the pop singer 
with some of rhythm and blues' hottest new producers. It's ironic, 
considering Simmons' declared hatred for rhythm and blues. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hated R&AMP;B in the state it was in,'' Simmons said. ``It was  
old. There was nobody talking to young people at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But not everything Simmons touches turns to gold.  
</P>
<P>
	His foray into film was a disaster. He started Def Jam Pictures  
with Polygram (a distributor of Def Jam Records until Polygram was 
absorbed by Universal), hoping to make the same impact in movies as 
in music. It didn't happen. 
</P>
<P>
	``My whole Hollywood thing was a joke,'' he said. ``I went out  
there to make movies for Polygram, and I basically got jerked 
around and wasted time and brought a house and didn't make any 
movies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Well, he did actually make some movies, but mostly on his own.  
His biggest success came as a producer of Eddie Murphy's ``The 
Nutty Professor.'' But ``How to Be a Player'' and ``Gridlock'd'' 
flopped. 
</P>
<P>
	But Simmons has no regrets.  
</P>
<P>
	``I knew it wasn't going to make any money,'' he said of ``The  
Funeral,'' the unsuccessful movie he made with director Abel 
Ferrara. 
</P>
<P>
	``But in terms of filmmaking, it was a better experience for me  
in terms of learning than making 'How to Be a Player'.'' 
</P>
<P>
	These days, much of his focus is on his fashion business. Phat  
Farm is now a multimillion-dollar business, and is probably the 
Rush Communications subsidiary that occupies most of his time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking at probably $50 million this year, without  
blinking, and that's a big number for us,'' he said. ``The only 
company that I think to this day will short circuit if I don't go 
to work is the clothing company, and that's because there is so 
much growth.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 14:45:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alcoa Reports Modest Income Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Alcoa's earnings rose 5 percent for the first  
quarter, partly due to acquisitions and production efficiencies 
that offset falling aluminum prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The results reported Wednesday beat Wall Street expectations and  
the stock surged $2.93 3/4 a share, or 7 percent, to $44 in trading on 
the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's biggest aluminum producer earned $221.1 million, or  
60 cents a share, in the first three months of 1999 compared to 
$209.9 million, or 62 cents a share, a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The per-share income declined because Alcoa increased the number  
of its common shares outstanding by 31 million to 367 million 
shares with its purchase of Alumax last July. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts surveyed by First Call expected Alcoa earnings of 55  
cents per share on average. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales increased 15.6 percent to $3.98 billion from $3.45 billion  
from a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcoa chairman Paul O'Neill said net income would have dropped  
$110 million without the production efficiencies and acquisitions 
of Alumax and Inespal. 
</P>
<P>
	Aluminum prices as reported on the London Metal Exchange have  
dropped 18 percent in the past year to their lowest level in five 
years, Alcoa spokeswoman Bonita Cersosimo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcoa purchased Inespal for $410 million in February 1998 and  
Alumax for $3.8 billion in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 15:49:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford, Dole Criticize Kosovo Tactics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Miscalculations by the White House have made the use of ground  
troops in Kosovo the only option short of NATO's defeat, former 
President Ford said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration overemphasized the power of  
airstrikes and underestimated the magnitude of the humanitarian 
crisis, Ford said in a telephone interview from his home in Rancho 
Mirage, Calif. ``The net result is they have two choices,'' he 
said. ``One choice is to go all-out and win the war with ground 
troops, or two, to quit and admit defeat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Continuing on the current course ``I don't think is going to do  
anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The air campaign drew a mixed review Wednesday from former Sen.  
Bob Dole, who served President Clinton as an envoy in Yugoslavia. 
Dole said the effort was suffering from poor preparation but 
appeared finally to be achieving some goals. 
</P>
<P>
	He said in an interview he cannot understand why it is taking so  
long to get Apache helicopters in place and it appears military 
leaders are generally running into some political interference. He 
also questioned why Clinton would rule out ground troops -- 
``telegraph your punches'' -- at the outset of the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I support the general effort,'' Dole said. ``I think it comes  
years too late and I kind of hoped we'd been better prepared. A lot 
of ... just basic preparation wasn't done. But that's history and 
we have to deal with where we are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The air attacks, he said, are ``beginning to have an impact''  
even if the effort ``is not quite as rapid or intense as some of us 
had hoped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford, who has not often commented on Clinton's policies, said he  
told Vice President Al Gore when they talked at the beginning of 
the air campaign that he would publicly support the president's 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the interview, the former Republican president said the  
Kosovo mission was a humanitarian one, not a matter of national 
security for the United States until its forces got involved. He 
hoped Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic could be persuaded to 
let NATO forces in to monitor the return of displaced ethnic 
Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would just hope that the threat of NATO air and ground  
operations would shock him into doing what's right,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As special emissary for Clinton, Dole helped bring the ethnic  
Albanians over to supporting an agreement, which the Serbs refused 
to endorse. The Serb refusal led to the NATO bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole was also instrumental, as Senate majority leader, in  
helping Clinton win Republican congressional approval for sending 
ground troops to Bosnia to support the peace agreement reached in 
late 1995, just as the two men were preparing to go head to head in 
the 1996 presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to start second-guessing,'' Dole said of the NATO  
effort, acknowledging decisions unavoidably take time when 19 
member countries are involved. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said plans should have been made at least to permit rapid  
deployment of Apache helicopters, said to be capable of closely 
engaging Serb units too scattered or small for bombers. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said it may take a week to put the German-based  
Apaches in use because of strains on air transport caused by 
humanitarian flights and the complex support units required by the 
helicopters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
