<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Stops Refugee Exodus  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav authorities today prevented  
waves of ethnic Albanian refugees from leaving Kosovo by sealing 
off main border crossings with Albania today. After forcing more 
than 400,000 refugees out to neighboring countries, Yugoslav 
authorities closed the main exit route without explanation, forcing 
tens of thousands of people back toward the burned villages they 
had been escaping. Meanwhile, NATO stepped up its airstrikes, 
announcing their ``first major breakthrough against armored forces 
in the field'' in Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav Army Moves Into Montenegro  
</P>
<P>
	PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav forces positioned units in  
residential areas in Montenegro today, prompting fears that the 
army may be trying to draw NATO attacks to undermine this 
republic's pro-Western government. The republics of Serbia and the 
much smaller Montenegro together make up Yugoslavia. President Milo 
Djukanovic, an outspoken critic of Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic, has refused to go along with Milosevic's declaration of 
a state of war. NATO officials have largely spared Montenegrin 
targets as a sign of support for Djukanovic. 

</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! Reports $16M 1Q Profit  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Yahoo! Inc., the second-most popular  
Internet destination, reported a sharply higher first-quarter 
profit of $16 million today that beat Wall Street forecasts, helped 
by a surge of Web visitors and new deals with online businesses. 
Yahoo!, one of the few Internet companies that actually makes 
money, said its profit came to 7 cents a share in the three months 
ended March 31. That was up from a profit of $3.3 million, or 2 
cents a share, in the first quarter of 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	China Premier Arrives in Washington  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- His China policy under attack, President  
Clinton warned today that a souring of relations resulting from a 
``campaign-driven cold war'' with China could erase the gains that 
he claimed for his policy of engagement with Beijing. Chinese 
Premier Zhu Rongji arrived here today for two days of talks on 
security issues, trade, Taiwan and other subjects. Zhu hopes to 
close a deal with the Clinton administration to allow Beijing to 
join the World Trade Organization. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Accused of Rights Violations  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Human rights watchdog Amnesty International today  
showcased an alleged victim of American police brutality in an 
effort to strengthen its campaign against abuses in the United 
States. Amnesty has mounted a high-profile campaign to get the 
53-nation U.N. Human Rights Commission to censure the Americans at 
its six-week annual session. Shirley Alejos, a U.S. citizen of 
Puerto Rican origin, recounted her ordeal at the hands of Chicago 
police in 1994. Amnesty is citing police brutality as one of the 
key human rights violations in the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Cronyism Blamed for CEO Paychecks  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Conflicts of interest are too common across  
Corporate America, the AFL-CIO complained today in a report that 
blames cronyism for helping fuel skyrocketing executive paychecks. 
In part due to spiraling stock options, the average CEO of a major 
corporation made $7.8 million, or 326 times more than the $24,000 
earned by a typical American factory worker in 1997. The report 
cited examples like Carnival Corp. CEO Micky Arison, who sits on 
the compensation committee that created his nearly $6 million pay 
package. 

</P>
<P>
	'The Hours' Wins PEN/Faulkner Prize  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Michael Cunningham's ``The Hours'' has won the  
$15,000 PEN/Faulkner Award, the largest prize awarded by a jury in 
the United States for fiction. Four nominees for the PEN/Faulkner 
award will get $5,000 each: Russell Banks for ``Cloudsplitter,'' 
Barbara Kingsolver for ``The Poisonwood Bible,'' Brian Morton for 
``Starting Out in the Evening'' and Richard Selzer for ``The Doctor 
Stories.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes at 10,085.31, a New High  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average soared in the  
last hour of trading today and hit a new closing high as investors, 
nervous about upcoming earnings reports, sought the relative safety 
of blue-chip stocks. The Dow closed up 121.82 points at 10,085.31. 
On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,600-1,381. The Nasdaq fell 18.81 
to 2,544.36. 

</P>
<P>
	Ripken Misses Start Due to Injury  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- For the first time since 1982, Cal Ripken  
missed a start because of injury today. Ripken, who left the 
Baltimore Orioles' season opener Monday in the third inning with 
stiffness in his lower back, began Wednesday's game against Tampa 
Bay in the dugout while Willis Otanez took over at third base. The 
last time Ripken missed a game because of injury was in May 1982 
after he got beaned. His record consecutive-game streak of 2,632 
began later that month and ended last Sept. 20. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  

</P>
</TEXT>
