<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Naval Academy Enforces Sex Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- Birk Billingsley fell in love last fall.  
He said his romantic relationship with an underclassman was 
intimate, but didn't include sex. 
</P>
<P>
	It was still too much for the Navy.  
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the 22-year-old senior walked out the gates of the  
U.S. Naval Academy, expelled a few weeks shy of graduation for 
having an inappropriate relationship with a member of his squad. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made a mistake. There's really no excuse for my actions -- I  
fell in love,'' Billingsley said. ``I really don't think what I did 
warrants my expulsion from the academy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is just one of several midshipmen disciplined recently for  
sexual misconduct at the Academy, where officials still struggle to 
regulate the urges of college-age men and women after 22 years of 
coeducational classes. 
</P>
<P>
	Four students were expelled this year for sexual misconduct or  
fraternization, pending the Navy's final ruling. Five were expelled 
last year, The (Baltimore) Sun reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice Adm. John Ryan, has reminded midshipmen that he won't  
tolerate fraternization. But academy officials know they're 
restricting activities that, on any other campus, are commonplace. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the rules -- no sex with a freshman, no sex on campus --  
midshipmen regularly fall in love, have sex and sometimes get 
caught. Billingsley's expulsion is an example of how difficult the 
rules are to enforce. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Navy quarterback Chris McCoy was accused of having  
sex off campus with a freshman who allegedly had sex with two other 
midshipmen on campus. She was expelled. He wasn't. 
</P>
<P>
	Some midshipmen have had sex with freshmen off campus without  
being expelled, while others who have merely kissed on campus have 
been told to leave. Some who have been expelled say the system 
seems unfair. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no formula or template used to determine outcomes and  
it is wrong to assume that every case should be treated 
identically,'' said Cmdr. Mike Brady, a spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Billingsley's expulsion means the Dublin, Texas, student is  
responsible for paying the $93,000 cost of his education. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Billingsley is reluctantly applying to Stanford, Georgia  
Tech and Purdue universities to finish his aerospace engineering 
degree. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been the most humiliating and excruciating experience  
of my entire life,'' he said. ``To come this far, it's just really 
difficult.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
