<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Six Runners Join Boston Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Six runners have joined the elite field of  
athletes set to compete in the 103rd Boston Marathon, and two 
runners withdrew, marathon officials announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the women's side, running the race will be Anuta Catuna of  
Romania, who finished third in the 1998 Boston Marathon in 2 hours, 
27 minutes, 34 seconds, and Martha Tenorio of Ecuador, who finished 
seventh in 1994 in 2:30:12. 
</P>
<P>
	On the men's side, Jose Garcia of Spain, Isaac Garcia of Mexico,  
Maskaki Oya of Japan and Silvio Guerra of Ecuador will debut in the 
race April 19. 
</P>
<P>
	The six runners join an already strong field which includes  
Moses Tanui of Kenya, who won last year's Boston Marathon with a 
strong finishing kick, and Fatuma Roba of Ethiopia, who won the 
women's race by a wide margin. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Tanui and Roba have won two previous Boston Marathons and  
last year's winning times were the third best for men and women in 
the 102 runnings of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson Kabiga of Kenya and German Silva of Mexico withdrew,  
Kabiga for personal reasons and Silva due to a foot injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
