<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.Has Warning for Serb Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department warned nine top Serb  
military officers in Kosovo today that they could be charged with 
war crimes and crimes against humanity being commited under their 
commands. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin read the names of nine  
commanders U.S. officials believe are in charge of operations that 
have pushed more than 400,000 ethnic Albanians out of Kosovo since 
NATO bombing of Yugoslavia began two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The fact that they may have been under orders from Yugoslav  
President Slobodan Milosevic, who has also been targeted by U.S. 
officials for possible prosecution, would not leave them immune 
from individual prosecution, Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that someone is ordered to commit crimes does not  
relieve that person of the individual criminal liability,'' he 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
