<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Virgin Islands Cannot Pay Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) -- The government  
announced Tuesday that cannot pay any of its 10,000 workers this 
week, marking a long-running financial crisis on this U.S. 
territory in the Caribbean. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Charles Turnbull, a Democrat, inherited a debt of more than  
$1 billion when he took over the government in January from 
Republican Roy Schneider. 
</P>
<P>
	After meeting with financial advisers and sympathetic labor  
leaders, Turnbull told a news conference Tuesday that there was 
only $2 million in the government account in March. 
</P>
<P>
	``After a long discussion with advisers, we determined that the  
wise course of action is to delay pay roll until early next week,'' 
he said of the twice-monthly payment due Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would ask legislators Thursday to approve short-term  
borrowing to finance the pay checks. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a time for panic,'' Turnbull appealed. ``We Virgin  
Islanders are a strong and resolute people. We've been through 
hurricanes in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The government employs about one-third of the islands' work  
force and has long been accused of overstaffing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Virgin Islands has a vibrant economy built on tourism and  
light manufacturing but its public finances have been marked for 
years by budget shortfalls and irregularities. Two major hurricanes 
in 1989 and 1995 worsened the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	Turnbull's announcement comes as his government considers a  
bailout deal from controversial businessman Jeffrey Prosser. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosser proposes to give land to government workers in lieu of  
about $180 million they are owed in unpaid wages, and to build 
community projects he values at $7.8 million on each of the three 
islands of the U.S. territory. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, he wants tax breaks worth about $180 million over 30  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say it is just such tax breaks that have helped bankrupt  
the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
