<HEADLINE> Former FSU Hoops Coach Loucks Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- H. Donald Loucks, who coached Florida  
State's first men's basketball team in 1947, has died of heart 
failure. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Loucks, who died Tuesday, also coached tennis for several years  
at the university beginning in 1947, the year Florida State College 
for Women became the coeducational Florida State University. 
</P>
<P>
	His basketball team finished the inaugural 1947-48 season 5-13.  
That was the only year he coached the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Loucks, who also served as dean of men, retired from teaching  
physical education in 1980 and became a member of FSU's Hall of 
Fame in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a native of Bicknell, Ind., and earned a Ph.D. in  
physical education at Indiana University. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife Mary Etta, son Don, and daughter Judy  
Dillard, all of Tallahassee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
