<HEADLINE> Spyglass To Work With Microsoft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAPERVILLE, Ill. (AP) -- Spyglass Inc. will license technology to  
Microsoft Corp. and work with the company to help accelerate the 
development of Windows CE-based products, Spyglass announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the strategic agreement, Microsoft will pay Spyglass  
$20 million over three years, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spyglass will help Internet device manufacturers develop and  
integrate Windows CE-based applications into their products. The 
products include screen telephones, medical instruments and devices 
in automobiles, said Doug Colbeth, president and chief executive 
officer of Spyglass. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft also is licensing Spyglass technology to explore ways  
to enhance the Windows CE experience, Spyglass said. Windows CE is 
operating system software used for devices that don't require a 
full-featured operating system like Windows 98. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft has used Spyglass' technology before. In 1995, it  
licensed Spyglass' Mosaic software code for its Internet Explorer 
browser. 

</P>
</TEXT>
