<HEADLINE> Charges Dropped Vs. NYC Protesters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prosecutors dropped charges Wednesday against  
the 1,166 celebrities, politicians and other people arrested during 
15 days of protests over the police slaying of an unarmed West 
African immigrant. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Raymond Castello said the protesters were  
sufficiently punished when they were held for several hours after 
their arrests. 
</P>
<P>
	Amadou Diallo, a street vendor from Guinea, was killed Feb. 4  
outside his Bronx apartment when four white officers looking for a 
rapist fired 41 shots. The officers were charged last week with 
murder. 
</P>
<P>
	The slaying led to allegations of police brutality and racism.  
</P>
<P>
	Among those arrested during the demonstrations outside police  
headquarters were the Rev. Jesse Jackson, former Mayor David 
Dinkins, NAACP President Kweisi Mfume, and actors Ossie Davis, Ruby 
Dee and Susan Sarandon. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, a judge dismissed the trespassing and  
disorderly-conduct charges at the request of District Attorney 
Robert Morgenthau. Although the protesters blocked building 
entrances, prosecutors said they were nonviolent and cooperated 
with police. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have the utmost respect for District Attorney Morgenthau,  
and in most instances, I agree with him,'' Police Commissioner 
Howard Safir said. ``This time, however, I do not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, Safir said police had caught the rapist the four  
officers were searching for when Diallo was killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspect, Issaac Jones, 38, lives less than a mile from  
Diallo's apartment. Safir said Jones is believed to have raped 51 
women since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
