<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Engineering Animation's Stock Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Shares of Engineering Animation Inc. plunged  
45.7 percent Wednesday after the company projected 
lower-than-expected profits and revenue for the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The producer of software for three-dimensional designing and  
animation for businesses such as Ford Motor Co. and Lockheed Martin 
Corp. cited a failure to close a half dozen contracts for the poor 
results. 
</P>
<P>
	Its stock fell $18.25 in heavy trading to close at a 52-week low  
of $21.68 3/4 a share Wednesday on the Nasdaq Stock Market following 
the earnings warning Tuesday evening and an apologetic conference 
call Wednesday with analysts, investors and reporters. Engineering 
Animation traded as high as $72 a share last July. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said first-quarter revenue will be about 15 percent  
below analysts' estimates, ranging from $29 million to $31 million, 
and that profit will be below the 26 cents a share that analysts 
had been estimating. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Rizai, Engineering Animation's president and chief  
executive, said that up until now, the Ames-based business had 
exceeded earnings and revenue estimates for each of the 12 quarters 
since it first sold stock to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm more than disappointed -- I'm personally embarrassed,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rizai said the shortfall was not the result of increased  
competition or concerns among software buyers about the Year 2000 
computer flaw. 
</P>
<P>
	``EAI's growth and earnings potential remain strong,'' he said.  
``We have the best technology in the industry, a unique set of 
business solutions for manufacturing companies and a strong and 
growing customer base.'' 
</P>
<P>
	EAI's first-quarter earnings will be announced later this month.  
In the first quarter of 1998, it posted a loss of $448,000, or 5 
cents a share, on revenue of $15.8 million. 


</P>
</TEXT>
