<DOCNO> APW19990407.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 10:45:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	``Deluxe Edition'' (Alligator Records) -- William Clarke, Katie  
Webster, Hound Dog Taylor and the Houserockers 

</P>
<P>
	With the ``Deluxe Edition'' series, Alligator Records founder  
Bruce Iglauer pays tribute to his label's artists. The latest batch 
of releases features three artists with widely varying styles that 
prove the blues are more than 12 bars and a sad lyric. Each compact 
disc contains previously unreleased material and is handsomely 
packaged with candid photos and Iglauer's liner notes. 
</P>
<P>
	Hound Dog Taylor and the Houserockers personified electric  
Chicago blues at the most ragged, no-frills level. Iglauer first 
heard the trio in 1970 and started his label to record them. Rail 
thin and armed with a high-pitched voice, cheap guitar and a slide, 
Taylor banged away at the blues with abandon in South Side clubs 
and Chicago's Maxwell Street market. 
</P>
<P>
	Alligator brought Taylor a measure of fame and international  
exposure. ``Deluxe Edition'' captures the essence of Taylor: 
intimate knowledge of the masters from Elmore James to Big Bill 
Broonzy and originals that rank as classics now (``Give Me Back My 
Wig''), all in a blast-away style that sent audiences home sweating 
before his death in the mid 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	At the other end of the spectrum stands William Clarke,  
harmonica swing master from California. The former machinist turned 
to the blues full time after 20 years on the line, though he never 
left his workingman's roots. Clarke was a fine songwriter as well 
as composer who chronicled some of life's basic issues: family, 
love, money and sex. He did it with a great sense of lyricism in 
his music and a swing that was infectious. 
</P>
<P>
	Tutored by George ``Harmonica'' Smith, Clarke learned the  
chromatic harp and took it a step further, bringing the rich sound 
to smaller harps. In his trademark dark sunglasses and goatee, 
Clark cut an imposing figure on the bandstand, though he was not 
boisterous or bantering. His music did the talking. Clarke's last 
release, 1996's ``The Hard Way,'' was an innovative step toward an 
even broader mix of jazz, swing and blues and won the W.C. Handy 
Award for best contemporary blues album. Clarke never collected the 
award. he died suddenly at 45. 
</P>
<P>
	Somewhere between Clarke and Taylor (geographically, even)  
stands Katie Webster, the ``Swamp Boogie Queen.'' The title cut of 
Webster's ``Deluxe Edition'' says it all about the Louisiana piano 
player: ``Two-Fisted Mama.'' Webster combined a soulful voice with 
a rollicking piano style to reign as Queen of the Boogie. Labelmate 
Koko Taylor gets top billing as Queen of the Blues but Webster 
could hold her own in writing, singing and playing. 
</P>
<P>
	Webster already had a successful career when she came to  
Alligator for her last three recordings, but the selection gives a 
good overview. A stroke in 1993 cut short her career, though she 
still makes occasional appearances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
