<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racist Gang Threats Probed in Texas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- State and federal authorities are investigating  
threats by a racist gang to hold a gathering in the town where a 
black man was dragged to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray said Texas prison  
officials told his office they intercepted letters from members of 
the Aryan Circle. Coded messages in the letters referred to ``a 
family reunion and annual Jasper tractor pull and drag racing 
event'' on April 19. 
</P>
<P>
	April 19 is the anniversary of the 1993 Branch Davidian fire in  
Waco, Texas. The Oklahoma City bombing occurred two years later. 
Both events have taken on symbolic importance to some extremists. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities told today's Dallas Morning News that they are  
taking the letters seriously. The group allegedly has influence 
outside the prison system. 
</P>
<P>
	``The language itself doesn't say something violent. These guys  
know their mail is monitored,'' Gray said. ``But knowing their 
history and thought processes, you'd almost have to assume it was 
going to be violence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letters were sent by an inmate who served time with two of  
the men accused of dragging James Byrd Jr. to death with a truck. 
</P>
<P>
	The first of three alleged white supremacists to stand trial,  
John William King, 24, was sentenced to death in February. 
Co-defendant Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, is scheduled to go on 
trial May 17. No trial date has been set for Shawn Allen Berry, 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray said authorities are concerned Aryan Circle members could  
be planning ``something retaliatory for King's conviction. It's 
very clear that racial extremists and hate groups behind bars are 
adopting King and Brewer as heroes.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
