<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Novice Hopes To Win Masters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Apparently, someone forgot to tell ``El  
Nino'' that no amateur has won the Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	Spanish teen-ager Sergio Garcia, whose nickname means the little  
boy, struts around Augusta National with the confidence of a pro 
twice his age. So, when someone asked Wednesday if an amateur dare 
dream of being fitted for a green jacket, Garcia didn't flinch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very difficult, but I think it's possible to win,'' he  
said. ``You just have to have the week of your life -- playing 
great, putting great, do everything right. I think most of the 
amateurs that are playing in this Masters can have one of those 
weeks. Why not?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Why not, indeed. Garcia has seemed destined for greatness since  
he first swung a golf club at age 3. He was the champion of the 
Mediterraneo Club de Golf -- where his father ran the pro shop -- by 
the time he turned 12. He made the cut in his tour debut on the PGA 
European Tour at 14. He won the Catalonian Open at 17. Finally, he 
captured the British Amateur title last year to earn his first trip 
to the Masters at 19. 
</P>
<P>
	An impressive resume, to be sure. But it doesn't erase the cold,  
hard facts at Augusta National -- the green jacket has been reserved 
for pros only. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Stranahan came within two strokes of Jimmy Demaret in  
1947. Billy Joe Patton finished one stroke out of the 1954 playoff 
between Sam Snead and Ben Hogan. Ken Venturi had a four-stroke lead 
going into the final round in 1956, but shot a staggering 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Matt Kuchar tied for 21st with an even-par 288, the  
first amateur to make the cut since 1992 and the best score by an 
amateur since Rick Fehr in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuchar earned a return trip to Augusta, where he will be joined  
by Garcia and reigning U.S. Amateur champion Hank Kuehne, who was 
knocking balls onto Washington Avenue from the practice range, 
clearing an 85-foot fence that's 285 yards away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the amateur field is pretty good,'' said Garcia, who  
played Kuehne in a match play event near Atlanta a couple of weeks 
ago and won 6 and 4. ``Maybe we can do something good in this 
Masters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia played a practice round with Tiger Woods and Mark O'Meara  
-- the last two champions at Augusta National -- and gleaned some 
valuable knowledge from two-time champion and countryman Seve 
Ballesteros, whom Garcia calls his ``second father.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a great week around here, playing with all these  
great players,'' the teen-ager said. ``It's just something that I 
couldn't imagine when I qualified for the tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia has played four practice rounds at Augusta National since  
Saturday, to go along with two other rounds last November. He 
doesn't think a lack of course knowledge will be a problem in his 
Masters debut. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to be very patient all week,'' Garcia said. ``You  
must hit every shot with a lot of confidence and a lot of 
concentration, because it can cost you a lot of shots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia got a taste of reality during his practice round with  
O'Meara and Woods. The two pros, showing their experience, lured 
the Spaniard and the other member of the foursome, Kuehne, into 
some friendly wagering. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I turn pro, I'd have to win three tournaments to pay back  
the dinners that we lost,'' Garcia quipped afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	All signs point to Garcia turning pro in the Spanish Open, two  
weeks after the Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a thing I have to (discuss) with my dad, with all of my  
family, after this tournament,'' he said. ``I can't tell you for 
sure. I know it's going to be after this tournament, but I don't 
know exactly which day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like Kuchar, the sensation from last year's Masters, Garcia will  
be accompanied on the course by his father, caddie-turned-teaching 
pro Victor Garcia. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of my dreams was to play in Augusta and one of his was  
caddying for me in Augusta,'' the younger Garcia said. `It's going 
to be a great week for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All signs point to a great career, as well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
