<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Novelist in Posthumous Opera Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- More than three years after his death, renowned  
Canadian novelist Robertson Davies makes his opera debut as 
librettist for a world-premiere production based on an ancient 
Roman tale. 
</P>
<P>
	Davies' adaptation of the ``The Golden Ass'' was his last work,  
completed shortly before he died at 82 in December 1995. He helped 
pick the composer and was a personal friend of the director, but 
never had a chance to hear the full score or see the show take 
shape. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact the score, by composer Randolph Peters, didn't get  
finished until a few weeks before rehearsals began at the Canadian 
Opera Company on March 5. The opera will be performed April 13. 
</P>
<P>
	It represents one of the company's most ambitious attempts to  
present a brand-new opera with predominantly Canadian origins and 
personnel. At a cost of $1.2 million, it is the most expensive 
opera commissioned by the company in two decades and has a huge 
entourage, including a 55-member orchestra, 40-member chorus and 
eight dancers for a ballet scene that Davies insisted upon. 
</P>
<P>
	Davies, considered by many to be the most accomplished Canadian  
novelist of all time, was an actor in his youth, an enthusiastic 
pianist and a lifelong opera lover. 
</P>
<P>
	As far back as 1989, the Canadian Opera Company's executive  
director, Richard Bradshaw, urged Davies to write a libretto. 
</P>
<P>
	The author initially demurred, but admitted -- when the topic was  
raised again six years later -- that he had in fact been toying with 
the idea of an opera adapted from a nearly 2,000-year-old Roman 
tale, ``The Golden Ass,'' by Apuleius. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the story of a handsome, hedonistic man named Lucius whose  
curiosity about magic leads to his transformation into a donkey, 
with subsequent misadventures as he tries to earn back his human 
shape. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradshaw, who will conduct ``The Golden Ass,'' said Davies  
``knew his marquee value'' and set his sights high when the early 
discussions of the project turned to a composer. Davies would have 
wanted Leonard Bernstein, had he still been alive, and encouraged 
preliminary contacts with Andre Previn, who was occupied with his 
``A Streetcar Named Desire'' opera project, Bradshaw said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradshaw had his own idea. He sent part of Davies' libretto to  
Randolph Peters, asked for some samples of music, then had the 
compositions played for Davies, who was delighted. That clinched 
the composing job for Peters, whose previous work, ``Nosferatu,'' 
was a Canadian Opera Company world premiere in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The experimental ``Nosferatu'' score received mixed reviews, and  
Bradshaw says Peters' work for ``The Golden Ass'' is likely to 
resonate more warmly with audiences. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's witty, it's bright,'' Bradshaw said. ``We thought in  
places there should be a very strong underlying jazz element.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As director, Bradshaw recruited Colin Graham, a U.S.-based  
Briton who was a friend of Davies. Graham has directed more than 50 
productions of new operas, including many of the works of Benjamin 
Britten as well as Previn's ``Streetcar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradshaw says Graham had the confidence to make some changes in  
the original libretto, even explaining his revisions to Davies' 
wife, Brenda. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Davies, a former actress, has attended some of the  
rehearsals and is expected to receive a tribute on opening night. 
</P>
<P>
	The cast is mostly Canadian, although the role of Lucius will be  
sung by American tenor Kevin Anderson. The choreography is by Debra 
Graham, long associated with the Montreal-based Cirque du Soleil. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradshaw sees the whole project as a gamble, and will consider  
himself a winner if ``The Golden Ass'' is sought by other 
companies. Directors or managers are coming to the premiere from 
top opera companies in the United States, Britain and France. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important to us that it go elsewhere,'' Bradshaw said.  
``Everyone is looking for the new opera that works. We need a 
20th-century opera that enters the repertoire.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
