<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Williams Sisters May Make Fed Squad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Now that Venus and Serena Williams have  
received their primer on the Fed Cup, it shouldn't be much longer 
before they represent the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. team captain Billie Jean King talked with the tennis  
playing sisters last weekend and thinks she made some progress 
toward including the two on the next Fed Cup squad. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told them what the Fed Cup is about because they really  
didn't know,'' King said. ``And hopefully, they will be available 
in July, but I don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the honors go to Lindsay Davenport, the No. 2 player in  
the world; Monica Seles, ranked fourth; Chanda Rubin and Lisa 
Raymond. The U.S. will face Croatia in a quarterfinal match on 
April 17-18. 
</P>
<P>
	The match was originally scheduled for Zagreb, Croatia, but the  
current NATO military action against Yugoslavia led officials to 
move the match here for safety considerations. 
</P>
<P>
	King's talk with the Williams sisters was made possible with the  
help of Pam Shriver and Zina Garrison, both mentors to the sisters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was able to have a nice discussion on Sunday with both of  
the players,'' King said Tuesday. ``.... I was very pleased with 
what transpired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Currently ranked 11th, Serena Williams may not have been able to  
play next weekend even if she knew the history of the Fed Cup, 
according to King. 
</P>
<P>
	``Serena's left knee had been bothering her, and she has done  
very, very well over the last month ... and she just felt that her 
left knee was not going to cut it,'' King said. ``She needed a 
rest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Venus Williams is ranked sixth by the WTA. She and with her  
sister made tennis history when they faced each other in the finals 
of the Lipton Championships last month. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, the International Tennis Federation announced it is  
changing the Fed Cup format for the second time in five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Next year's competition will feature a 13-nation World Group,  
with 12 teams competing in a round-robin stage for three semifinal 
spots and the defending champion earning an automatic berth in the 
final four. 
</P>
<P>
	The round-robin phase will take place over one week. The finals  
will be staged in another week at a venue selected by the defending 
champion. 
</P>
<P>
	In the new format, the eight teams in the 1999 World Group One  
will automatically go into the qualifying round along with the four 
winning teams from World Group Two. 
</P>
<P>
	The final spot will go to the winner of a playoff between the  
four remaining World Group Two nations and the four regional 
qualifying Group One winners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
