<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hero Sailor Poised To Win Solo Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Giovanni Soldini already is a hero. Now he can become a  
champion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian sailor has a 10-day lead heading into the fourth and  
final leg of the Around Alone yacht race, a 27,000-mile, nine-month 
odyssey that takes solo sailors through some of the world's most 
treacherous seas. 
</P>
<P>
	With that kind of cushion, he could sail backward for several  
days and still win. Still, he knows that Atlantic winds are fickle 
-- and remembers his embarrassment there on the first leg, where one 
tactical mistake left him too close to the ocean calms and 500 
miles behind his competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine sailors -- down from an original fleet of 16 -- will take off  
April 10 from Punta del Este, Uruguay, heading through the tropics 
to Charleston, S.C. 
</P>
<P>
	More than the scenery changes: Sailors have spent the last few  
weeks stripping their boats of heavy weather gear as the course 
shifts from a roller-coaster survival run into a tricky, tactical 
upwind dance along the South American coast. 
</P>
<P>
	The race itself was wide open until the third leg, when the  
sailors left Auckland, New Zealand, on Feb. 5 to traverse the 
unpredictable waters around Cape Horn. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the carnage began. Within days, Josh Hall of Britain lost  
his mast and was out of the race; Isabelle Autissier, a heavy 
favorite to win, flipped and could not right her 60-foot yacht, 
PRB; Marc Thiercelin, a fellow French native who was her main 
rival, saw his 80-foot mast crumple and smash a large hole in his 
deck. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was lucky that my head was not cut off,'' Thiercelin said at  
the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Into it all rode Soldini, barreling through 30-foot seas to find  
Autissier's upside-down boat 22 hours later in a Pacific region so 
remote that national rescue agencies would not venture into it. 
Taking only her passport, Autissier opened her boat's final hatch 
and sent her million-dollar racing machine to the ocean floor. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I am here today, if I am able to speak to you, to laugh or  
cry or whatever, it is because Giovanni came,'' she told the 
hundreds who greeted her and Soldini when they arrived March 3 in 
Punta del Este. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, I am sad about my boat, but to be alive is  
better,'' she added. 
</P>
<P>
	Autissier, one of the finest single-handed sailors, gave up her  
decade-long quest to win the race and announced her retirement. 
Soldini earned a medal of heroism from Italy -- and the deep 
admiration of thousands following the race on its Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Thiercelin made a makeshift mast, saw his lead evaporate into a  
huge deficit and was vilified in cyberspace for not coming to 
Autissier's aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldini and Thiercelin are all that's left of Class I, for boats  
up to 60 feet. In Class II, for boats up to 50 feet, Jean-Pierre 
Mouligne of France has a nearly an eight-day lead and is the 
favorite to win. 
</P>
<P>
	But the racing spirit has not been lost -- a fight for second has  
emerged between 54-year-old Mike Garside of Britain and Brad Van 
Liew, 31, of Santa Monica, Calif., the youngest sailor and only 
American left. 
</P>
<P>
	After 35 strenuous days on the second leg, the two Class II  
racers arrived in Auckland within 2 1/2 minutes of each other -- the 
closest finish in race history. Garside has a 9 1/2-hour lead over Van 
Liew going into the fourth leg. 
</P>
<P>
	``This race-within-a-race has definitely increased the stress  
level,'' Van Liew said from Punta del Este, where he was 
overhauling his boat and trying to gain back some of the 30 pounds 
he had lost on the third leg. ``The next leg, all the gloves are 
off.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
