<HEADLINE> Lindros' Father Urges Caution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Eric Lindros' father urged the  
Philadelphia Flyers to ``err on the side of caution'' when it comes 
to his son, who was hospitalized with a collapsed lung. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to wait for the doctors to convince me that he is going  
to be playing in the near future. Eric is going to make the final 
decision,'' said Carl Lindros. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors removed a tube from Eric Lindros' chest, but when the  
Flyers captain can return home remains uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to see how everything goes now with the tube out, make  
sure that he's comfortable and make sure that things remain 
stable,'' team physician Dr. Gary Dorshimer said Tuesday after 
speaking with doctors at Baptist Hospital in Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	The team was hoping to bring the Flyers' star center and one of  
the top scorers in the NHL home today. But Dorshimer said traveling 
depends on how Lindros heals over the next day or so. 
</P>
<P>
	``He obviously has some relief of his pain with that tube being  
out,'' Dorshimer said. ``He had a decent night's sleep, and he's 
planning to do a little more walking around ....'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors were worried that Lindros' right lung might collapse  
again when the tube keeping it inflated was removed. But Dorshimer 
said the X-rays look good. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros woke up in pain Friday morning after a 2-1 victory over  
the Nashville Predators the night before. At about six pints of 
blood had seeped into his chest cavity, apparently causing his 
right lung to collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorshimer said doctors will have to study his progress to  
determine any further treatment once he returns home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
