<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kissinger, Ueberroth on IOC Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- One helped broker peace in Vietnam and the  
Middle East. The other helped turn the Olympics from nearly broke 
into a virtual money machine. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, the IOC hopes Henry Kissinger and Peter Ueberroth can  
help clean up its worst scandal and make sure it never recurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic sources said Tuesday that Kissinger, the former  
secretary of state, and Ueberroth, head organizer of the 1984 
Summer Games in Los Angeles, had been picked for a panel to 
restructure the International Olympic Committee in the wake of the 
Salt Lake bribery case. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not known if either accepted the appointments from IOC  
president Juan Antonio Samaranch, but news that Kissinger was 
involved brought immediate praise from the IOC's harshest 
congressional critic, Sen. John McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is pleased to see the appointment of someone of Dr.  
Kissinger's stature,'' said Pia Pialorsi, a spokeswoman for the 
Arizona Republican whose Commerce Committee has scheduled hearings 
on the Olympic scandal next week. 
</P>
<P>
	She said McCain still hoped for quick reforms by the IOC ``to  
ensure transparency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sources, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said  
Samaranch also asked IOC vice president Anita DeFrantz to serve on 
the panel, IOC 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Hybl, president of the U.S. Olympic Committee, was the  
first member announced earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Kissinger, Ueberroth and DeFrantz were traveling Tuesday and  
unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland, were closed for the  
day and communications director Franklin Servan-Schreiber was 
unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC 2000 was set up last month as the committee's primary engine  
for change after the Salt Lake scandal, in which six members were 
expelled in a million-dollar gifts-for-votes scheme involving the 
Utah capital's successful quest for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission will have 20-24 members, half from the IOC and  
half ``leading personalities who understand sport,'' and 
essentially will come up with a new version of the Olympic Charter, 
the IOC's century-old bylaws. 
</P>
<P>
	It will study and make recommendations on selection of Olympic  
host cities; how IOC members are elected; term limits; structure 
and membership of the ruling executive board; and further roles for 
Olympic athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel also will look at revenue sharing and the evolution of  
the games themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch wants the commission to meet in early June, with an  
interim report presented to the IOC general assembly later that 
month in Seoul, South Korea, the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch, as IOC president, will head the commission and  
appoint its members, two points attacked last month by critics, 
including McCain, who felt the panel needed more independence. 
</P>
<P>
	But with Kissinger a member, the IOC reform panel gains instant  
credibility because of his long record of statesmanship and 
diplomacy. Samaranch had mentioned Kissinger as the type of 
heavyweight he wanted on the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Ueberroth also brings weight -- and an educated outsider's view --  
to the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	After leading the Los Angeles Games to athletic success and a  
$225 million surplus that convinced cities and sponsors the 
Olympics were a good investment, Ueberroth served as baseball 
commissioner and now heads the Contrarian Group, a venture capital 
company based in southern California. He has been critical of the 
IOC and its president. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz was a bronze-medal rower at the 1976 Games who sued  
over the White House-led boycott of the 1980 Games in Moscow. She 
worked with Ueberroth in 1984, was appointed to the IOC in 1986 and 
now runs the foundation of amateur sports in Los Angeles, financed 
by seed money from the '84 surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	Hybl, a former Colorado prosecutor, heads El Pomar, one of the  
nation's largest charitable foundations. He has been USOC president 
since 1996 and headed the ethics investigation into the 1994 
scandal involving figure skating rivals Tonya Harding and Nancy 
Kerrigan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
