<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diller Purchases Two Movie Studios </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Media mogul Barry Diller will get a  
much-needed movie pipeline for his cable outlets with his purchase 
of Seagram Co.'s art house labels October Films, Gramercy Pictures 
and the remains of Polygram Filmed Entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase provides Diller -- who once ran Paramount Pictures --  
with movies for his cable channels USA Network and Sci-Fi Channel. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, announced Wednesday, also positions Diller as a major  
competitor to Miramax, the leader of the art house genre. 
</P>
<P>
	October and Gramercy are major distributors of so-called art  
house films, which offer unconventional themes and are produced on 
relatively small budgets. 
</P>
<P>
	The new movie venture, to be called USA Films, will be headed by  
Scott Greenstein, who had been one of the presidents of October 
Films. USA Films will be a division of USA Networks Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the art house labels, Diller also purchased  
PolyGram's domestic movie operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was valued at between $200 million and $300 million,  
according to sources. 
</P>
<P>
	For Montreal-based Seagram, the sale helps reduce the heavy debt  
it took on last year through its $10.4 billion purchase of 
PolyGram's parent company,PolyGram NV. 
</P>
<P>
	Ever since that deal was struck, Seagram had been looking for  
buyers for much of PolyGram's movie assets, while planning to 
retain its large recorded music business. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagram, which also owns Universal Studios, will keep its hands  
in the art house film business. Universal has a deal with Working 
Title Films -- a production house formerly affiliated with Gramercy 
-- to create three to five movies a year with budgets of up to $20 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Working Title has a strong track record that includes the Oscar  
nominees ``Elizabeth'' and ``Fargo'' and the blockbuster ``Four 
Weddings and a Funeral.'' It also produced the upcoming Julia 
Roberts-Hugh Grant romance ``Notting Hill,'' which will be 
distributed by Universal on May 28. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagram will maintain close ties to Diller with a 45 percent  
ownership stake in USA Networks Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	While Diller doesn't get the creative minds at Working Title, he  
has in October Films a company with an impressive history in the 
independent movie business. 
</P>
<P>
	Its 60 releases include ``Hilary and Jackie,'' ``Secrets and  
Lies,'' ``The Apostle'' and the current release ``Cookie's 
Fortune'' from director Robert Altman. Its upcoming films include 
Sundance Film Festival winner ``Three Seasons'' and Albert Brooks' 
``The Muse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Diller got back into the movie business in the same manner he  
launched his television operation: by shopping at Seagram. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Seagram chief executive Edgar Bronfman Jr. shocked  
Hollywood by selling most of Universal's television assets to his 
mentor, Diller. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the USA Network and Sci-Fi Channel, Diller's USA  
Networks now includes Home Shopping Network and Ticketmaster, the 
telephone ticket ordering service. 
</P>
<P>
	After Bronfman sold the TV assets, questions swept the  
entertainment industry on whether he would remain committed to the 
movie business. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation heightened as Bronfman bought PolyGram to bolster  
his music business and after Universal produced a string of movie 
flops last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech last month in Canada, Bronfman insisted he was  
committed to films, saying the movie business ``plays an important 
strategic role in enhancing the value of our other entertainment 
assets.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
