<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Charges in Ill. License Scam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Six people, including two former supervisors at a  
suburban Chicago driver's licensing facility, have been charged 
with selling commercial driver's licenses to hundreds of 
unqualified applicants. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors said from 1991 to 1998, the six defendants  
conspired to make sure certain applicants passed licensing tests at 
an Illinois Secretary of State facility. They took bribes of up to 
$1,200 per license, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two former managers of the McCook office -- Marion Seibel, 61, of  
Lemont, and George Velasco, 50, of Westchester -- were charged, 
along with three state Transportation Department workers and a 
trucking company employee. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictments bring to a dozen the number of people charged in  
the U.S. attorney's Operation Safe Road investigation. As with past 
defendants, some of those charged Tuesday were accused of using the 
bribes to purchase campaign fund-raising tickets for Gov. George 
Ryan. Ryan was secretary of state prior to entering the governor's 
office in January. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we've charged another case like this where  
there's been this extent of bribery (money) that went into a 
political campaign,'' said U.S. Attorney Scott Lassar. ``It's an 
unusual case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lassar has said previously that Ryan is not a target of the  
federal probe. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan spokesman Dave Urbanek said his boss knew nothing of the  
alleged scheme to sell licenses or to convert the money into 
campaign contributions. He said workers were not pressured to sell 
fund-raising tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Lassar said his office has discovered that more than 400 drivers  
illegally obtained licenses. The investigation is continuing, he 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
