<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Round-the-World Balloon Lands in DC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Smithsonian Institution's newest exhibit  
is as tall as the Tower of Pisa, as heavy as a fighter plane and 
inflates to the volume of seven Olympic swimming pools: the silvery 
hot-air balloon that carried two adventurers around the world in 20 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	The balloonists, Brian Jones and Bertrand Piccard, got a hero's  
welcome Wednesday at the National Air and Space Museum where their 
historic vehicle soon will be displayed alongside Charles 
Lindbergh's Spirit of St. Louis airplane, Orville and Wilbur 
Wright's 1903 flyer and the Apollo 11 command module from man's 
first mission to the moon. 
</P>
<P>
	The balloon, minus the hot air that makes it soar 181 feet, will  
be on display beginning in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The balloon, known as the Breitling Orbiter 3, will arrive at  
the museum after exhibits in Switzerland and London. The skin of 
the balloon, made of a thin, reflective synthetic material, will be 
displayed, but the main attraction will be the gondola. 
</P>
<P>
	The high-tech gondola -- about the size of two minivans -- has a  
bunk, toilet, kitchen area, control panel, oxygen and nitrogen 
tanks, solar panels, satellite phones and a fax machine. Quarters 
were tight, but the two say they did not have a cross word during 
their more than 26,500-mile ride on the jet streams. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't have to overcome nature ... we had to harmonize with  
the wind,'' said Jones, 52, a British pilot and balloon instructor. 
``We just had to put our capsule into a position where Mother 
Nature could just take us in her arms. It was a wonderful 
feeling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For their effort, Anheuser-Busch Cos. made good on its 1997  
pledge to give $1 million to the first balloon team to travel 
nonstop around the globe. 
</P>
<P>
	The team will share half the money. The rest will be used to  
support humanitarian projects around the world, said Marie Bodman, 
president of Breitling U.S.A. Inc., part of a Swiss company that 
makes watches and precision instruments and sponsored the balloon 
excursion. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1984, eight ballooning teams, including five from America,  
have attempted the feat, museum director Donald Engen said. Jones 
and Piccard, 41, a doctor who specializes in psychiatry, were the 
first to succeed -- in 19 days, 21 hours and 47 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	They launched the balloon on March 1 in the Swiss Alps. They  
spent six days over the Pacific Ocean. High above the Gulf of 
Mexico, the weary flyers became poisoned by carbon dioxide, a gas 
from their exhaled breath that built up inside the cabin. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like a really bad attack of asthma,'' Jones said.  
</P>
<P>
	They started inhaling oxygen and changed the cabin's carbon  
dioxide filters. They were breathing fine by the time they crossed 
the Atlantic Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	The balloon landed March 21 in a desert in Egypt. Piccard opened  
the gondola hatch, put his feet in the sand and thought about Neil 
Armstrong, the first man to walk on the moon. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong was so happy to be so far away, Piccard said.  
</P>
<P>
	``We were so happy to put our footprint back on the Earth,'' he  
said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
