<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Edgerrin James Visits Eagles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Miami running back Edgerrin James realizes  
that the April 17 NFL draft will end one journey for him and begin 
another. 
</P>
<P>
	A part of him wishes the date was already past.  
</P>
<P>
	``You're just curious to find out what's going to happen,'' said  
James, who visited the Philadelphia Eagles on Wednesday. ``You just 
do all you can do, go out and show people what you're capable of 
doing as far as the combines and the meetings and everything, and 
it's up to them to make the decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles, who many believe are leaning toward drafting a  
quarterback with the second pick in the draft -- if they don't trade 
the pick -- were also preparing for a visit by Heisman 
Trophy-winning running back Ricky Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia already entertained quarterbacks Akili Smith,  
Daunte Culpepper, Donovan McNabb and Tim Couch, and team officials 
are said to consider all four potential ``franchise'' quarterbacks. 
The visits by James and Williams indicate the Eagles are, at the 
very least, keeping an open mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not surprised the Eagles showed this interest,'' said  
James, who left Miami after a junior year in which he rushed for 
1,416 yards, 17 touchdowns and averaged 5.9 yards per carry. ``If 
they look at my workouts and take into consideration my athletic 
ability, they can't rule me out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	James has been in the long shadow of Williams all year, but he  
has no problem with that. He figures that once he reaches the NFL, 
things will change. 
</P>
<P>
	``We come from two different situations,'' James said. ``I come  
from the University of Miami, where there's no featured person. 
Everybody gets the ball. We have a lot of talent. Not to say Texas 
doesn't, but we don't showcase the running back and they did. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything will pan out once we get to the NFL,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, the Eagles entertained Washington Redskins tight  
end Jamie Asher, an unrestricted free agent. Asher caught 28 passes 
in an injury-shortened nine-game season in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a good fit if it happens,'' Asher said. ``I can  
get open and catch passes. That's what they want the tight end to 
do.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
