<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Plans New Windows Version </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft has postponed indefinitely its plans to  
merge its consumer-oriented Windows 95/98 operating system with the 
business-oriented Windows NT platform. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the company plans to release a new version based on the  
Windows 95/98 operating system, Microsoft president Steve Ballmer 
said Wednesday in a speech at the Windows Hardware Engineering 
Conference and Exhibition in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft officials had previously said that any new consumer  
versions of Windows would be built on the same technology as its 
Windows NT operating systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft postponed its goal of merging the two operating  
systems in order to respond to customer demand, spokesman Bill 
Zolna said. 
</P>
<P>
	The software giant has been struggling to produce its latest  
upgrade to Windows NT, now called Windows 2000. It originally was 
expected out in 1998, but is now more than a year late and is not 
expected out for several months. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft has a lot riding on Windows 2000, especially as  
competitors such as Linux are beginning to chip away at Microsoft's 
dominant market share. The massive and sophisticated network 
software program will be Microsoft's primary operating system for 
business and large-scale computing. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a transcript of the speech posted on Microsoft's  
Web site, Ballmer said Microsoft had hoped to have a consumer 
version built on the business platform by 2000, ``but we've decided 
to do the things that we all need to do to simplify the experience. 
The right approach next year is to continue to enhance the Windows 
98 product.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Features of the so-far unnamed new consumer version of Windows  
include a faster boot-up sequence and an improved ability to handle 
digital media, including images, movies and music, Zolna said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new operating system will be designed to simplify computers  
for users, something Ballmer referred to as an ``It Just Works'' 
concept. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft does not yet have a release date for the new consumer  
version of Windows, Zolna said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
