<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Leader Touts Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil's economy is emerging from a  
prolonged crisis stronger than before, President Fernando Henrique 
Cardoso said in a published interview Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Brazilian economy is stronger than you think,'' Cardoso  
told the Jornal do Brasil of Rio de Janeiro. 
</P>
<P>
	The abrupt devaluation of its currency, the real, in January,  
failed to produce economic collapse or high inflation, as some 
economists predicted. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were difficult moments ... few countries resist a blow  
like that,'' Cardoso said. ``What bank went under? What company 
went under? What country was contaminated? None.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the Banco Marka did go bankrupt. But the Central Bank  
sold it dollars at a subsidized rate to pay off its debts, allowing 
it to go under without alarming the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The widely criticized bailout is now a target of investigation  
by a Parliamentary Panel of Inquiry, or CPI, into the financial 
system and the Central Bank. The government had hoped to avoid such 
an inquiry, but Cardoso said there was nothing to hide. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to stop this mania of seeing risks in everything,'' he  
said. ``Right now, I don't see how a CPI about this endangers the 
currency or the Central Bank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A second congressional inquiry into the judicial system is  
``more complicated,'' Cardoso admitted. The danger is that it could 
create a ``confrontation'' between the legislative and judicial 
branches, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardoso also denied rumors that he planned to replace Finance  
Minister Pedro Malan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Malan is a public servant, a correct man and doesn't abandon  
ship at a time of difficulty,'' Cardoso said. ``The government 
needs people like that. Malan is not leaving.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
