<HEADLINE> 'The Hours' Wins PEN/Faulkner Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Michael Cunningham's ``The Hours'' has won the  
$15,000 PEN/Faulkner Award, the largest prize awarded by a jury in 
the United States for fiction. 
</P>
<P>
	The book, Cunningham's third novel, is set in New York and tells  
a complex story based on Virginia Woolf's famous novel ``Mrs. 
Dalloway.'' Earlier this year ``The Hours'' was a nominee for the 
award of the National Book Critics Circle. 
</P>
<P>
	Four nominees for the PEN/Faulkner award will get $5,000 each:  
Russell Banks for ``Cloudsplitter,'' Barbara Kingsolver for ``The 
Poisonwood Bible,'' Brian Morton for ``Starting Out in the 
Evening'' and Richard Selzer for ``The Doctor Stories.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Past winners include Philip Roth, T. Coraghessan Boyle, E. L  
Doctorow, Don DeLillo and Richard Ford. 
</P>
</TEXT>
