<HEADLINE> Boeing To Sell Info Services Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VIENNA, Va. (AP) -- Boeing Co. is in talks to sell its Boeing  
Information Services subsidiary that provides information and 
systems integration services to the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	The subsidiary has about 1,200 employees throughout the United  
States and overseas. Boeing said Wednesday it is in discussions 
with potential buyers and expects to announce the purchaser in the 
second quarter of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing is the world's largest manufacturer of commercial  
jetliners and military aircraft, and serves as NASA's largest 
contractor. The Seattle, Wash.-based company employs more than 
222,000 people worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing said it believes aligning Vienna, Va.-based information  
services unit with an organization focused on information 
technology may provide enhanced business and career growth 
opportunities not available previously. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing's strategy is to focus company resources on aircraft  
manufacturing. 

</P>
