<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 12:55:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jackson Shifts Focus to Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- After years of trying to shake things up in  
Washington, the Rev. Jesse Jackson is turning his attention to Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The civil rights leader and his followers have bought token  
amounts of stock to get in the door at shareholder meetings of more 
than 200 companies nationwide. His goal is to push the companies to 
put minorities on their boards and invest in minority-owned 
enterprises. 
</P>
<P>
	``We go to them as shareholders, not sharecroppers,'' Jackson  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although there's disagreement over how much effect Jackson can  
have, he turns heads at annual meetings, receiving warm applause 
and polite attention as he stands to ask questions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who is on our board of directors?'' he likes to ask. ``Who's  
managing our 401(k) and pension funds? Who is managing our 
portfolio?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The move puts the two-time presidential candidate on less  
familiar turf, but his Wall Street project has already brought 
results. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, for example, has given a commitment to issue $1 billion in  
bonds through Blaylock &AMP; Partners L.P., a black-owned brokerage in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	And by some accounts, Jackson was instrumental in a deal  
announced this week in which Ameritech Corp. sold nearly half its 
cellular phone interests to GTE Corp. and a minority-owned investor 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	That group, Georgetown Partners, has contributed to the Jackson  
project and will help run the wireless subsidiary if the deal goes 
through. It will be the first black ownership in a 
telecommunications company, something the Federal Communications 
Commission has been seeking for years. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH Coalition will convene a conference next  
Thursday in Chicago. Participants include several Cabinet members, 
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and Arthur Levitt, chairman 
of the Securities and Exchange Commission, in addition to 
executives from American Express, Boeing and Ameritech. 
</P>
<P>
	And on Monday, Jackson plans to meet with executives in Silicon  
Valley, where his organization has bought about $70,000 worth of 
shares in 50 companies, including Hewlett-Packard, Sun Microsystems 
and Apple Computer. 
</P>
<P>
	His biggest complaint is that of the 362 people now on those 50  
companies' boards, only 24 are women, five are black and one is 
Hispanic. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson noted that Apple has no blacks, Hispanics or women on  
its six-member board but uses black figures such as Miles Davis and 
Jackie Robinson in its ``Think Different'' marketing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``They, in fact, are not different,'' Jackson said of Apple.  
</P>
<P>
	Company officials declined to comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Tim Bajarin, president of Creative Strategies Research  
International, a high-tech consulting firm, said Jackson might have 
``a hard time calling any Silicon Valley company prejudiced'' 
because so many employees are of Asian descent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be surprised if he has any effect on these companies  
other than he gets their ear,'' Bajarin said. ``The bottom line is 
that we employ people that are absolutely skilled and trained.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But others say Jackson shows how shareholders can pressure  
companies to make changes. Shareholders need to own as little as 
$2,000 in stock to force a vote on a resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	``It puts the matter right in front of top managers so they have  
to deal with it,'' said Alisa Gravitz, vice president of the Social 
Investment Forum, a Washington-based nonprofit organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co. now counts Jackson among its  
shareholders, and Coke spokesman Robert Baskin said Jackson is 
welcome to address its 12-member board, which includes one black 
and two women. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd love to have him,'' Baskin said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
