<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- A human rights group on Wednesday  
protested the inclusion of a member of a Miami-based Cuban exile 
group in a delegation representing Nicaragua before the United 
Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nicaraguan Human Rights Center said Luis Zuniga Rey was not  
``morally qualified'' to be part of the delegation to the U.N. 
Human Rights Commission in Geneva. 
</P>
<P>
	The center's president, Vilma Nunez de Escorcia, said Zuniga's  
membership in the Cuban American National Foundation disqualified 
him because Cuba says group members funded and planned terrorist 
bombings in Havana. 
</P>
<P>
	The group has repeatedly denied involvement in the bombings,  
which killed an Italian tourist and wounded 11 people in 1997. Two 
Salvadoran men have been convicted in the bombings. 
</P>
<P>
	Zuniga, president of the foundation's human rights branch, said  
President Arnoldo Aleman appointed him to the delegation because he 
appreciates the need to speak out about abuses in Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- A U.S. insurance company has asked a  
Nicaraguan court to turn over a luxury plane stolen from Florida 
and later found to have been used by the nation's president. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacific Insurance Co. of Pennsylvania made the claim Tuesday  
in the 1st District Criminal Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane, a Learjet 35A, was reported stolen from B.L. Bennet  
Aviation in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., in December 1997. The insurance 
company's lawyer, Francisco Ortega Gonzalez, said his firm paid 
$2.3 million for the loss of the plane. 
</P>
<P>
	In May 1998, a national scandal broke out when it was discovered  
that the plane was in Nicaragua and had been used by President 
Arnoldo Aleman and Vice President Enrique Bolanos on official 
trips. Traces of cocaine also were found inside the plane. 
</P>
<P>
	Aleman has said he had no idea the plane was stolen.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- Guatemalan authorities searched Wednesday  
for those responsible for hacking to death a woman and her five 
children, apparently to steal profits from the family's corn crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Amalia Villatoro Argueta de Guinac, 32, was killed with a  
machete Tuesday in Retalhuleu, southwest of Guatemala City. Her 
three daughters and two sons, ages 6 to 14, also were slain. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators say whoever killed them was motivated by robbery.  
Argueta de Guinac had about $715 in profits from the family's corn 
crop. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Puerto Rican rap singer William Jorge  
Brewley was arrested Wednesday for possession of heroin as he tried 
to board an airplane bound for Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Brewley, also known as the ``Godfather of  
Rap,'' had 6 1/2 pounds of heroin hidden in plastic bags in the soles 
of his sneakers, which had false bottoms. 
</P>
<P>
	Col. Manuel Verde Acosta of the National Guard's anti-drug unit  
said agents decided to search Brewley because he looked nervous 
while trying to board the flight at Simon Bolivar International 
Airport outside Caracas. His ultimate destination was Puerto Rico. 
</P>
<P>
	Juan Perez Aponte, who was traveling with Brewley, also was  
arrested on drug charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewley could face between 10 and 20 years in Venezuela's  
prisons, considered among the most violent in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- A Learjet crashed and exploded at a Sao  
Paulo state airport Wednesday, killing all four people aboard, TV 
Globo reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane exploded when it hit the runway in Ribeirao Preto, 190  
miles northwest of Sao Paulo, the station said. TV pictures showed 
the mangled wreckage of the plane on the runway. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane had taken off from Sao Paulo airport and began to have  
difficulties when it was 195 feet in the air, TV Globo said. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims were identified as three pilots and an official from  
a local airline company. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the crash was not immediately clear.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
