<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 14:55:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steelworkers Angered Over Bonuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Union employees of USX's U.S. Steel division  
are angry with what they call meager profit-sharing offerings and 
are urging a return to old-fashioned pay raises during contract 
talks set for later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	While the final sum has not been released, the presidents of  
United Steelworkers' locals have been told that full-time hourly 
employees can expect a bonus of about $360 each under their 
profit-sharing plan with the steelmaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Of that amount, $300 comes from a previous agreement that  
resolved an earlier profit-sharing dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Steelworkers say the paltry sum is insulting.  
</P>
<P>
	``We deserve more than $55 or $60,'' said Don Thomas, president  
of Local 1219 at the Edgar Thomson plant in Braddock. ``If that's 
what they think of their workers, we have a problem. I'm against 
any profit-sharing or bonuses. It's a joke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to steelworkers' irritation is USX chairman Thomas J.  
Usher's annual bonus of $1.2 million or more. His incentive pay is 
based on the performance of U.S. Steel and its sister company, 
USX-Marathon Group. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1993 labor agreement, union profit-sharing payments are  
based on pretax income after adjustments for such items as U.S. 
Steel's share of USX's overall debt costs. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Steel earned a $364 million net profit last year;  
profit-sharing checks for union workers are to be distributed by 
April 15. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997 U.S. Steel's net profit was $452 million; steelworkers  
each got $1,605. In 1996 they were given nothing based on a profit 
of $273 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Disgruntled workers say they have been duped by U.S. Steel.  
After 1996, the union took its complaint to arbitration and hired 
an accounting firm to audit U.S. Steel's financial statements. 
</P>
<P>
	After the audit, union officials concluded that they were  
getting what their contract required and accepted a settlement of 
an extra $500 last year and the additional $300 this year. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Steel spokesman Mike Dixon said the company has made  
profit-sharing payments eight times since the incentive was added. 
He said a glut of steel on the U.S. market last year cut profits 19 
percent from 1997's record pace. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Walt Lonce, president of Local 227 at the Irvin plant,  
said his members liken this year's proposed bonus to a ``smack in 
the face.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he wants to get rid of profit sharing when the USW  
negotiates a new labor agreement with U.S. Steel. The current 
contract covering about 15,000 workers expires Aug. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an embarrassment to send a check for $60,'' he said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
