<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Longer, Meaner Augusta National  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Augusta National has struck back,  
retaliating against graphite shafts, titanium drivers and souped-up 
golf balls with the most sweeping changes in the course's 68-year 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be a longer, meaner Augusta National meeting the  
challenge of star-wars golf technology when the Masters begins 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pine trees have been planted, rough grown, tees moved back,  
bunkers reshaped, greens raised and mounds shaved in a new Masters 
examination of golfing skills. 
</P>
<P>
	The facelift, presided over by new Masters chairman Hootie  
Johnson, created instant criticism. Most players think that far 
from ``Tigerproofing'' Augusta National it has reinforced its 
reputation as a long-hitter's paradise. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17th hole in particular has been toughened. It's no longer a  
drive and a wedge 400-yard par-4. The tee was moved back 25 yards 
and pine trees planted left and right of the fairway. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Masters champion Gary Player said of the hole: ``Bobby  
Jones would turn over in his grave.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, players could easily drive over the ``Eisenhower  
Tree'' at the edge of the left fairway and have a short iron to the 
green. Now, short hitters have to rifle the ball between Ike's tree 
on the left and the new pines on the right. 
</P>
<P>
	Players were caroming balls off the tree during practice and  
shaking their heads. 
</P>
<P>
	``They hit the tree and it's like a light bulb goes off over  
their head,'' said a spectator, watching the show. ``It's a harder 
hole now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Power hitters, however, may have a solution. John Daly pulled  
out his driver in a practice round, took a mighty swing and the 
ball cleared ``Ike's Tree'' on the 17th hole and landed some 300 
yards down the fairway. 
</P>
<P>
	President Eisenhower hated the pine tree that continually  
blocked his shots on the 17th fairway. He suggested one time that 
the offensive tree be sawed down. 
</P>
<P>
	Late chairman Clifford Roberts heard Eisenhower's complaint and  
replied by naming the tree ``Ike's Tree'' and ordering more 
fertilizer and water for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Modern technology and livelier golf balls made the tree a  
non-factor until the tees were moved back recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiger Woods, the 1997 Masters champion, smiles the smile of a  
sly young fox when he talks about the changes. He believes the 
``Tigerproofing'' has only served to help him. 
</P>
<P>
	``No. 17 in particular is a huge advantage for the long  
hitter,'' Woods said. ``The Eisenhower tree doesn't bother me. I 
just hit the ball over it without even thinking about it. The 
shorter hitters have to work the ball around the tree and probably 
hit 5-irons to the green.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Six-times Masters champion Jack Nicklaus wishes officials hadn't  
given a facelift to golf's Mona Lisa. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told Hootie Johnson I wish he hadn't made them, but the  
changes he made are quite good,'' Nicklaus said. ``I like what they 
did on 17. It's played too short and too easy for too long.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Mark O'Meara birdied No. 17 on the way to his  
Masters title last year. He said the hole now demands more respect. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't hit it over the top of the tree now,'' O'Meara said.  
``The course is longer now and it favors the longer hitters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Norman said changes on No. 17 made it a ``dogleg straight  
hole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It definitely favors the longer hitter who can carry the  
tree,'' Norman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other changes:  
</P>
<P>
	--Moving the tee back 25 yards on the 575-yard, par-5 No. 2 and  
shifting a fairway bunker to the right. 
</P>
<P>
	--Raising the green 2 feet on the 455-yard, par-4 No. 11,  
removing two bunkers and creating a large bunker in the back. Rae's 
Creek to the left of the green was widened and raised a foot. 
</P>
<P>
	--Grading the mounds to the right of the 500-yard, par-5 No. 15,  
planting 20 pine trees on the right, removing the mound on the 
right of the green and planting six pine trees. 
</P>
<P>
	The course has been remeasured from 6,925 to 6,985 yards.  
</P>
<P>
	The rough is 1 3/8 inches high and will create devilish flying  
lies. It's still far below the 4-inch rough at the U.S. Open or the 
3-inch rough at the PGA. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rough creates a little uncertainty when you're playing the  
ball into the greens,'' Nicklaus said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said the changes were made to ``try to keep up with the  
world of golf. It's the most significant changes ever made at 
Augusta and we're just trying to stay in tune with the times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the motive for the changes was to ``require greater  
accuracy off the tee and put certain hazards back into play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Couples, the 1992 Masters champion, said the manipulations  
will raise scores. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody is going to shoot 18-under again like Tiger did,''  
Couples said. 
</P>
<P>
	His prediction for the winning score?  
</P>
<P>
	``Eight or 10-under will be a great score,'' he said. ``The  
course is really playing mean and tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just the way members at Augusta National want it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
