<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toxic Site Wrongly Declared Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUAKERTOWN, Pa. (AP) -- Federal investigators are examining a  
toxic dump that was mistakenly declared safe 18 years ago after 
inspectors went to the wrong site. Neighbors fear they were 
poisoned rather than protected. 
</P>
<P>
	The Environmental Protection Agency arrived here recently to  
examine the dump -- where 3,200 tons of paints, pigments and resins 
were buried in the late 1960s -- after activists brought the 
situation to its attention last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the EPA is trying to determine whether the 86 acres in  
Eastern Pennsylvania is a threat to groundwater and should be 
cleaned up. High levels of arsenic have been found in nearby 
drinking water, but it is unclear if the contamination was caused 
by the dump. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking at the groundwater in residential wells and soil  
at the site to see if the landfill is a danger to the community,'' 
EPA spokeswoman Ruth Podems said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	During the EPA's original probe in 1981, agency officials  
visited the wrong site because of what Ms. Podems called 
``misinformation'' from county records. The land was removed from a 
list of sites marked by the Superfund program as potentially among 
the nation's most polluted waste dumps. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Podems said the site doesn't appear to be particularly  
hazardous, but that is little comfort to Gerald Hardcastle, who 
lives a half-mile away. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardcastle recently found out his well has been contaminated  
with arsenic at 700 times the agency's risk level. The EPA said if 
consumed for many years, the water could pose an increased cancer 
risk. Hardcastle had been drinking the water since 1976. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't know what was in that dump,'' he said. ``It could  
have been paint or anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The private dump, shut down in 1973, was once used by W.R. Grace  
Co., a Boca Raton, Fla.-based supplier of special chemical, 
construction and container products. In a celebrated case in 
Woburn, Mass., Grace paid $8 million to families who blamed 
polluted drinking water for the leukemia that killed their 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal records show that a W.R. Grace subsidiary sent tons of  
paints and resins to the Pennsylvania dump in the late 1960s. 
Activists say there are no documents showing that the waste was 
ever removed. 
</P>
<P>
	Given that the EPA had to assess 20,000 dump sites nationwide at  
the time, Ms. Podems said it's not surprising that a mistake was 
made. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress gave us a tremendous task to find all the messes out  
there,'' she said. ``It's somewhat of a miracle that we got all the 
rest of them right.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
