<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Photos Could Cost Ohio Couple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIMA, Ohio (AP) -- Virginia and Henry Otto say they are so used  
to cars careening off the road near their home that they have 
developed a routine. 
</P>
<P>
	First they call 911, then check the victim and grab a camera to  
take pictures in case they need to file an insurance claim over the 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
	But their most recent photos have them facing charges of  
interfering with paramedics and officers. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident happened early Sunday when a car ran a stop sign  
and hit a gas meter early Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff Dan Beck said Mrs. Otto was told to stop taking pictures  
because the flash could ignite the leaking gas. Mrs. Otto didn't 
comply and a deputy grabbed her camera and accidentally broke the 
flash, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Otto said she must have misunderstood the deputy.  
</P>
<P>
	``If I knew he was going to be that infuriated, I surely  
wouldn't have done it,'' she said. ``It's not that I willfully 
disobeyed that man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Otto said her husband was arrested after he questioned the  
seizure of her camera. 
</P>
<P>
	He was charged with persistent disorderly conduct and misconduct  
at an emergency. His wife was charged with obstructing official 
business and misconduct at an emergency. Both pleaded not guilty on 
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
