<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:24:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM's Sales Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. blamed a lean inventory of  
its hottest-selling vehicle, the full-size Chevrolet Silverado 
pickup, for a March sales performance that lagged behind most of 
its competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said Wednesday that its U.S. sales were off 2 percent from a  
year ago -- lower than analysts had expected. While GM's car sales 
increased 1 percent, sales of light trucks were off 6 percent 
compared with the robust truck sales of March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a bad performance, but when you look at the  
competition, they had a much better month than GM did,'' said 
analyst Greg Salchow of Roney &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The No. 1 automaker's report closed the books on a month that  
saw a surprisingly strong 8 percent increase in sales industrywide, 
despite GM's decline. For the first quarter, overall sales were up 
a robust 11 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I've seen this kind of quarter for about 10  
years,'' said Roy Roberts, GM's North American sales chief. ``It's 
really been a shock to all of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts noted that GM economists predicted sales this year would  
run between 15 million and 15.2 million light vehicles; in the 
first quarter, sales ran at a seasonally adjusted rate of 16.4 
million. Last year the industry sold 15.6 million cars and light 
trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past week, Ford Motor Co. reported its March U.S. sales  
were up 14 percent and DaimlerChrysler AG said its Chrysler unit 
posted a 17 percent improvement. Most major foreign automakers also 
reported strong gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately for GM, many buyers have been turning to Ford and  
Dodge dealers when they've been unable to get a new Silverado 
pickup equipped the way they want. The Silverado is all-new for 
1999, as is its GMC twin, the Sierra. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is virtually selling as fast as we can build it,'' Roberts  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though GM has plans to build 250,000 more trucks this year than  
last, that extra production has only recently begun to kick in. 
</P>
<P>
	While inventories of the more expensive Sierra are fine, GM says  
it has been unable to get stocks of the Silverado up to where it 
wants because of the strong demand. GM also has been hurt by a 
shortage of double-deck rail cars in Canada, where one of its three 
pickup plants is located, Roberts said. 
</P>
<P>
	GM also sold about 10,000 fewer pickups to business, government  
and rental fleet customers last month than it did in March 1998, as 
it focused on meeting more profitable retail orders. A total of 
53,097 Silverados and 20,042 Sierras were sold last month. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said it has an inventory of about 155,000 full-size pickups,  
but needs between 165,000 to 175,000 to meet dealer needs. About 
30,000 of the current inventory are in transit to dealers. Roberts 
said he expected inventories to reach adequate levels in about five 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts said GM also sold fewer of its compact pickups last  
month because it declined to match the level of sales incentives 
offered by its competition, opting for higher profits over 
increased market share. GM's compacts also lack four-door versions 
that some competitors offer. 
</P>
<P>
	GM's U.S. market share last month was 29.5 percent, down from  
29.7 percent in February but ahead of last year's strike-effected 
29.1 percent. GM has started the year with the goal of gaining 32 
percent of the market, but that's appearing unlikely. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pushing to be north of 30,'' Roberts said.  


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
