<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McDougal Closing Arguments Heard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The trial of President Clinton's former  
business partner, Susan McDougal, neared its close Wednesday with 
her lawyer comparing Kenneth Starr's tactics to the Third Reich and 
a prosecutor bristling at inflammatory allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury deliberations were expected to begin Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	In closing arguments, defense attorney Mark Geragos mocked  
testimony from Whitewater prosecutors who said they only wanted the 
truth from Mrs. McDougal and were not out to get the president. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something so offensive for them to say with a straight  
face they wanted to look to see if they could clear the president. 
How dumb do they think we are?'' he asked. Geragos added later: 
``Their goal is to crush everything between them and President and 
Mrs. Clinton'' 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the five-week trial, Mrs. McDougal's defense has been  
based on attacking the independent counsel's office. Mrs. McDougal, 
charged with twice refusing to answer questions before a federal 
grand jury, testified that she feared prosecutors would charge her 
with perjury if she told the truth and did not implicate the 
Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the courthouse, prosecutors noted ``there are lingering  
questions'' in the Whitewater investigation even though Mrs. 
McDougal answered some of the questions related to the Clintons. 
However, prosecutor Mark Barrett added, ``In terms of Mr. and Mrs. 
Clinton, I heard nothing that would have tended to show 
wrongdoing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Julie Myers told jurors that they had to weigh Mrs.  
McDougal's credibility against that of two of Starr's prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who is more credible? Two career federal prosecutors versus  
the defendant who is convicted of four felonies?'' Myers asked, 
referring to her own co-workers on Starr's staff, Ray Jahn and 
Hickman Ewing, who testified in the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	She portrayed Mrs. McDougal, who was convicted of fraud for her  
role in the Whitewater case, as a chronic liar and publicity-seeker 
who reveled in telling a phony story of persecution in TV 
interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	``She craved the spotlight. She enjoyed the attention. And that  
was probably her real reason for not testifying, not those lame 
excuses,'' Myers told jurors. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, who was convicted of four Whitewater-related  
felonies in 1996, testified that her former husband, James 
McDougal, later urged her to say she had sex with the president to 
mollify prosecutors eager to get Clinton for something and thereby 
escape further prosecution herself. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something you expect to see in the Third Reich,''  
Geragos told the jury. Mrs. McDougal has denied any intimate 
relationship with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she was the con artist, the liar, that Ms. Myers made her  
out to be, wouldn't it have been easier to say `I slept with 
President Clinton?''' Geragos asked. ``She could have gotten on any 
talk show she wanted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also noted that Mrs. McDougal had already served 18 months in  
jail for civil contempt because of her refusal to ``become a tool 
for out of control prosecutors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Myers said the suggestion that prosecutors wanted Mrs. McDougal  
to reveal a relationship with the president was an ``inflammatory 
allegation, an astounding allegation, an allegation that's 
absolutely unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal is charged with obstruction of justice and two  
counts of criminal contempt . The judge has limited what the jury 
can consider as her defense. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegation that prosecutors pressured her to implicate the  
Clintons can only be considered in relation to the obstruction 
charge, not the other two counts, U.S. District Judge George Howard 
ruled Tuesday in approving written instructions to the jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Myers noted that Mrs. McDougal said she appreciated Clinton  
providing testimony at her 1996 trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``But when she had information that, according to her, would  
help demonstrate the president's innocence, she selfishly refused 
to provide it to the grand jury or to anyone,'' Myers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett, cited as an example first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton,  
who testified by videotape to the Whitewater grand jury -- without 
the promise of limited immunity that Mrs. McDougal had been 
granted. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mrs. Clinton stepped up to bat and she did her duty,'' Barrett  
said in his rebuttal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
