<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olivetti Pushes Telecom Italia Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Olivetti SpA shareholders approved issuing an  
additional $2.8 billion in stock to help finance the Italian 
company's hostile bid for its larger rival, Telecom Italia SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	The shareholders' meeting Wednesday in Ivrea, Italy, marked an  
escalation in the biggest takeover battle ever launched in Europe's 
telecommunications industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti last month increased its offer for Telecom shares by 15  
percent to 60.4 billion euros, or $65.2 billion at current exchange 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to authorizing Olivetti's board to issue more stock,  
shareholders also approved the sale of bonds worth up to $4.5 
billion over the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti chief executive Roberto Colaninno on Wednesday also  
attempted to clarify the company's strategy for pursuing Telecom 
Italia, which is five times Olivetti's size. 
</P>
<P>
	Colaninno said that Olivetti needs at least 35 percent of  
Telecom's shares in order to manage the bigger company effectively. 
</P>
<P>
	``With 6 percent, one cannot manage. With 35 percent, you can,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Colaninno had said Tuesday that Olivetti would not accept less  
than 35 percent of Telecom's ordinary voting shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Later that day, he backed off from that specific level, saying  
that Olivetti ``reserves the right to decide'' whether to honor its 
takeover offer if its bid gathers between 35 percent and 67 percent 
of Telecom's ordinary voting shares. If Olivetti accepted just 35 
percent of Telecom shares, it would pay about $22.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Colaninno was responding to requests by the Italian stock market  
regulator Consob that Olivetti clarify the minimum level of Telecom 
shares it would accept. Consob said Wednesday that it was still 
evaluating Olivetti's recent declarations regarding its bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom accused Olivetti on Tuesday of ``rewriting the takeover  
rules'' by refusing to clarify the minimum level of shares it was 
seeking. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom said the wide range between 35 percent and 67 percent  
doesn't give its shareholders a clear idea about Telecom's future 
capital structure and ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shareholders ... must be aware that they still are facing a  
takeover bid whose essential elements are absolutely uncertain,'' 
Telecom said. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom chief executive Franco Bernabe has called a  
shareholders' meeting of his own this weekend to consider measures 
aimed at boosting Telecom's value and making a takeover 
prohibitively expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	The measures include converting nonvoting savings shares into  
voting shares; buying back 10 percent of Telecom's outstanding 
shares; and spending some $24 billion to buy the 40 percent of 
Telecom's mobile phone subsidiary, Telecom Italia Mobila SpA, that 
it doesn't already own. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom, a former state-run monopoly, was privatized in 1997.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
