<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Open Higher; Dow Up 37.46 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher Wednesday as aluminum maker  
Alcoa released first-quarter earnings that soundly beat analysts' 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 37.46 at 10,000.95. Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent sessions, the fortunes of the Dow have turned on early  
indications of companies' first-quarter earnings. On Tuesday, 
Gillette's announcement that it expects to miss analysts' estimates 
by one penny depressed consumer stocks all day and prompted 
investors to send Gillette down 7 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow slipped 43.84 Tuesday to close at 9,963.49.  
</P>
<P>
	Today, Alcoa offered a different story. The metals company, a  
component of the Dow, said it earned 60 cents a share in the first 
quarter, while analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. had expected 
earnings of 54 cents a share. Alcoa shares rose 1 1/16 to 42 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were eagerly anticipating the after-hours earnings  
release from Yahoo!, which is also expected to beat estimates. Its 
shares rose 9/16 to 215 7/16. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. stock market also drew strength today from overseas.  
European markets were strong for a second consecutive session. 
Japan's Nikkei index increased a solid 0.5 percent, and Hong Kong's 
Hang Seng soared 5 percent after a long holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 7.81 at 1,325.70, and the  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was up 23.99 at 2,587.16. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 99.5 million 
shares, well ahead of Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 1.99 at 614.31, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was down 0.66 at 714.55. 
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading overseas, Germany's DAX index was up 1.0  
percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.4 percent, and France's 
CAC-40 was up 1.8 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
