<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers' Lindros Status Uncertain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Eric Lindros is coming home. Will the memory  
of his last game of the season stay in Nashville? 
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia Flyers star, recovering from a collapsed lung  
in a Nashville, Tenn., hospital, is scheduled to be flown home 
Thursday. His status for the playoffs is still uncertain, with one 
doctor acknowledging that Lindros will need at least 3-4 weeks to 
regenerate the blood he lost. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked to him today and to the doctors,'' Flyers physician  
Dr. Jeff Hartzell said. ``He's feeling a lot better. His condition 
is perfectly satisfactory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Well, satisfactory for a guy with a desk job, not for one of the  
most talented, ferocious players in hockey. It may be quite some 
time before Lindros gets to put on a burst of speed at the blue 
line again, smack the puck past a goaltender or drop the gloves and 
give the Flyers the boost needed to make a run in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	This is not a chipped tooth, sprained knee or fat lip, the most  
common injuries in Lindros' brutal sport. His collapsed lung, which 
filled with about three liters of blood, was termed 
life-threatening if it hadn't been treated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to wait for the doctors to convince me that he is going  
to be playing in the near future,'' said his father and agent, Carl 
Lindros, who is concerned about his son being rushed back. ``Eric 
is going to make the final decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hartzell spoke with Lindros' father Tuesday and reassured him  
that nothing would be done to jeopardize his son's health. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no rush,'' Flyers general manager Bob Clarke said.  
``We want Eric to come back when the doctors say he's ready. It 
hasn't changed since day 1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros will get a sendoff in the form of a news conference at  
11 a.m. EDT before he leaves Nashville's Baptist Hospital. He will 
be examined by doctors and accompanied by renowned chest surgeon 
Larry Kaiser of the University of Pennsylvania hospitals. Kaiser 
will have the final say as to whether Lindros is ready to travel. 
</P>
<P>
	If all goes as planned, he will be flown to Philadelphia on team  
chairman Ed Snider's jet and sent home to recover. Doctors are 
being tight-lipped about Lindros' prospects for playing again this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``My opinion is, I think nobody really knows,'' Hartzell said.  
``In my own view, two things have to happen. One, Eric has to feel 
strong and ready to play. Two, doctors would have to say there's no 
risk for him to play, and I don't know when that's going to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Gary Dorshimer, another Flyers doctor, said Lindros'  
temperature spiking above 100 degrees Tuesday night was not a 
setback. Lindros had mucous removed from one of his bronchial 
tubes, which could have caused the fever. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros never had a blood transfusion during the ordeal that  
began early Friday morning after a 2-1 victory over the Nashville 
Predators. Doctors are still doing tests to determine what caused 
the injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros is on numerous medications, including epogen, a hormone  
that stimulates bone marrow to produce red blood cells. Hartzell 
said Lindros' red blood count is increasing. But he acknowledged 
that Lindros can't begin to contemplate playing hockey until 
``virtually all'' of the red blood cells he lost are replenished. 
</P>
<P>
	``You do the math,'' Hartzell said. ``Three to four weeks, and  
then he has to have his conditioning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers, once considered a favorite to contend for the  
Stanley Cup, have been without Lindros and three other top players. 
John LeClair, Mark Recchi and Eric Desjardins have been cleared to 
play Thursday night against Pittsburgh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
