<HEADLINE>  Neil Armstrong Launches First Pitch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Neil Armstrong isn't much for public appearances,  
but the space pioneer made an exception for the start of the 
Astrodome's farewell baseball season. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, among 23 astronauts who simultaneously threw out  
ceremonial first pitches when the Astrodome opened April 12, 1965, 
did the job solo today before Houston's opener against the Chicago 
Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I called him, and he said, `I don't do public events,' ''  
Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. said. Armstrong, fiercely 
protective of his privacy in recent years, relented after McLane 
explained the historic significance of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	This will be club's 35th and final season in the Astrodome, the  
world's first indoor stadium. Next April, the Astros will move into 
a new retractable-roof ballpark downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	Acting as de facto spokesman for Armstrong, who rarely does  
interviews, McLane said Armstrong was a fixture at Colt .45s and 
Astros games when he lived in the area for eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	``He loved living in Houston. He had such a great experience  
living here,'' said McLane, who was host to the Ohio native in his 
field-level box. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong was escorted onto the field by Jimmy Wynn and Bob  
Aspromonte, members of the 1965 Astros. About 70 current astronauts 
lined both baselines while Armstrong waved twice to a standing 
ovation and delivered a one-hop pitch to Craig Biggio. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong will mark the 30th anniversary of his landmark moon  
walk July 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
