<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Austin School District Indicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- The Austin school district and a deputy  
superintendent have been indicted on charges of manipulating 
statewide test results in a scheme to boost school performance 
ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Parents in our district and throughout the state have a right  
to know the truth about their children's schools,'' prosecutor Ken 
Oden said Tuesday. ``The goal of our enforcement efforts is to see 
that the system is not covering up the truth to make itself look 
good while the students' needs are overlooked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oden said the indictments mark the first time in Texas history  
that criminal charges have been filed against a school district. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted of tampering with a government record, the Austin  
Independent School District could face fines of up to $160,000. The 
deputy superintendent, Margaret Kay Psencik, could face up to a 
year in jail, a $4,000 fine or both. 
</P>
<P>
	Her lawyer, Roy Minton, said she did nothing wrong.  
</P>
<P>
	``We'll certainly be ready to go to trial on this. The lady has  
not done a single thing that's a violation of any law, nor anything 
that's improper,'' Minton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation was launched in September after reports that  
student identification numbers were changed on some Texas 
Assessment of Academic Skills tests, which are used to rate and 
compare schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas Education Agency lowered some Austin schools' ratings  
after an audit suggested school officials changed the numbers of 
students who performed poorly on the test in order to raise 
ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	Oden said the district can be held legally liable for the  
criminal acts of its employees. He emphasized that the indictment 
didn't charge or imply personal wrongdoing by school board members. 
</P>
<P>
	``On behalf of the board of trustees, let me reiterate that we  
do not condone these behaviors which have brought us to this 
point,'' Superintendent A.C. Gonzalez said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
