<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ripken Misses Start Due to Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- After going 2,632 games without a day off, Cal  
Ripken is suddenly getting in the habit of watching from the 
dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since 1982, the Baltimore Orioles third  
baseman missed a game because of injury Wednesday. Saddled with a 
stiff lower back, Ripken decided it would be better to take a seat 
than to take a chance. 
</P>
<P>
	So he never picked up a bat and watched the Orioles lose to  
Tampa Bay 8-5. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second time in the Orioles' last 10 games Ripken  
failed to play. Last Sept. 20, he voluntarily ended his record 
consecutive games streak by sitting out Baltimore's final home game 
against the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, who left the Orioles' season opener Monday in the third  
inning with painful back spasms, began Wednesday night's game in 
the dugout while Willis Otanez took over at third base. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could beat my head against the wall and go do it today, but  
it doesn't make sense,'' Ripken said. ```We're going to just work 
toward being ready tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hours before the game, Ripken told manager Ray Miller that he  
wasn't quite 100 percent. So Miller decided to give Ripken the day 
off, even though he had already written the third baseman into the 
starting lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him I'd rather err on the side of caution and give him  
another 24 hours,'' Miller said. ``In my heart I know he never 
played a game just because of the streak. Fortunately for us it's 
not there anymore, so we can use a little better judgment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the streak were still alive, it probably would have come to a  
dramatic conclusion Wednesday night. Although Ripken's back felt a 
lot better than it did Monday, it was far from peak condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it was 90 percent, playing would be a no-brainer,'' he  
said. ``Every situation is different, but I doubt I'd play tonight 
regardless if the streak was still alive. ... I want to be able to 
contribute this whole season, and it wouldn't make sense to push it 
just to play one game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Ripken missed a game because of injury was on May  
3, 1982 after he got beaned by Seattle rookie Mike Moore. His 
record streak began later that month and survived two ankle 
injuries, a twisted knee and a herniated disc in his back in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	None of those ailments affected him the way his injury did  
Monday, when he was rendered helpless by stiffness, tightness and 
spasms in his lower back. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't consider myself superhuman. But I never reached a  
point where I couldn't play until the other day,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Otanez, meanwhile, was delighted to get his third major league  
start, but would have preferred it occurred under different 
circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice for me, I was happy to see I'm playing,'' he said.  
``But I don't want my teammate to get hurt like that. That's not 
good. I hope he gets well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Otanez hit his first major league homer and doubled in a 2-for-5  
night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
