<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sex Offenders Map Plan Under Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A plan to distribute maps that vaguely show  
where sex offenders live near elementary schools has triggered 
criticism from civil liberties activists who fear ex-cons could 
become targets of vigilantism and harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	Police in South Gate, a city of 87,000 southeast of Los Angeles,  
want to pass out the maps to children in 13 elementary schools. The 
maps are tailored for each school, with black dots showing the 
general location of the offenders' homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The fliers don't provide names or addresses.  
</P>
<P>
	Teachers expected to begin passing out the maps to students  
Tuesday. But the Los Angeles Unified School District, which 
presides over 10 of South Gate's grade schools, ordered teachers to 
hold off so administrators could review the fliers. 
</P>
<P>
	The map project is patterned after one in the Northern  
California city of Fremont. In 1997, about 80 elementary and junior 
high schools in that city's school district distributed similar 
maps to parents and students. Police there call their program 
``very successful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But critics say residents could use the fliers to harass or  
attack the sex offenders. They also say the maps are based on a 
state computer database of sex offenders plagued in the past with 
inaccurate information. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no guarantee that this map will be accurate the day  
after it's published, but you forever branded the home where that 
person previously lived,'' said Elizabeth Schroeder, associate 
director of the American Civil Liberties Union of Southern 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Megan's Law, Californians can learn from police the names  
and descriptions of nearly 64,000 convicted sex offenders living in 
their communities. The law is named for Megan Kanka, a 7-year-old 
New Jersey girl raped and strangled in 1994 by a twice-convicted 
sex offender. 
</P>
<P>
	Many states like California keep such information on a computer  
database accessible at computer terminals in police and sheriff's 
stations. 
</P>
<P>
	In Fremont, the maps prompted many parents to familiarize  
themselves with local molesters, although just one ``high-risk'' 
sex offender remains in the area, said Detective Dennis Madsen. 
</P>
<P>
	``It raised the interest of parents,'' he said. ``They lined up  
four or five hours to get onto that computer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Madsen said detectives check the map's accuracy, and there's  
little danger of vigilantism because the black dots represent an 
area too vague for possible harassment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
