<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hanford Contractors Sued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- Two contractors have been accused in a  
federal lawsuit of overcharging the Department of Energy by at 
least $85 million for cleanup work at the Hanford nuclear 
reservation. 
</P>
<P>
	Westinghouse Hanford Co. and Fluor Daniel Hanford Inc. used a  
computerized accounting scheme involving wages, according to the 
lawsuit filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court here. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department has not joined the suit filed by David  
Carbaugh, an accountant who worked for both contractors. Carbaugh 
claims his complaints to supervisors eventually led to his 
dismissal by Fluor. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit seeks $240 million in damages.  
</P>
<P>
	Hanford, built in 1943 as part of the secret World War II  
Manhattan Project, produced plutonium for the U.S. nuclear arsenal 
into the 1980s. The 560-square-mile Department of Energy site in 
southeastern Washington is considered the nation's most 
contaminated nuclear site. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit claims the contractors were allowed to bill the  
government 14 cents for every dollar paid workers in straight time, 
in order to cover vacation, sick time and holiday pay. However, 
they allegedly added the surcharge to overtime wages -- and used 
inflated labor costs to calculate pensions, benefits and general 
overhead. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Westinghouse said the charges were similar to  
ones Carbaugh filed in a 1996 lawsuit and were untrue. A spokesman 
for Fluor said the company was not aware of the suit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
