<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Washington, Jefferson and Gardening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SLEEPY HOLLOW, N.Y. (AP) -- George Washington as a profit-making  
whiskey distiller was a role you might not have suspected of the 
Father of Our Country. 
</P>
<P>
	Nor might you have known him for his Potomac River fishery or as  
the designer of a 16-sided barn where horses treaded wheat. This 
building was so unique it has now been recreated at Mount Vernon 
featuring daily shows of how it worked. 
</P>
<P>
	While Rip Van Winkle was sleeping here in legend, Washington was  
fighting Hudson River Valley battles. But his thoughts turned 
constantly to his Virginia plantation. His life as a farmer rather 
than soldier was re-enacted here in this 200th anniversary year of 
his death. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate lecture at historic Philipsburg Manor, Thomas  
Jefferson was hailed as a super gardener who said ``there's not a 
shoot of grass that springs uninteresting to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two presidents' ties to the good earth were evoked by Dennis  
Pogue, director of restoration at Mount Vernon, and Peter Hatch, 
director of gardens and grounds for Monticello, Jefferson's 
Virginia home. The lectures were sponsored by the Lyndhurst site of 
the National Trust for Historic reservation. 
</P>
<P>
	Pogue said Washington went into the whiskey business when his  
Scottish plantation master convinced him that a distillery would be 
very profitable. 
</P>
<P>
	``In fact, it was,'' Pogue said. ``In the first year of  
operation, they made over $7,000.'' That would be the equivalent of 
about $63,000 today. 
</P>
<P>
	His fishery on the river, a major enterprise, was one of  
Washington's most profitable operations, Pogue said. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington, who marketed grain broadly, decided to bring his  
wheat-threshing operation indoors to a specially-designed barn 
because both the weather and theft were causing him losses 
outdoors, Pogue said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the slave labor plantations of the Chesapeake area of that  
time, wheat was either flailed by hand or laid out in a large 
circle for horses to tread on it. The action of the hooves threshed 
out the grain. 
</P>
<P>
	Unhappy with the results outdoors, Washington built a barn with  
a floor on the second level large enough to accommodate horses. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington ``conceived the innovation of leaving spaces between  
the floorboards so that the grain would fall through to the granary 
below,'' Pogue said. ``There, it could be kept stored in bins and 
sent on to the mills to be ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That barn and other farm structures have been meticulously  
recreated at Mount Vernon as part of a $3 million project. The 
American lumber industry ``helped us come remarkably close to the 
kinds of wood used in Washington's time,'' Pogue said. (Online 
essays on the reconstruction are available on www. 
mountvernon.org). 
</P>
<P>
	Washington ``worked on his farms virtually every day,'' Pogue  
said. ``He would ride around all the different farms and inspect 
them and talk to the overseers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was very much a hands-on guy. All the time he was going out  
and marking trees that needed to be cut down or relocated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two days before he died in 1799, he had been marking trees and  
came down with strep throat that killed him, Pogue said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jefferson, long celebrated for his Monticello farming and  
gardening, was pictured in Hatch's lecture as seeing ``plants as a 
vehicle for social intercourse, as a way of relating to people. 
</P>
<P>
	``Throughout his gardening letters there is this sort of union  
of gardening and sociability, particularly in his letters to his 
daughters and granddaughter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole family would get together to plant tulip bulbs and  
hyacinth bulbs. Jefferson's job was to label the plants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch said Jefferson suggested adding gardening to the fine arts  
not as horticulture ``but as the art of embellishing grounds by 
fancy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``As a young man, he dreamed up futuristic and romantic grottos.  
He also had plans for cascading waterfalls and fish ponds.'' Hatch 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jefferson pictured flower seasons as acts in a play, the tulips  
doing their acts and receiving their applause, to be followed by 
the iris and then the lilies, Hatch said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Jefferson referred to the flowers themselves ``as being  
what he called the belles of the day, who after flowering retired 
to the more interesting office of reproducing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A great grower of vegetables and flowers, Jefferson also set out  
1,400 fruit trees in the south orchard alone, Hatch said. He 
explained that for most Americans before 1850 horticulture meant 
fruit growing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pioneers began planting their orchards before building their  
houses,'' he said. One reason was the importance of peach brandy 
and apple cider. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans began drinking the fruit rather than eating it,''  
Hatch said. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	George Bria retired from the AP in 1981 after 40 years that  
included coverage of World War II from Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
