<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft To Stay in Charlotte </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. on Tuesday rejected thoughts of  
moving its East Coast technical support center to South Carolina 
and will search for a new Charlotte site. 
</P>
<P>
	``Microsoft has decided it will look at real estate  
opportunities in North Carolina,'' company spokesman Dan Leach 
said. ``It was an exceptionally difficult decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Redmond, Wash.-based software giant said it planned to pick  
a site in the Charlotte area this summer and occupy new quarters by 
fall 2000 for its East Coast Product Support Center, which now 
employs nearly 1,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Leach refused to characterize Microsoft's plans as expansion.  
Gov. Jim Hunt's office said the company is searching for 325,000 
square feet of office space for expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's center is currently housed in five buildings near  
the Charlotte Coliseum. It is facing expiring leases and new 
product releases later this year, The Charlotte Observer reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Leach declined to specify South Carolina sites Microsoft had  
considered. He praised South Carolina's vision for developing the 
Interstate 77 corridor between Charlotte and Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's Charlotte employees were told of the decision at  
meetings Tuesday, Leach said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
