<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Real Estate Co. Settles ADA Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department announced Wednesday  
that a Toronto-based real estate company agreed to pay a nonprofit 
organization and the federal government $560,000 to settle a 
dispute alleging it discriminated against people with disabilities. 
</P>
<P>
	TrizecHahn has agreed to pay $550,000 to the EndDependence  
Center and $10,000 in civil penalties to the government, said 
Allison Nichol, deputy chief of the Justice Department's 
Disabilities Rights Section. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichol said the EndDependence Center, an independent living  
center for people with disabilities, filed a complaint against 
TrizecHahn last year for allegedly refusing to lease the 
organization space in its suburban Arlington, Va., building. 
</P>
<P>
	``They refused to negotiate with the center,'' Nichol said.  
``The reason was they didn't want people with disabilities in their 
building.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nichol said anecdotal evidence indicates groups who work with  
people with disabilities often have problems renting commercial 
space, but she said people are often hesitant to file complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes people don't know it's discrimination,'' she said.  
``It may be discrimination with a smile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the terms of the agreement reached Wednesday, TrizecHahn  
did not admit wrongdoing but promised not to discriminate when 
leasing space. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also agreed to instruct employees on the  
requirements of the Americans with Disabilities Act that pertain to 
the leasing of commercial real estate. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was an isolated incident. It in no way reflects  
TrizecHahn's corporate values or policies. In fact, the Department 
of Justice determined that their finding was not based on any 
pattern or practice of discrimination by our company, said Tabb 
Davis, a spokeswoman for the company. She said it made every effort 
to deal with the allegation quickly and to cooperate with the 
Department of Justice fully. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
