<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Macedonia Criticizes NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- Macedonian authorities early today  
emptied a border enclave where tens of thousands of Kosovo refugees 
had been trapped for days in squalid, chaotic conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia had been busing refugees out of the teeming Blace camp  
for days, but the pace was sharply stepped up late Tuesday and 
early today. Many of the Blace refugees, who had numbered in the 
tens of thousands the day before, were taken to NATO-run camps, but 
aid workers scrambled to track the others. 
</P>
<P>
	The fate of a miles-long line of ethnic Albanian refugees who  
had been waiting on the other side of Macedonia's frontier with 
Yugoslavia was not known, and there were fears they had been turned 
back to Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The move to swiftly empty the Blace (pronounced blah-TSAY)  
encampment came against a backdrop of growing tensions between 
Western aid and alliance officials and authorities in Macedonia, a 
former Yugoslav republic. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Macedonia's prime minister, Llubco Georgievski,  
criticized NATO as ``completely irresponsible'' for ignoring 
warnings that airstrikes on Yugoslavia could trigger a humanitarian 
disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations and other Western aid agencies, for their  
part, have accused Macedonia of using bureaucratic delays to slow 
the influx of both refugees and aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia, flooded with more than 130,000 refugees since the  
NATO bombing campaign against Yugoslavia began two weeks ago, has 
said it can take in 20,000 and wants the rest quickly shipped to 
other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonia fears the flood of refugees will destabilize its  
ethnic balance and lead to calls for Albanian autonomy in this 
country of 2.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Paramilitary police kept journalists at a distance today from  
what had been a sprawling encampment. All that remained at the site 
was a giant, smoldering pit, with garbage fires burning and muddy 
clothing and plastic sheeting strewn about. 
</P>
<P>
	Filthy, primitive conditions in the camp had led to an outbreak  
of illness and some deaths in recent days. Serbian troops and 
police have been accused of forcing the refugees out of their homes 
in Kosovo, sending many on arduous treks by foot to the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who made it into Macedonia said they believed people on  
the Yugoslav side of the border at Blace, where a line of waiting 
cars stretched for 6 miles, had been pushed back into Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``People saw them being turned back,'' said Rronn Qena, 20, a  
Kosovar painter who arrived at a NATO-run tent camp at Stankovac, a 
suburb of the Macedonian capital, Skopje. 
</P>
<P>
	An Associated Press Television News crew at another crossing,  
Jazince, saw empty Yugoslav buses waiting on the other side of the 
border, apparently preparing to transport refugees from the border 
back into Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Aid workers arriving early today at the emptied Blace site said  
they were trying to track where refugees had been taken. 
</P>
<P>
	Paula Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the U.N. refugee agency, said  
about 15,000 of the refugees from Blace had been taken to a transit 
camp near Macedonia's capital but officials were not sure what 
happened to the others. 
</P>
<P>
	In Albania, a spokesman for the Organization for Security and  
Cooperation in Europe, Andrea Angeli, said about 10,000 Kosovo 
refugees had been transported overnight from Macedonia into 
Albania. It was not known whether any were the same refugees taken 
from the Blace camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Western aid agencies, meanwhile, were looking into reports that  
Macedonia may be forcing Kosovo Albanians to leave the country in a 
Western-organized airlift. 
</P>
<P>
	Flights to Norway and Turkey that began Monday have carried out  
only a few thousand refugees. Another planeload of refugees landed 
in Norway today with 78 refugees, including about 20 children. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonian authorities also have apparently discouraged the  
reunion of any arriving ethnic Albanian refugees with relatives in 
Macedonia. Refugee Nebi Qena, 21, said he had family in the former 
Yugoslav republic, but his relatives had not been allowed to visit 
the camp where he was staying. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news release late Tuesday, the government hinted it would  
take steps to ensure any arrivals did not stay long. It said they 
would go directly to camps ``where they will be transferred to 
other countries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anti-NATO sentiment has been growing among Macedonian  
nationalists angry at both the airstrikes against fellow Orthodox 
Serbs and the refugee inflow. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO troops in Macedonia have been working day and night to set  
up nine tent cities to temporarily house refugees. The alliance 
said it had ferried into Macedonia more than 1,373 tons of aid, 
including 350 tons of food and water and 250 tons of tents and 
other supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Private and military aircraft were scheduled to begin flying  
Kosovo refugees today from Macedonia to Germany, which has promised 
to provide temporary shelter to 10,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
