<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 10:45:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baby I'm Only 'Society's Child' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cradling the huge guitar, she looked prim in her  
blue turtleneck, white A-line jumper that brushed the tops of her 
knees, black tights and low-heel, pointy-toe black pumps with 
buckles. Her long, dark curly hair was parted and tied back, as if 
to tame it. Then she let loose her dangerous song. 
</P>
<P>
	``Come to my door, baby. Face is clean and shining, black as  
night. ... She called you 'boy' instead of your name!'' Janis Ian's 
sweet, strong soprano achingly sang out that she was ``only 
society's child.'' After mom, teachers and friends let her know a 
white girl must not cherish a black boy, she was resigned: ``I 
don't want to see you anymore, baby.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This was no mere folk song. With her grief-stricken hymn to love  
crushed by bigotry, the white teen-ager indicted America for its 
racism and hypocrisy. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the 1960s, a time of race riots and civil rights  
struggles, and right before the U.S. Supreme Court struck down 
state laws that barred interracial marriage. The song brought a 
rash of hate mail and many radio stations would not play it. 
</P>
<P>
	But ``Society's Child'' also attracted more positive things.  
Leonard Bernstein, composer, conductor and music teacher to a 
nation expressed only awe when he presented Ian on national 
television April 25, 1967, in a CBS special, ``Inside Pop: The Rock 
Revolution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That voice! Those words! That key change!'' Bernstein gushed.  
``Oh Janis, how did you ever write such a thing at the age of 15? 
You're a great creature!'' Predicting ``a brilliant career,'' he 
delicately lifted her hand to his lips for a kiss. 
</P>
<P>
	This past January, on a chilly night sticky with fog, Janis Ian  
stood alone on the stage of a Jewish community center in Whippany, 
N.J. Deep in the suburbs 25 miles from New York City, she took 
another step in what has become one long, continuous comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, you look friendly,'' she said with a nervous smile.  
Gaunt and fragile-looking at 47, she was still recovering from 
surgery to excise a benign tumor from her liver. ``I haven't done a 
show in two months,'' she told the mostly fortysomething audience 
of 350. 
</P>
<P>
	The voice is deeper, and richer. In performance she drapes her 4  
feet 10 inches in an oversized black T-shirt that declares 
``Godlike'' in white letters. Underneath, she wears shiny black 
leggings and black high-heel sneakers. Her curly hair is short and 
brushed out to frame her somber, intense face. She breaks into a 
radiant grin only when the audience applauds -- and it's always 
huge, thundering applause. 
</P>
<P>
	Ian's audiences stretch over generations. Some come out of  
nostalgia; they bring their teen-agers and grandchildren. Others 
are just discovering her. 
</P>
<P>
	Still best known is her biggest hit, ``At Seventeen.'' Released  
in 1975, her frank reflection on adolescence has proved so durable 
and true, its wordsare still recited by gray-haired women and 
balding men: ``I learned the truth at 17, that love was meant for 
beauty queens ... those of us with ravaged faces, lacking in the 
social graces, desperately remained at home, inventing lovers on 
the phone, who called to say come dance with me. ... It isn't all 
it seems, at 17.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There have been many more songs, including tunes for TV  
commercials and movies. Writing words and music has been her only 
constant in a turbulent life. That, and her courage. She has walked 
away from fame, twice. She survived a suicide attempt, a stormy 
marriage and ugly divorce, frail health, the theft of her childhood 
guitar, financial ruin and her mother's slow death from multiple 
sclerosis. 
</P>
<P>
	And she started over in Nashville, Tenn., where she has found  
enduring love with another woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaking off a touch of rust on the high notes, Ian opened the  
Whippany show with ``This Train Still Runs'': ``It doesn't matter 
where it's gone, this train still runs. And though the baggage 
weighs a ton, we carry on. Nothing is forever young -- I'm not done. 
This train still runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Janis Ian was back.  
</P>
<P>
	Two days later she played Madison Square Garden, one of eight  
performers in a benefit concert for Zero Population Growth that 
included Jewel, Paula Cole, Odetta and Phoebe Snow. She got a 
standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	A few weeks later, she was back in New York City for the 25th  
anniversary show at The Bottom Line, a Greenwich Village relic from 
the folk scene heyday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be really happy if I could write songs the rest of my  
life, and do little concerts, and other people would record my 
songs,'' Ian said in an interview. Wearing dark sweat pants and a 
roomy shirt the color of lilacs, she sat on a chair in a hotel near 
Wall Street. Ruby-colored eyeglasses set off her brown eyes. Smoke 
from her pungent cigarettes -- a pricey brand free of additives -- 
drifted around the small, plain room. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite her Buddha-like composure, her conversation leapt  
between clipped replies and chatty streams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't need to be playing for 20,000 people,'' she said.  
``I'd be very happy to have another hit record. ... But I'm not 
going to spend the next 20 years spinning my wheels. ... This is a 
harsh business that I'm in, and it gets harsher every year. '' 
</P>
<P>
	Janis Ian was never society's child.  
</P>
<P>
	Born Janis Fink, a granddaughter of Russian immigrants, she  
spent her first years on the New Jersey chicken farm where her 
father grew up and worked until he became a music teacher. Her 
parents were patriotic Americans and fervent socialists, agitating 
for equality, whether it was voting rights or fair wages. Their 
activities filled FBI files. As a result, she said, her father was 
denied tenure in public schools and they moved a lot. 
</P>
<P>
	Brave and single-minded, at age 2 1/2 she connected her father to  
the sound coming from their piano when he played ``Clair de Lune.'' 
She wanted lessons. Her father insisted she first learn the 
alphabet, count to 10 and tell time. Piano lessons led to the 
organ, flute and French horn. 
</P>
<P>
	Even her name had to be her own making. She discarded Fink, for  
the middle name of her younger brother, Eric. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 she picked up her father's guitar, a battered Martin D-18  
he had bought in 1948 from a farmer's widow for $25. In a few years 
her song, ``Hair of Spun Gold,'' was published in the folk magazine 
Broadside. 
</P>
<P>
	Living in East Orange, N.J., she was part of a small white  
minority when she wrote ``Society's Child.'' It wasn't 
autobiographical or based on anyone she knew, just her response to 
a world in social agony. It grabbed the attention of a record 
producer in New York City, where she had become a regular on the 
folk scene. He put ``Society's Child'' out as a single. 
</P>
<P>
	By now she was a sophomore at New York's competitive High School  
of Music &AMP; Art. But she quit when she turned 16. ``It wasn't for 
me. I don't like organizations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heroes like Paul Revere were her standard. Her parents  
encouraged their daughter's spirit and potential. She credits them 
with her self-confidence, and with the honesty of her songs. 
</P>
<P>
	They ``never punished me for telling the truth, no matter how  
awful it was. I was punished for lying -- and you can't be a hero 
and lie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That honesty, its eloquence and depth may be her chief legacy to  
contemporary music. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, as a writer, I have very meager strengths,'' she said.  
``I don't write great choruses. I don't have the gift of an Irving 
Berlin, you know, to just write something that everyone can sing. I 
don't have the gift for simplicity of a lot of country writers I 
know have. But I do honesty really well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By the time she fell under Leonard Bernstein's adoring gaze, she  
had begun touring. From ``The Tonight Show'' to Time magazine she 
was a sensation. Her debut album, ``Janis Ian,'' won the first of 
seven Grammy Award nominations. 
</P>
<P>
	There were also hard lessons, and frightening, ugly moments. She  
was 16 and playing Escondido, Calif., whena group in the audience 
screamed racial obscenities. Upset, she left the stage. The 
promoter found her crying in the bathroom. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, 'I'm not going back out there.' ... And the promoter  
looked at me and said, 'You've got to go back out there. If you 
don't go back out, they've won.' '' She went back on stage and 
picked up where she left off. 
</P>
<P>
	Making her solitary way in the world cost heavily, though. At 17  
she suffered a nervous breakdown and attempted suicide with pills. 
Her parents were getting a divorce, she was having difficulties 
with the record producer. She checked out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to go to sleep 'til it was over and then wake up  
different. I think that's what most kids who try that want. You 
don't want to die, you just want things to stop for a while, until 
you can cope with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In psychotherapy, she began to pull herself together, almost  
literally. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until then I was all these different people: I was this  
songwriter. I was this hero to a generation. I was this publicity 
machine. I was this recording artist. I was this kid on TV. I was 
my parents' daughter, I was my brother's sister, I was my 
boyfriend's girlfriend. It was all very confusing.'' Therapy helped 
her integrate all those facets of her life. 
</P>
<P>
	She had given much of her money to charity and needy friends.  
``When you're that young, you figure you could always make more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Broke, barely out of her teens and already washed up, she was  
living with her mother when she read a New York Times article about 
a debutante. It began, she recalls, ``I learned the truth at 18.'' 
The result several months later was the autobiographical ``At 
Seventeen.'' Her first comeback was about to begin. 
</P>
<P>
	Her early 20s produced three popular albums: ``Stars'' (1973),  
with the ballad ``Jesse,'' later a hit for Roberta Flack; ``Between 
the Lines'' (1975), which featured ``At Seventeen''; and 
``Aftertones'' (1976). 
</P>
<P>
	``At Seventeen'' sold more than 1 million copies and earned a  
Grammy for best pop vocal performance of 1975. It also got her a 
spot on the inaugural ``NBC's Saturday Night'' -- later renamed 
``Saturday Night Live'' -- her sober songs an odd if moving contrast 
to the wackiness of George Carlin, John Belushi, Dan Aykroyd and 
Jane Curtin. 
</P>
<P>
	Based at various times in Los Angeles, Philadelphia and New  
York, through much of the 1970s she lived out of suitcases, touring 
the world and pouring out albums. She fell in love with a longtime 
friend and married in 1978, hoping to raise a family. 
</P>
<P>
	Then in 1982, ending a tour in South Africa, she took a break.  
No records. No shows. Then the troubles started. The hiatus would 
lapse into a decade. Janis Ian vanished. 
</P>
<P>
	She studied acting, ballet and piano. But this was also when her  
marriage soured, ending in divorce after a decade. And suspicion 
that she couldn't bear children was confirmed; the cause was 
massive fibroids, and at 35 she had a hysterectomy. 
</P>
<P>
	Her former accountant, now dead, had stopped paying her taxes in  
1979, and the IRS caught up with her in 1986. At the time, Ian was 
hospitalized in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., with a burst intestine. The 
IRS shut down her bank accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Good in business, she had made lucrative real estate buys and  
smart stock market investments. The problem was being on the road 
10 months of the year, leaving someone else to pay bills. 
</P>
<P>
	She owed the IRS $1.2 million, New York State $350,000, debts  
she finally paid off last year. It meant liquidating what she 
could, selling instruments and even rights to her songs. And 
slowly, she laid the ground for another comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	Ready for a spell of composing, she was living in Los Angeles in  
1986 when a music publisher recommended Nashville. The town teems 
with professional songwriters and this folk artist with a jazzy 
bent found there a haven of kindred artists. Two years later, she 
made the move permanent. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's made me a lot simpler, made me a lot cleaner writer, less  
inclined to go off and wander,'' she said of her new hometown. 
``It's forced me to develop my craft.'' In that Southern city, 
she's ``just another grunt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nashville was also where 10 years ago she met her love, Pat  
Snyder. The warm, quiet and witty redhead offered company with 
chess games when Ian was emerging from a six-month bout of chronic 
fatigue syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon they moved in together. Ian put Snyder, a former university  
archivist, through law school, just as she paid for the education 
of her mother, Pearl Yadoff, who in middle-age earned undergraduate 
and graduate degrees from Goddard College. She died in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Once Ian was back on her feet, albums and concerts followed  
early in this decade. She counts 300 songs to her credit. She's 
also been branching out. 
</P>
<P>
	She gives master classes to college musicians. Venturing into  
prose, she become a columnist, first for a gay magazine, The 
Advocate, and now for a trade journal, The Professional Songwriter. 
She has a website, and a company, Rude Girl Inc., that sells her 
songbook and T-shirts and imports her CDs from Europe to sell at 
lower cost. As she turned 48 on April 7, she was in Los Angeles 
recording her 17th album, for Windham Hill Records. 
</P>
<P>
	And she got her Martin D-18 back.  
</P>
<P>
	The venerable 1937 guitar on which she wrote ``Society's Child''  
and ``Jesse,'' the instrument she used to wow Leonard Bernstein, 
was stolen from her apartment soon after she moved to Los Angeles 
in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	She posted wanted notices on her albums. Then last year, an  
e-mail arrived. A guitar shop in California had a customer. The 
customer had her guitar, identified by its serial number. He had 
bought it from a store in Berkeley, Calif., 26 years earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, she seldom lets the guitar out of sight. ``It sleeps in  
the bedroom with me,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	With her life in a pleasant equilibrium, Ian spends mornings  
doing business, afternoons writing. For fun she reads, and watches 
``King of the Hill'' and ``The X-Files.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And she contemplates taking new, bold directions and satisfying  
old hankerings, like performing at Radio City Music Hall, nailing a 
writing gig at Time or Newsweek or starting her autobiography. And 
then there's her dream of teaming with Paul McCartney or Billy 
Joel. 
</P>
<P>
	Janis Ian once thanked her mother for indulging her daughter's  
ambition for stardom and fame. Her mother replied: ``We had no 
choice. Nothing would have stopped you.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
