<HEADLINE> Ark. Toughens Law on Child Killers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Youngsters convicted of murder could  
now face life in prison under a new state law passed in response to 
last year's deadly school shooting in Jonesboro. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Mike Huckabee signed the measure on Wednesday. Under the  
new law, children of any age who are convicted of first-degree 
murder can receive adult punishment, including life in prison, but 
not the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	State law previously protected children under 14 from facing  
adult punishment. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of that, Mitchell Johnson, then 13, and Andrew Golden,  
then 11, were sentenced to a juvenile detention center for the 
Jonesboro shootings and must be released by the time they turn 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Four students and a teacher were killed in the March 24, 1998,  
shootings at Westside Middle School. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
