<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Guard El-Amin To Return to UConn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Khalid El-Amin is passing up a shot at  
the NBA draft and will reurn for his junior year, hoping to lead 
Connecticut to another national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-foot-10 point guard helped the Huskies (36-2) to their  
first national championship with a 77-74 victory over Duke last 
week. It was the school's first trip to the Final Four in 21 tries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think doing it a second time would be even better,'' El-Amin  
said. ``I want to come back and try to relive the great memories 
and experiences we all shared in the recent NCAA championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very interested in playing with a different group of guys  
... and helping introduce them to the highest level of college 
basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the past three years, the end of basketball season has meant  
decision time for the portly sophomore from Minneapolis, a married 
man with two children. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jim Calhoun said the extra year will allow El-Amin to  
further develop. 
</P>
<P>
	``Khalid obviously played a major role in our national  
championship journey,'' Calhoun said. ``I believe he will enjoy an 
even more dynamic year as he expands his wonderful leadership 
qualities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scoring leader Richard Hamilton still was considering whether to  
return for his senior year. 
</P>
<P>
	``He gave me no indication about any kind of announcement  
anytime soon,'' Calhoun said. ``He's enjoying the fruits of his 
accomplishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	El-Amin has been a starter in 71 games and became the third  
UConn player to reach 1,000 points as a sophomore. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past two seasons, he has averaged 14.9 points and 4.1  
assists. He finished second on the team this season in scoring at 
13.8 points a game and led the squad in assists with 140. 
</P>
<P>
	El-Amin was placed on the Final Four all-tournament team after  
scoring 30 points and dishing out 10 assists in victories over Ohio 
State in the semifinals and Duke in the title game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
