<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Utility Barred From Seeking Damages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge has blocked a major Midwestern  
utility from seeking potentially huge civil damages from the 
federal government for not taking its commercial nuclear reactor 
waste. 
</P>
<P>
	While the case involved only the Northern States Power Co. in  
Minnesota, government and industry representatives acknowledged 
Wednesday it could influence similar cases involving other 
utilities seeking billions of dollars from the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge John P. Wiese of the U.S. Court of Federal Claims ruled  
that Northern States should pursue its claim administratively by 
seeking an adjustment in its contract with the Energy Department, 
not through a civil suit seeking damages. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department has refused to transfer nearly 40,000 tons  
of reactor waste now at power plants in 34 states, although it 
agreed years ago to begin to accept such waste. The industry has 
claimed the refusal could lead to as much as $56 billion in damage 
claims as a result of civil litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	But Wiese, in a 24-page opinion issued late Tuesday and made  
public on Wednesday, said that while the department may be 
obligated to accept the waste, any compensation for its delays 
should be pursued ``thorough the administrative remedies 
established in the standard contract'' with the Energy Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Northern States was among four utilities that sought about $4  
billion in damages from the federal government because it has 
refused to deal with the waste problem. The cases of the other 
three -- Florida Power &AMP; Light, Duke Power and Indiana-Michigan 
Power -- remain to be decided. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiese's ruling contradicts a ruling by another judge in the U.S.  
Court of Federal Claims last year involving three closed New 
England reactors. In that case the judge said the reactor owners 
could pursue a court claim, although no monetary amount was 
stipulated. The New England utilities have sought $268 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department had no comment on Wiese's decision,  
although senior department officials privately welcomed the ruling 
and were optimistic it might foreshadow similar rulings in the 
other pending cases. Dozens of utilities have been watching the 
early cases to determine whether they too should file claims. 
</P>
<P>
	``The court now has decided we are interpreting the contract and  
its provisions correctly,'' said one DOE official, speaking on 
condition he not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Silberg, the attorney for Northern States Power, said no  
decision had been made on whether to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were not surprised, although disappointed. We're evaluating  
what our next step will be,'' said Silberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Government lawyers said the Northern States decision was  
significant in that it was the first one involving operating 
reactors whose owners are continuing to pay into a federal nuclear 
waste disposal fund. The New England case involved three reactors 
that were already shut down. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department had argued any claim of damages should be  
resolved by reducing payments into the federal waste fund -- an 
approach Wiese endorsed in his legal opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, another federal court ruled that the government need  
not take the waste until it has a safe place to put it, but also 
gave a green light for utilities to file claims with the court of 
claims for breach of contract. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1982, Congress assured utilities that the government would  
find a central storage site for spent reactor fuel and begin 
accepting the waste by 1998. The deadline passed, but the 
government is not expected to have a central waste storage facility 
until 2010 at the earliest. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
