<HEADLINE> Explosion Rocks Lab at San Jose St. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- A chemical explosion rocked a laboratory  
at San Jose State University Wednesday morning, injuring six 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	The explosion happened shortly after 11 a.m. when two or three  
students doing a chemical experiment poured nitric acid into a 
beaker with ethanol residue in it, said Fire Chief Rob Piper. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not a chemist. All I can tell you is, when they're mixed  
together they go boom!'' Piper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Six people were exposed to chemicals and flying glass, including  
the students' instructor. Five were taken to a hospital for minor 
cuts and chemical exposure. The instructor was treated at the 
scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Piper said damage was confined to the classroom and no  
environmental problems were anticipated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
