<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Noted Jazz Musician Red Norvo Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Red Norvo, who performed with such  
greats as Charles Mingus and Frank Sinatra and is credited with 
introducing the xylophone to jazz, has died. He was 91. 
</P>
<P>
	Norvo died Tuesday at the Fireside Convalescent Home, grandson  
Aaron Corlin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a fabulous man,'' Corlin said. ``He was always thinking  
about music, it was his life. ... His position in jazz history says 
a lot for itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Born Kenneth Norville in Beardstown, Ill., he taught himself how  
to play piano and xylophone. By age 17, he was touring with a 
vaudeville show and later joined the Paul Ash Orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
	His last name changed to Norvo after Ash mispronounced it to a  
reporter and Norvo's manager decided the shorter name was more 
fitting. 
</P>
<P>
	During Norvo's tenure with Paul Whiteman's Orchestra, which he  
joined in 1932, he met singer Mildred Bailey, whom he later 
married. By 1935, he formed his own sextet that played in clubs on 
New York City's 52nd Street. 
</P>
<P>
	In subsequent years, Norvo and his wife, who were known as ``Mr.  
and Mrs. Swing,'' formed several groups in New York and Chicago. 
Among their hits in the 1930s were ``Rockin' Chair,'' ``Please Be 
Kind,'' ``Says My Heart'' and ``Have You Forgotten So Soon?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1943, he switched from xylophone to vibraphone, which he  
played almost exclusively for the rest of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1945, Norvo joined the Benny Goodman orchestra, and a year  
later played with Woody Herman's orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
	He returned to leading his own small groups, forming a trio in  
1950 that included Tal Farlow on guitar and Mingus on bass. He also 
toured and appeared on television with Sinatra. 
</P>
<P>
	Norvo continued to perform through the early 1990s, when he  
suffered a stroke that ended his public performances. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bailey, whose likeness was featured on a 1996 U.S. postage  
stamp, died in 1951. Norvo later married Eve Rogers, who died in 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides his grandson, Norvo is survived by his daughter, Portia.  
Funeral arrangements were pending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 01:52:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Chiquita Lawyer on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A reporter who promised to protect the  
identity of a source at the Chiquita banana company is legally 
bound to keep that agreement, according to the source himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for George G. Ventura made the argument Tuesday to try  
to prevent two former reporters for The Cincinnati Enquirer from 
linking him to the illegal intrusion into Chiquita's internal 
voice-mail system. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense is trying to persuade a judge to throw out all 10  
felony charges against Ventura, a former lawyer for Chiquita Brands 
International Inc. who is now in private practice in Salt Lake 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Ann Marie Tracey didn't say when she will decide.  
</P>
<P>
	Ventura has pleaded innocent to unlawful interception of  
communications and unauthorized access to computer systems. He 
could get 12 1/2 years in prison if convicted. His trial begins July 
6. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the former Enquirer reporters identified Ventura in court  
this week as a source -- and the attorney's lawyers referred to the 
disclosure Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	They argued that a reporter who promises anonymity to a source  
has effectively entered into a legally binding contract that 
protects the source against being exposed later by the reporter, 
even under pressure of prosecution. They said Ohio's shield law, 
which allows reporters to protect the identities of confidential 
sources, also protects the sources. 
</P>
<P>
	``If one (reporter) decides he is going to become an arm of the  
prosecutor and divulge the identity of a confidential source, then 
he has done journalism a tremendous disservice, because then no 
confidential source is ever going to cooperate with a reporter 
again,'' said Marc Mezibov, a lawyer for Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Breyer, the prosecutor, said he saw no reason to legally  
protect the identity of sources. He said that could have the effect 
of releasing sources from any accountability for their actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters Michael Gallagher and Cameron McWhirter relied on the  
voice mail messages in an Enquirer package of stories last May 
accusing Cincinnati-based Chiquita of improper dealings in Central 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, the Enquirer fired Gallagher, apologized on its front  
page to Chiquita and said it was paying Chiquita more than $10 
million to settle any claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher pleaded guilty in September to felony charges and is  
awaiting sentencing that could range from 2 1/2 years in prison to 
probation. 
</P>
<P>
	McWhirter has not been charged and now works for The Detroit  
News. He has said he did not access Chiquita's system but got codes 
from a source and gave them to Gallagher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:05:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gambling Commission Prepares Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Members of a federal panel studying gambling  
seem largely united against ``convenience gambling'' -- via the 
Internet, or on slot machines in supermarkets -- and against slot 
machines at racetracks, bars and food stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Six members of the nine-member National Gambling Impact Study  
Commission attending a meeting here Wednesday seemed to agree on an 
overriding goal: to maintain gambling as a destination activity -- a 
reason to travel to places like Las Vegas or Atlantic City. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are wide divisions among commission members on the  
overall tone of the report they are drafting for Congress, the 
president, state governments and tribal governments on the economic 
and social impacts of legalized gambling. After two years of work, 
they face a June 18 deadline to submit that report. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner John Wilhelm, general president of the Hotel  
Employees and Restaurant Employees Union, said the theme should be 
informational -- what is known about the effects of gambling 
expansion and what should be monitored. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe a prohibitionist view of gambling is not going to  
work,'' Wilhelm said. ``History demonstrates that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But commissioner Richard Leone, a former state treasurer of New  
Jersey, said the report should acknowledge that the nation is ``on 
a slippery slope'' that could bring gambling outlets to every 
neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would not be surprised,'' Leone said, ``if a commission  
(studying gambling) in 20 years has to deal with franchise wars, 
between 'McGambling' and 'TGIGambling.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The two-day meeting that began Wednesday was billed as a session  
of the panel's three-member report subcommittee. But with the 
commission nearing its final report, six of the nine commissioners 
showed up. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioners reached some consensus regarding pari-mutuel  
betting -- betting on horse and dog racing and jai-alai -- that 
betting from home is a problem and that 21 should be the minimum 
age to wager at tracks, up from 18 in some states. 
</P>
<P>
	On state lotteries, commissioners generally agreed that states  
should spend more on addiction treatment and education programs, 
that lotteries should not branch into ``casino-type activities'' 
such as video poker, that advertising should be restrained and that 
lotteries should examine whether their marketing targets poor 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	As for casinos, commissioners voiced concern about the easy  
availability of credit and alcohol to gamblers. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's topics include Internet gambling, advertising, Indian  
gambling, compulsive gambling, gambling by minors, economic 
development and crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not making final conclusions,'' cautioned commission  
chairwoman Kay James. ``We are having a discussion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The discussion often returned to arguments over federalism --  
what power Washington should yield, and what authority states 
should retain. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilhelm said the report should make clear that federal oversight  
is limited to tribal and Internet gaming, and that states control 
lotteries and commercial casinos. 
</P>
<P>
	Also arguing against an increased role for Washington was  
William Bible, former chairman of the Nevada gaming control board, 
who said the federal government has ``absolutely abrogated (its) 
responsibility'' over Indian gaming. 
</P>
<P>
	But Leone took a more skeptical view toward states, saying they  
are predominantly concerned with blocking organized crime and 
making sure their treasuries get a fair share of gambling revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
