<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Cypriot Hopes To Free US Servicemen  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. officials indicated that NATO bombing of  
Belgrade would cease long enough tomorrow to allow a Cypriot leader 
to fly in with the hope of bringing back the three U.S. soldiers 
held by Yugoslavia. Earlier, a pentagon spokesman said NATO would 
not stop its current operations because of the effort by Cypriot 
parliament leader Spyros Kyprianou to gain the release of the 
servicemen. But he said, ``We have total control of the operations 
and certainly if it's necessary to have an aircraft fly into an 
area or out of an area at any time, that could be arranged.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Seals Off Kosovo Borders  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav authorities sealed off  
Kosovo's main border crossings today, preventing ethnic Albanians 
refugees from leaving. The main exit route was closed without 
explanation, forcing tens of thousands of people back toward the 
burned villages they had been escaping. More than 400,000 refugees 
have already been forced to flee to neighboring countries. 
Meanwhile, NATO intensified its airstrikes, announcing the ``first 
major breakthrough against armored forces in the field'' in 
Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Premier, Clinton To Meet  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji was meeting  
President Clinton tonight in the White House residence for an 
informal chat. Zhu arrived here today for two days of talks on 
security issues, trade, Taiwan and other subjects. He is expected 
to register China's differences with the United States on NATO's 
air war in Yugoslavia. Zhu also hopes to close a deal with the 
Clinton administration to allow Beijing to join the World Trade 
Organization. 

</P>
<P>
	Rwanda Marks Genocide Anniversary  
</P>
<P>
	KIBEHO, Rwanda (AP) -- Today, Rwandan leaders, religious  
officials and foreign diplomats concluded a week of national 
mourning in commemoration of 1994 genocide. More than half a 
million minority Tutsis and politically moderate Hutus were killed 
during the 90-day slaughter, which was carefully planned by the 
extremist Hutu government. At a ceremonial reburial of the remains 
of some of the victims, President Pasteur Bizimungu called on 
Rwanda to unite in condemning the genocide and ensure that it does 
not happen again. 

</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! Profits Soar  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Yahoo! Inc. today reported a first-quarter  
profit nearly five times higher than in the same period a year ago. 
Yahoo's profit of more than of $16 million, as compared to $3.3 
million in the first quarter of 1998, beat Wall Street forecasts. 
Yahoo! is one of the few Internet companies that actually makes 
money. 

</P>
<P>
	Witness Blames Talk Show for Death  
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- A psychiatrist testifying today in a $50  
million wrongful death lawsuit blamed ``The Jenny Jones Show'' for 
the death of a gay guest who revealed a secret crush on another 
man. Jonathan Schmitz confessed to shooting Scott Amedure in 1995 
three days after taping the show. Dr. Bernard Carroll, who 
testified for Amedure's family, said he thought the show deceived 
Schmitz, whom he said suffered from mental illnesses. Amedure's 
family sued the show and its producer, Warner Bros., claiming they 
ambushed a mentally ill Schmitz. 

</P>
<P>
	1998 Russian Alcohol Deaths: 23,986  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Alcohol poisoning killed 23,986 Russians last  
year, the highest figure in a decade, a news report said today. The 
chief epidemiological inspectorate of the Health Ministry compiled 
the numbers of deaths from alcohol poisoning, or drinking a lethal 
amount in one sitting. The inspectorate said the figure was the 
highest in 10 years, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. The Health 
Ministry estimates up to 10 million of Russia's 148 million people 
are alcoholics. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Open Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks opened mixed on Thursday. The  
Nikkei Stock Average fell 2 points to 16,552.50 early on. In New 
York Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 121.82 points 
to close at 10,085.31. That eclipsed the previous high of 10,007.33 
hit Monday. 

</P>
<P>
	Slumping Knicks Fall to the Hornets  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C.(AP) -- The New York Knicks lost for the third  
consecutive time and the eighth time in 12 games, falling to the 
Charlotte Hornets 106-82 tonight. Wesley finished with 24 points 
and seven assists as the Hornets broke a five-game losing skid. The 
Hornets shot 64 percent in the first half and wound up at 58 
percent, the highest figure allowed this season by the Knicks. 

</P>
<P>
	Mariners' Rodriguez Out 4-6 Weeks  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez will miss 4-6  
weeks with torn cartilage in his left knee, becoming the latest 
star to be sidelined this season. Rodriguez, 23, will undergo 
surgery tomorrow. Rodriguez hit .310 last season with 42 home runs 
and 46 stolen bases. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
