<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Virtual Life: Jack Nicklaus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With the latest Jack Nicklaus signature computer  
golf game, the Golden Bear knocks it stiff. 
</P>
<P>
	After years spent trailing its golf simulator nemesis ``Links,''  
which stars perennial Nicklaus rival Arnold Palmer, ``Jack Nicklaus 
Presents: Golden Bear Challenge'' is finally competing for a top 
spot on the leaderboard. 
</P>
<P>
	It is no small feat. Going after ``Links'' means taking the  
computer golf sim to a new level. 
</P>
<P>
	``Golden Bear,'' the sixth Nicklaus digital golf game, makes its  
move by vastly improving player graphics, the addition of 
customizing features that accent individual skills and spicing up 
the somewhat stagnant genre with irreverent commentary from 
wisecracking TV golf analyst Gary McCord. 
</P>
<P>
	There are new shot options, enhanced virtual golf ball physics  
and an unobtrusive yet handy interface that combine to bring added 
realism and ease of play to computer golf. 
</P>
<P>
	In perhaps the game's most significant new feature, players can  
assign skill points to various aspects of golf play: power, 
accuracy, the short game shots, sand play and putting. The number 
of skill points available to a player depends on the difficulty 
level he or she chooses. 
</P>
<P>
	Players can step into Nicklaus' shoes and play as the living  
legend, or they can play against him. There are also several other 
player animations to choose from, allowing players to choose a 
gender, body type and ethnicity. 
</P>
<P>
	Graphics quality stands out as another major improvement,  
including superb shimmering water hazards and flocks of birds 
flying out of trees hit by stray shots. It's all achieved through 
software, so having one of the latest 3-D video accelerators isn't 
required. 
</P>
<P>
	Game play can be viewed through a wide array of cameras,  
mimicking the many perspectives offered by televised golf coverage. 
Picture-in-picture setups can be modified at will, creating 
interesting possibilities like joining close-up and overhead views. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet play is supported, so people can arrange matches on the  
World Wide Web and compete via modem. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broadcast booth with McCord, the colorful former pro with  
a handlebar mustache, is stalwart CBS colleague Jim Nantz. Both 
evaluate play during games. 
</P>
<P>
	McCord, the teacher chosen to prepare Kevin Costner for his role  
in ``Tin Cup,'' isn't all fun and games, though. Good shots bring 
comments like telling players their ``swing should be hung in The 
Louvre,'' while bad shots bring remarks like ``call the coroner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The game features only courses designed by Nicklaus, whose  
renowned course architecture skills, on display all over the world, 
rival his playing prowess. The five offerings include Muirfield 
Village, site of the annual Memorial Golf Tournament, Shoal Creek, 
which was host to the PGA Championship in 1990, and the Cochise 
Course at Desert Mountain, home of The Tradition, a senior tour 
major tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Rounding out the offerings are Sherwood Country Club, site of  
the annual Greg Norman Shark Shootout, Sherry Montecastillo in 
Spain, where the Volvo Masters is played, and Nicklaus North in 
Whistler, British Columbia, site of the 1997 Canadian Skins Game. 
</P>
<P>
	Like previous Nicklaus games, the new version has a built-in  
course designer, a unique feature giving players the chance to 
create their own playable cyberspace layouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite relatively minor problems like somewhat slow graphics  
loading and often misleading putting information on the greens, 
Nicklaus wins this round, just as the Golden Bear did many times 
during his long rivalry with Palmer. Other digital golf contenders, 
including the highly touted ``Tiger Woods '99,'' don't even come 
close. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jack Nicklaus Presents: Golden Bear Challenge'' (Activision,  
CD-ROM for Windows95-98, $49.95) is as gifted as its namesake, 
pushing the envelope in an overcrowded sports software genre by 
taking dead aim and refusing to leave anything in the bag. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
