<DOCNO> APW19990407.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 03:35:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Snow was falling today in the southern Sierra Nevada, while an  
area of low pressure spread rain across New England. The central 
United States was mostly dry. 
</P>
<P>
	The rain in the Northeast should clear as the system moves  
offshore, but winds should remain gusty, exceeding 40 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	To the south, a few showers and thunderstorms were possible from  
the Carolinas into central Florida. Otherwise, the rest of the East 
Coast should be partly cloudy and dry. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain and higher elevation snow was expected from the central  
Rockies into the deserts of the Southwest. Most of the snow should 
fall above 6000 feet, where 4-8 inches were possible. 
</P>
<P>
	To the north and west, a cold front should deliver afternoon  
rain and mountain snow in the Pacific Northwest. The rain should 
spread into the lower elevations of Washington and Oregon by 
sunset. 
</P>
<P>
	Partly cloudy skies and dry weather were forecast for the  
northern Rockies, as well as in central California. 
</P>
<P>
	A weak disturbance may bring a few rain showers to northern  
portions of Wisconsin and Michigan. Elsewhere in the central United 
States, a few afternoon thunderstorms were possible in Oklahoma and 
Texas. The rest of the region should remain partly cloudy and dry. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature in the continental United States on  
Tuesday was 91 degrees at Fort Myers, Fla. The low was 10 at 
Flagstaff, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast to reach the 30s and 40s in the higher  
elevations of the Rockies and the Northwest; 50s and 60s in 
California, the Northeast, the Great Lakes and northern Plains; 60s 
and 70s in the Southwest; and 70s and 80s in the Southeast and 
southern Plains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
