<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Frederick W. Carr    	
</P>
<P>
	CLAREMONT, N.H. (AP) -- Frederick W. Carr, a World War II pilot  
and prisoner of war, died Monday at age 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Carr enlisted in the Army Air Corps when he turned 21 and then  
joined the 8th Army Air Force, 489th Bomber Group and the 846th 
Squadron, flying out of England. 
</P>
<P>
	On June 25, 1944, while flying his 18th mission, Carr was shot  
down near Gisors, France. He survived, and the French Underground 
hid him in Etrepagney, providing him with false identity papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Carr worked for a time in the laboratory of E.J. Hugel, mayor of  
Etrepagney and a leader in the underground. But during an attempt 
to escape occupied territory and rejoin the Allied Forces, he was 
captured by the Gestapo. 
</P>
<P>
	He was incarcerated in Fresnes Prison in Paris, then sent to the  
Buchenwald concentration camp in Germany. After four months, he was 
transferred to a prisoner of war camp in Poland, Stalag Luft III. 
</P>
<P>
	With other prisoners, he walked 500 miles to Munich to be  
liberated by U.S. Gen. George Patton on April 27, 1945. He later 
testified at the Nuremberg trials of Nazi war criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	Carr, who left the Air Force with the rank of captain, later  
became a high school principal. 

</P>
<P>
                          *H. Donald Loucks    	
</P>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- H. Donald Loucks, who coached Florida  
State's first men's basketball team in 1947, died Tuesday of heart 
failure. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Loucks also coached tennis for several years at the university  
beginning in 1947, the year Florida State College for Women became 
the coeducational Florida State University. 
</P>
<P>
	His basketball team finished the inaugural 1947-48 season 5-13.  
That was the only year he coached the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Loucks, who also served as dean of men, retired from teaching  
physical education in 1980 and became a member of FSU's Hall of 
Fame in 1985. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Michael Manuel    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Michael Manuel, a director and writer who worked  
with the Metropolitan Opera for a decade, died Monday of lung 
cancer. He was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in London, Manuel briefly attended the Royal Academy of  
Music in 1928. Twenty years later he joined the Royal Opera 
company, Covent Garden, as an assistant stage manager. Within three 
years he was stage manager for the Royal Ballet. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the Met in 1957 as executive stage manager, and  
directed Gluck's ``Orfeo and Eurydice'' and ``Alcestis,'' and 
Strauss' ``Elektra.'' In 1964 Manuel was appointed co-general 
manager of the Metropolitan Opera National Company, which played 
240 performances in 72 cities in its first season. 
</P>
<P>
	Manuel left the Met after the company's dissolution following  
its second season, and became a researcher and scriptwriter for the 
``New Media Bible'' and other educational television and video 
productions. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Robert B. Miller Sr.    	
</P>
<P>
	BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) -- Robert B. Miller Sr., who served as  
publisher of the Battle Creek Enquirer and News for 27 years, died 
Tuesday at age 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller was in the newspaper business for 50 years and also was a  
philanthropist and major investor in rebuilding downtown Battle 
Creek. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller's father, Albert Miller, became editor and publisher of  
C.W. Post's Morning Enquirer, one of three newspapers in the city 
in 1910. In 1918, Albert Miller merged the Morning Enquirer and the 
Evening News into the Battle Creek Enquirer and News. 
</P>
<P>
	His son became a reporter for the Battle Creek Enquirer and News  
in 1928. The younger Miller became publisher in 1952 and held the 
position until 1979, when his son, Robert B. Miller Jr., become the 
third generation of Millers to run the newspaper. He served as 
publisher until 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	The paper, now called the Battle Creek Enquirer, changed its  
name in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years the family acquired six other newspapers, forming  
Federated Publications. Federated was purchased by Gannett Co. Inc. 
in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors also include another son, Allen L. Miller.  

</P>
<P>
                             *Red Norvo    	
</P>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Red Norvo, who performed with such  
greats as Charles Mingus and Frank Sinatra and is credited with 
introducing the xylophone to jazz, died Tuesday at age 91. 
</P>
<P>
	He taught himself how to play piano and xylophone. By age 17, he  
was touring with a vaudeville show and later joined the Paul Ash 
Orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
	Born Kenneth Norville, his last name changed to Norvo after Ash  
mispronounced it to a reporter and his manager decided the shorter 
name was more fitting. 
</P>
<P>
	During Norvo's tenure with Paul Whiteman's Orchestra, which he  
joined in 1932, he met singer Mildred Bailey, whom he later 
married. By 1935, he formed his own sextet that played in clubs on 
New York City's 52nd Street. 
</P>
<P>
	In subsequent years, Norvo and his wife, who were known as ``Mr.  
and Mrs. Swing,'' formed several groups in New York and Chicago. 
Among their hits in the 1930s were ``Rockin' Chair,'' ``Please Be 
Kind,'' ``Says My Heart'' and ``Have You Forgotten So Soon?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1943, he switched from xylophone to vibraphone, which he  
played almost exclusively for the rest of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Norvo continued to perform until he suffered a stroke in the  
early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bailey, whose likeness was featured on a 1996 U.S. postage  
stamp, died in 1951. Norvo later married Eve Rogers, who died in 
1992. 

</P>
<P>
                      *Margaret MacFadyen Peck    	
</P>
<P>
	RIVERTON, Wyo. (AP) -- Margaret MacFadyen Peck, a co-founder of  
The Riverton Ranger, died Saturday following surgery. She was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	She shared her philosophy of life in her columns for more than  
50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Peck and her husband, Roy, and his brother, Bob Peck,  
helped start The Riverton Times in 1949. She became co-publisher 
with the founding of The Riverton Ranger in 1953. 
</P>
<P>
	She authored newspaper columns ``Dear Ruthie,'' ``Trying A  
Trifle,'' ``I Must Say'' and, more recently, ``Nasty Surprises.'' 
Her columns took first place in the annual Wyoming Press 
Association contest several times. 
</P>
<P>
	She was also a recipient of the Governor's Arts Award.  

</P>
<P>
                       *Madeleine Haas Russell    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Madeleine Haas Russell, a descendent of  
Levi Strauss who used her family fortune to support the arts, 
cultural groups and liberal political causes, died Friday on her 
84th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with her late brother, Mrs. Russell co-founded the  
Columbia Foundation, which distributed grants totaling about $3.5 
million in the last fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	One of her earliest grants after World War II went to the  
Emergency Committee of Atomic Scientists to help discourage the 
further use of nuclear weapons and energy. She later was active in 
causes that included the abolition of the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	She was a major contributor to Democratic candidates and the  
Democratic Party, supporting U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein, President 
Clinton, Rep. Nancy Pelosi and many others. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Russell also was a prominent supporter of the arts. Her  
foundation recently made large donations to the San Francisco 
Opera, the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art and the Asian Art 
Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	The current home of KQED, San Francisco's public TV and radio  
station, bears her name. 
</P>
<P>
	She was a great-grandniece of the Bavarian immigrant who crafted  
the first pair of blue jeans. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
