<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Dissident Kept From Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- An exiled Chinese dissident was  
prevented from flying to Hong Kong on Wednesday, two days after 
China refused him permission to travel to Beijing on a flight from 
South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang Xizhe has sought to return to China to pay his respects at  
the grave of his father and simultaneously test Beijing's policy of 
barring unwanted exiles and politically active foreigners. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebuffed, Wang left Bangkok Wednesday night on a flight bound  
for the United States via Seoul, South Korea, said a friend who saw 
him off at the airport, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang, a veteran dissident active for 25 years, said the apparent  
refusal of Hong Kong authorities to allow him entry proved that 
China was exercising undue influence over the former British colony 
it regained control of in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very angry,'' Wang told reporters. ``They say it's one  
nation, two systems, but first the Chinese government does not 
allow me to go, and now the Hong Kong government. How can this 
be?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wang, who has spent years in prison, sneaked out of China three  
years ago to evade arrest and carries no passport, only a ``refugee 
travel document'' issued by the U.S. government. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the 50-year-old Wang got as far as Seoul on an Asiana  
flight from New York before he was informed that China would not 
let him fly to Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	He then headed to Bangkok, accepting conditions set by Thai  
officials that he would not engage in anti-China protests. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang booked himself on a Thai Airways flight Wednesday to Hong  
Kong but was not allowed to check in when he arrived at Bangkok's 
international airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai Airways staff told Wang he did not have the required  
transit visa to stay in Hong Kong. As he was arguing his case, a 
telex arrived from the airline's Hong Kong office saying that 
authorities had no intention of offending China by allowing him 
entry. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really want to leave,'' Wang said.  
</P>
<P>
	Although Asiana's flights to Seoul and New York were packed,  
space was made to get Wang out of Bangkok. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement by the Hong Kong government denied that its  
officials ``had been in touch with Thai authorities over the entry 
or transit of Mr. Wang in Hong Kong.'' But it did not say whether 
it had contacted airline officials. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to the Supreme People's Court in China on Tuesday  
Wang said that barring him contradicted government claims to be 
building a society based on a clear system of laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
