<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> At Home To Expand Into Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) -- At Home Corp. announced today that  
it will form a joint venture to bring its high-speed cable 
Internet-access service to 5 million homes in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture, called At Home Japan, will also be partly owned by  
Japanese cable operator Jupiter Telecommunications and one of that 
company's owners, trading giant Sumitomo Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``With roughly 15 million Internet users, Japan is an extremely  
promising market for high-speed cable Internet services and a 
tremendous next step in At Home's international expansion,'' John 
O'Farrell, senior vice president of international operations for At 
Home, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	At Home will own 43 percent of the venture, Jupiter  
Telecommunications will hold 36 percent and Sumitomo will own a 21 
percent stake, O'Farrell said. 
</P>
<P>
	At Home now has about 330,000 customers in the United States and  
Canada who use its high-speed Internet access. But it has 
partnerships with 21 cable operators that give it exclusive access 
to sell to about 60 million homes. Analysts expect At Home to have 
1 million subscribers by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	At Home plans to launch a service in the Netherlands this fall  
aimed at 1.4 million users. That venture is co-owned by At Home, 
Dutch cable operators and Intel Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	About 11 percent of Japanese households had access to the  
Internet at the end of March, nearly double the amount of a year 
ago, according to Japan's Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications. 
</P>
<P>
	Jupiter Telecommunications, founded in 1995, is a joint venture  
between Sumitomo and Liberty Media International Inc. Liberty is 
part of a spinoff of Tele-Communications Inc., which was recently 
purchased by AT&AMP;T Corp. AT&AMP;T holds a controlling stake in At Home. 
</P>
<P>
	Jupiter Telecommunications provides cable TV to 348,000 homes in  
Japan. Its franchise, including Sumitomo's cable systems, covers 
5.1 million homes in 29 cable systems. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 10:15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some in Oregon Scapegoat California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Listeners jammed the radio station  
switchboard to complain about ``them'' and their funny-talking, 
bad-driving ways. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're glad you like Oregon. Now pack up and get out!'' one  
caller fumed. 
</P>
<P>
	This wasn't some fringe forum for supremacists. It was KOTK-AM  
Hot Talk in Portland, and the Oregonians calling in were griping 
about their favorite target: Californians. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the much-maligned migration from the Golden State to  
its rainy neighbor to the north has slowed by the thousands from 
its peak in the early 1990s, an anti-California undercurrent 
courses through Oregon. 
</P>
<P>
	As the state struggles to absorb an estimated 1 million more  
residents over the next 20 years, there's a new effort under way to 
revive the ``stay-out'' sentiment made famous in 1971 by then-Gov. 
Tom McCall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Come and visit us again and again,'' McCall said at the time.  
``But for heaven's sake, don't come here to live.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, state Sen. John Lim, himself an immigrant from Korea,  
introduced a bill to erect signs at the state line telling 
motorists: ``You are welcome to visit Oregon, but please don't 
stay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lim said the bill is a first step toward preserving Oregon's  
livability, which he believes is threatened by growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Californians represent about a third of new residents, though  
the numbers have been steadily dropping as that state's economy has 
improved. Using driver's licenses as a rough indicator, the net 
migration from California to Oregon is half of what it was: 23,000 
in 1993 vs. 11,000 in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet most of the growth-related blame remains focused on the  
Golden State. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of a scapegoating thing,'' said John Findlay, a  
University of Washington history professor. ``It's these outsiders 
coming in, especially Californians, that are forcing up home 
prices, clogging freeways and bringing gangs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Findlay teaches a course in Northwest history. Over the past 10  
years, when he has asked his students for words associated with 
California, they've consistently come up with: bad drivers, 
pollution, overcrowded, pushy, vain, rude, disrespectful and 
superficial. 
</P>
<P>
	``Californians learn pretty quickly when they get here to change  
their plates and take off their UCLA sweatshirt,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Judy Combs said she became well aware of how native Oregonians  
felt after she moved to Lake Oswego from San Jose, Calif., in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was just this attitude,'' she said. ``We were very  
cautious about who we would tell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She quickly changed license plates and anxiously awaited her new  
driver's license in the mail. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just hated to go into a grocery store and have to drag out  
your California license,'' Ms. Combs said. ``You could just see 
them thinking, `Oh no, not another California transplant.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Even those from other places quickly learn the value of  
disassociation. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I need to say is `I'm not from California' and no one  
gives me any trouble,'' said Allana Morgan, a waitress who moved to 
Oregon 5 1/2 years ago from Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Rick Emerson, who as host of the KOTK show hears his share  
of outrageous things, said he was taken aback by Oregonians' 
dislike of Californians. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't expect it to be quite so vitriolic,'' he said. ``I've  
lived in a lot of places and they all have a feeling of propriety 
over their state. But I have never seen such a rabid fear. It 
almost causes them physical pain to see these Californians coming 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. John Kitzhaber himself repeatedly cites Southern California  
as an example of what Oregon doesn't want to become. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the issue of growth management, we've done it right,'' said  
Kitzhaber's spokesman Bob Applegate. ``If that means pointing out 
that our neighbors to the south have not done it right, then our 
apologies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, the governor believes that growth and prosperity go  
hand in hand and has nothing against Californians who choose to 
move here, Applegate said: ``They came to the right state.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
