<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Closes at New High: 10,085.31 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average soared in the  
last hour of trading today and hit a new record high as investors, 
nervous about upcoming earnings reports, sought the relative safety 
of blue-chip stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 121.82 at 10,085.31. It was the Dow's third close 
above 10,000, and eclipsed the previous high close of 10,007.33, 
reached Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed, reflecting the fact that  
investors are for the time being turning away from unpredictable 
technology stocks and moving their money to blue-chips that are 
seen as surer bets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite index, heavily weighted in technology  
issues, fell 18.81 to 2,544.36, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index 
rose 8.86 to 1,326.75. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks opened strongly as aluminum maker Alcoa released  
first-quarter earnings that soundly beat analysts' expectations. 
The good news from Alcoa, a component of the Dow, helped many 
blue-chips move higher. Alcoa itself was up 2 13/16 to 43 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, another Dow stock, was up 4 13/16 at 84 15/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The financial sector was mostly higher as analysts said banks  
and brokerages have hinted they will report strong earnings when 
they begin releasing first-quarter results next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Ned Riley, chief investment officer at BankBoston, said  
investors may be rewarding those companies for weathering the 
global financial crises of 1998. The financial companies are also 
benefiting from stable interest rates, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase Manhattan rose 5 1/8 to 84 3/8, and Merrill Lynch rose 5 1/8 to  
96 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong sales report from Ford Motor sent its shares up 2 1/2 to  
60 3/4. The automaker said in its report Tuesday it plans to increase 
production in the coming months. The news enticed investors with 
hints of future strength. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip stocks easily outperformed technology stocks  
today. Computer companies held the market in check for much the 
afternoon after Merrill Lynch analysts warned of some tough times 
ahead for the high-tech sector. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem, according to William Meehan, chief market analyst  
at Cantor Fitzgerald, is that stocks are too overvalued to 
withstand even the slightest hint of caution. ``It doesn't take 
much to trigger any kind of stampede,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Software maker Novell slipped 1 1/8 to 22 15/16, and Sun  
Microsystems fell 1 7/8 to 138 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, traders were optimistically looking ahead to an  
after-hours earnings release from Yahoo!, which was expected to 
beat analyst estimates -- and did so, by three cents a share. Yahoo! 
ended lower in profit-taking after rising more than 16 points 
earlier in the day. 


</P>
</TEXT>
