<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Star Watch: Claire Danes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The doodles gave her away.  
</P>
<P>
	Try as she might, Claire Danes, the oh-so-serious actress who  
favors doomed and angst-ridden young women, just couldn't keep the 
sober act up much longer. 
</P>
<P>
	Exhibit A: Danes' hotel writing pad, currently filled with puffy  
hearts speared by Cupid's arrows, three puffy thingamajigs and a 
bunch of cute stars. 
</P>
<P>
	Hearts and stars?  
</P>
<P>
	``When people first meet me, they're automatically  
disillusioned,'' she says with a laugh as she inspects her 
handiwork. ``It doesn't take them long to be demystified.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She may have a Golden Globe, she may go to Yale University and  
count Steven Spielberg among her devoted fans, but Claire Danes is 
still very much a teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
	You were expecting something else?  
</P>
<P>
	``The trick to dealing with Claire is that you have to remind  
yourself that she's only 19,'' says Scott Silver, who directed 
Danes in her current film, ``The Mod Squad,'' a poorly reviewed 
copy of the acclaimed 1960s TV show about three 
youths-turned-undercover cops. 
</P>
<P>
	``On one level, she's completely composed. And on another level,  
a teen-ager. You have both these things in the same person -- which 
is remarkable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The newsstands agree. Last month, Danes' mugged her way onto the  
cover of teeny-bopper YM magazine, alongside articles on ``41 Ways 
to Make Him Swoon'' and ``Five Tasty First-Kiss Tips.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, wasn't she also gracing the cover of Jane magazine, with  
its mature stories on embattled abortion clinics, the confessions 
of an ex-Hooters girl and fashion tips for Venezuela? 
</P>
<P>
	Now a few weeks shy of her 20th birthday, Danes, an awkward  
beauty with eyes as wide as bird baths, admits she won't be doing 
this tightrope walk between adolescence and adulthood too much 
longer. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is my last bout of being a reckless teen-ager,'' she  
says. ``My actions will still be excused for the next year or so, 
so I should take advantage of the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That explains her odd foray into action-adventure in ``The Mod  
Squad,'' in which Danes gets to strut around as an ex-druggie in 
Urban Outfitters-like jackets, boot-cut jeans and midriff-bearing 
tops. 
</P>
<P>
	Plus, she gets to blow stuff up.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've never tackled this genre before,'' she says. ``I was  
craving some levity. A huge motivation for me to do the project was 
people's surprised reaction to my decision. They were practically 
appalled!'' 
</P>
<P>
	To be sure, Danes' screen characters haven't lived long or happy  
lives. Danes sprung to fame at age 15 as the hyper-observant star 
of the TV drama ``My So-Called Life,'' a critically acclaimed -- yet 
short-lived -- series about high school angst. 
</P>
<P>
	``I exhausted the idea of adolescence making that show,'' she  
says. ``I explored so many different facets of being a teen-ager, I 
was done! I got it! I was satiated! So when the next crop of films 
came along, I just didn't have an interest discussing those themes 
any more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Danes made her movie debut in ``Little Women,'' and  
co-starred in the tough-to-take dramas ``How to Make an American 
Quilt'' and ``Home for the Holidays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her darker path continued, playing a daughter whose mother has  
died in ``To Gillian on Her 37th Birthday,'' the doomed female lead 
in ``William Shakespeare's Romeo &AMP; Juliet,'' an abused wife in 
``The Rainmaker'' and the melancholy Cosette in ``Les Miserables.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The work I've done has been some intense projects. The  
characters are in real periods of crisis and are in true turmoil -- 
so that's just what I've been exploring lately. I wasn't providing 
escapism,'' she says. ``I wanted to hit straight-on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By the time Spielberg singled her out as ``one of the most  
exciting actresses to debut in 10 years,'' Danes-mania was in full 
gear. She made Entertainment Weekly's list of the 12 best actresses 
of the coming decade, and People magazine's 50-most-beautiful list. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's flattering. It's nice,'' she says, unconvincingly.  
</P>
<P>
	``Well, it's just that I'm so hard on myself that whatever  
expectation other people are throwing out at me, I can outdo them. 
It's not something I'm proud of. I want to loosen up a little bit 
and be less harsh on myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Could Yale offer Danes a necessary refuge -- a new beginning?  
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, it's really good for me to be there at the moment. I'm  
fine when I'm completely immersed in either one of the two worlds: 
Hollywood or academia,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	``When they start to conflict or merge, I start feeling  
fractured and confused and I don't know how to handle either of 
them. I've met some amazing people who are my age and I'm not 
shielded anymore by what I experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although she admits loving John Hughes' bubble-gum films as a  
child, as an actress Danes could be the anti-Molly Ringwald, never 
willing to act her age for an easy buck. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really easy to exploit teen-agers because they have  
relatively little power and are adorable,'' she says. Of the 
current crop of teen-orientated fare, she adds, ``It's a phase. The 
interest and infatuation will pass.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of her own current phase, Danes is ambivalent. ``I'm meditating  
on where I want to go next. I think I've reached a kind of plateau. 
I'm curious to see what sort of effect my going to school will have 
on my future acting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When asked what she most fears, Danes responds with a story. She  
recalls being driven one morning to the set of ``Les Miserables'' 
in the Czech Republic. The script that day was filled with grueling 
scenes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were passing through the gates of the studio and I thought,  
'Why do I do this to myself? I really want to be the driver right 
now. I really want to be the make-up person right now! Why am I 
putting myself through this utter torture?' 
</P>
<P>
	``I always refer to that moment when I'm freaked out,'' Danes  
says. ``I always think, 'Well, when am I going to become impervious 
to this nervousness?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Probably never. Welcome to adulthood, Claire.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
