<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990407.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 02:32:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Awards Ex-Anchor More Than $7M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- An anchorwoman who was demoted then fired  
after she went on disability leave has won $7.3 million in a 
discrimination lawsuit against her former station. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that it sends a wake-up call to television stations  
around the country who believe that they may be omnipotent, who 
believe that they're above the law,'' Sara Lee Kessler said after 
the jury's verdict Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does not serve communities for television stations to  
practice corporate discrimination and retaliation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The jury ordered WWOR-TV in Secaucus to pay Kessler for demoting  
her and forcing her to take a disability leave after she injured 
her tailbone. 
</P>
<P>
	WWOR attorney John D. Arsenault called the amount of the award  
``ludicrous'' and said the station would appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors rejected the 47-year-old woman's claims that the station  
demoted, then dismissed her because of her age, sex and religion. 
Kessler, an Orthodox Jew, had claimed managers frequently made her 
work past sundown on the Jewish Sabbath. 
</P>
<P>
	Kessler was hired by WWOR in 1976 and became anchor of the  
``News Noon'' show in 1989. She won an Emmy for anchoring coverage 
of the 1993 World Trade Center bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	The award includes more than $2.8 million in lost wages. Kessler  
now works as a reporter at New Jersey Network, where her lawyers 
said she makes about $50,000, compared to $300,000 at WWOR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
