<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McDougal Closing Arguments Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Susan McDougal owed it to President  
Clinton to testify if she could have helped clear his name during 
the Whitewater investigation, a prosecutor argued today at the 
close of Mrs. McDougal's trial for refusing to answer grand jury 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Associate Independent Counsel Julie Myers noted that Mrs.  
McDougal was glad that Clinton testified on her behalf in 1996, 
when she was convicted of fraud related to Whitewater business 
deals. 
</P>
<P>
	``But when she had information that according to her would help  
demonstrate the president's innocence ... she selfishly refused to 
provide it to the grand jury or anyone,'' Myers told the jury. 
</P>
<P>
	She also noted that first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton had  
testified when called by the Whitewater grand jury spurned by Mrs. 
McDougal. 
</P>
<P>
	Myers told jurors they would have to weigh the credibility of  
Mrs. McDougal, who says she refused to testify because she feared 
Kenneth Starr's team, against the word of Whitewater prosecutors 
Hickman Ewing and Ray Jahn, who testified in the trial that they 
only wanted the truth. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who is more credible? Two career federal prosecutors vs. the  
defendant who is convicted of four felonies?'' Myers asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal's attorneys have argued that Starr's office was  
out to get President and Mrs. Clinton and wanted Mrs. McDougal to 
falsely implicate them. Mrs. McDougal said she feared being charged 
with perjury if her testimony did not suit Starr's team. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal arrived this morning with her parents, five of her  
six brothers and sisters and other relatives. A member of the 
California jury that acquitted her on unrelated embezzlement 
charges was also in the courtroom to show support. 
</P>
<P>
	Myers said Mrs. McDougal had a duty to testify because she was  
``central to the grand jury's investigation.'' Yet she refused to 
comply with the court order and kept demanding new protections even 
after being granted limited immunity from prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not Burger King. The defendant can't have it her way,''  
Myers said. 
</P>
<P>
	She told jurors that Mrs. McDougal planned to break the law,  
even calling the jail the day before her 1996 grand jury appearance 
to inquire about what she could bring with her. 
</P>
<P>
	``She knew what she was doing,'' Myers argued, describing Mrs.  
McDougal as a stubborn woman who craved public attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal's defense may be hampered by instructions to the  
jury. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge George Howard Jr. ruled Tuesday that in  
deciding the criminal contempt charges, jurors cannot consider 
evidence that prosecutors wanted something other than Mrs. 
McDougal's truthful testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury may consider her accusations against Starr only on the  
companion obstruction of justice charge, the judge added. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury instructions, which the judge put in writing Tuesday, were  
to be delivered after closing arguments. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were pleased overall'' with the instructions, Associate  
Independent Counsel Mark Barrett said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, the Clintons' former business partner in the  
Whitewater real estate venture, was indicted after she refused on 
two occasions to answer grand jury questions about the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett said the prosecution was able to block a defense request  
for an instruction that jurors could acquit Mrs. McDougal of 
criminal contempt if she proved she had ``just cause'' to refuse to 
answer the grand jury questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Harris, Mrs. McDougal's fiance and co-counsel for the  
defense, had a matter-of-fact response. ``Some of them we got. Some 
of them we didn't,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
