<HEADLINE> Talk Show Slaying Case Going Slow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- The judge presiding over the $50 million  
wrongful death lawsuit against ``The Jenny Jones Show'' grew so 
exasperated with the slow pace that he pleaded with the lawyers to 
stop bickering. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you guys would just stop the hyperbole this would move  
along a lot quicker -- please,'' Judge Gene Schnelz said before 
adjourning Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The family of Scott Amedure sued the show, claiming its  
``ambush'' tactics humiliated Jonathan Schmitz and drove him to 
shoot Amedure in March 1995, three days after they appeared on the 
program. Amedure revealed he had a crush on Schmitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz was convicted in 1996 of murdering Amedure. The verdict  
was overturned because of an error in jury selection, and a retrial 
is set for Aug. 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Only four out of a potential 100 witnesses have testified since  
the trial began March 29, and the judge has said repeatedly ``one 
at a time'' while the two lead attorneys argue various points. 
</P>
<P>
	Amedure's family is represented by Geoffrey Fieger, known for  
bombastic and successful defenses of Dr. Jack Kevorkian. The show 
and its producer, Warner Bros., are represented by James Feeney, 
who has defended General Motors Corp. and DaimlerChrysler AG in 
product lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenny Jones was to testify today, but lawyers now say she likely  
will not take the stand before next week. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Patricia Cielinski testified that she sat next to  
Schmitz on a 90-minute plane ride after the show and that he was 
disappointed and surprised. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said he wasn't mad right there at that point in time, but  
if he thought about it long enough, he'd get mad,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Feeney and Fieger spent 30 minutes fighting over whether Ms.  
Cielinski should testify at all, with Fieger ultimately prevailing. 

</P>
</TEXT>
