<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Faith Hill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Faith Hill still bubbles over with  
enthusiasm. 
</P>
<P>
	A lot has happened since the country music singer from Star,  
Miss., became an instant star with ``Wild One'' in 1993. Then, she 
sang the praises of role model Reba McEntire and swore she had 
never heard Janis Joplin's classic record of ``Piece of My Heart,'' 
her second single. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, 31, now rivals McEntire as a country music icon. She's  
collected seven No. 1 hits, culminating with the massive success of 
``This Kiss,'' which crossed over last year to get airplay on rock 
stations. 
</P>
<P>
	Her fame dramatically increased in 1996 when she married singer  
Tim McGraw. Country music fans haven't had such a high-profile star 
couple since the 1970s and the glory days of George Jones and Tammy 
Wynette. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill and McGraw have recorded two highly successful duets and  
will probably do more. But first, Hill is using her first year 
untouched by pregnancy since 1995 to launch an overdue headlining 
tour. The 21-date first leg begins Friday (April 9) at the Orpheum 
Theater in Minneapolis, and includes Chicago, Milwaukee, Seattle, 
Los Angeles and Salt Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
	1. How do you feel about finally being a headliner instead of an  
opening act? 
</P>
<P>
	Hill: Nervous. Excited. Oh gosh, I could go on! ... When I saw  
the stage the other day, I just cried. I can't believe all that 
stuff is mine. And I get to tell it when to move, you know? ... 
There'll be some surprises, but I'm not going to be flying from the 
ceiling or that sort of thing. That would be fun, but I'm not going 
to do it this time around. 
</P>
<P>
	2. You've been a star for five years. Why didn't you headline  
sooner? 
</P>
<P>
	Hill: I wanted to do it right, you know what I'm saying? ... And  
that's why we waited. Now, I can have the things I always wanted. 
I've never even had my own backdrop in all the years I've been 
working. Isn't that funny? Plus, I've had so many opportunities in 
the past to work on some incredible tours. Last year I was part of 
the George Strait festival that played stadiums. I've been able to 
play in front of a million people or so in the five years I've 
worked. 
</P>
<P>
	3. You're asking fans to donate books at each of your shows.  
Why? 
</P>
<P>
	Hill: My father was one of 13 children, and he had to quit  
school at a very young age, and he never learned to read. He had to 
work on the family farm. When I became an adult, I realized what he 
had missed out on. I don't know how he made it. There's such a 
world out there that I want him to discover. So I started this 
foundation, The Family Literacy Project, just to bring awareness to 
illiteracy in our country. ... We're asking the fans to bring a 
book when they come to the show, and the next day they're going to 
be distributed to inner-city schools and hospitals and libraries -- 
just places that need books to read to children. Volunteers from 
America's Promise: The Alliance for Youth will collect the books 
and distribute them. 
</P>
<P>
	3 1/2. What is Volunteers from America's Promise?  
</P>
<P>
	Hill: America's Promise is Gen. Colin Powell's organization that  
is about mentoring children, so they know that they have got a 
chance in this world. ... And also, when you donate a book, you'll 
sign a little card, and before the show we'll have a drawing and I 
get to meet that person. 
</P>
<P>
	4. ``This Kiss'' seems to have put you into another league by  
getting airplay on rock stations. Did that catch you by surprise? 
</P>
<P>
	Hill: Yeah, I was very surprised. I think a station in Seattle  
was the first rock station to play `This Kiss.' I think their 
sister station was a country station and they started playing it, 
and their listeners just responded. Other stations followed suit, 
and we just went for it from there. It's still going. I spoke to a 
radio station yesterday in South Africa, where it's a huge single. 
Isn't that amazing? That just blows my mind for some reason. 
</P>
<P>
	5. You've got two young daughters and a husband with a very busy  
career. How do you balance all of it? 
</P>
<P>
	Hill: Together, we make it work. Our family comes first, and  
from there everything seems to work out. People do it every day. 
The only difference with us is we travel. ... It's definitely like 
a Rubik's Cube. Our organizations work so hard to put our schedules 
together. ... We're never apart for more than three days. 
</P>
<P>
	5 1/2. You've had two wildly popular duets with Tim (``It's Your  
Love,'' ``Just to Hear You Say That You Love Me''). Are there more 
coming, and perhaps a concert tour together? 
</P>
<P>
	Hill: We certainly want to do more of that in the future, and  
possibly even an album together. We just enjoy singing together, 
it's really a beautiful thing. And it would be great to bring it 
all together. It would be a lot of fun. There are no concrete 
plans, but I think that's in the future. We just don't know when. 
</P>
</TEXT>
