<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Westwood: Golf's Globe-Trotter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- About the only difference Lee Westwood sees  
between himself and David Duval is the places they play. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, they'll play only a group apart as the two hottest  
golfers on each side of the Atlantic tee off in search of their 
first major championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody who wants to be the best in the world has to keep up  
with the one setting the standard,'' Westwood said. ``Tiger and 
David may be the best two at the moment, but I'm not that far 
behind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Westwood comes into the Masters with credentials almost as  
impeccable as those of Duval, who has won 11 of his last 34 starts, 
including his last two. 
</P>
<P>
	Westwood has won 11 times himself in the last two years. But,  
outside of a win in New Orleans last year, they have all come in 
Europe or Asia, keeping Westwood from moving up further from his 
spot as the No. 7-ranked player in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a situation Westwood doesn't think is quite fair, although  
he shies away from staking a claim to the No. 1 spot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've got a good record over the last couple of years.  
I wouldn't compare it to David's,'' Westwood said. ``You know, he 
plays in America. People might say the tournaments are bigger over 
here, but they play in the same conditions as we do. Maybe it 
doesn't test your game as much as playing all around the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Duval is coming off wins at The Players Championship and  
BellSouth Classic a few hours down Interstate 20 from Augusta, 
Westwood's resume is littered with names from more exotic locales. 
</P>
<P>
	The 25-year-old Englishman has won in Malaysia and in the  
Japanese cities of Gotemba and Miyazaki. Last year, he had 
victories in Belgium, Scotland, Germany, England and Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like playing all around the world and experiencing all the  
different cultures and such,'' said Westwood, who will play in the 
MCI Classic next week to complete a three tournament PGA swing 
before heading back to the European tour. 
</P>
<P>
	But his only win in America was last year in the  
Freeport-McDermott Classic, and he doesn't play the PGA Tour enough 
to get the added weight of American tour wins into the rankings 
that determine the world's top players. 
</P>
<P>
	He played in only eight PGA tournaments last year, but had three  
top-10 finishes, including the win in New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's easier to do it over here because the American rankings  
is loaded in the Americans' favor,'' Westwood said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though they play different tours, Duval and Westwood do have one  
thing in common. Neither has won a major. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval came close last year, losing on Mark O'Meara's 20-footer  
for a birdie on the last hole of the Masters. But Westwood has 
finished over par on both his appearances at Augusta National, and 
has a spotty record in the other majors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to be ready for the tournament this time, where I  
wore myself out the last couple of years doing my preparation,'' 
Westwood said. ``This year I'm going into it only playing nine 
holes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Faldo, the 1996 winner, struggling mightily, and other  
Europeans playing erratically, Westwood may be the best foreign 
chance in the field of 96 at Augusta National. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Americans have won the last two Masters, Europeans won 10  
of the 18 before that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not really trying to beat the rest of the Europeans. I'm  
trying to beat the rest of the field,'' Westwood said. ``Whether 
I'm the European favorite or not doesn't concern me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the field, of course, includes Woods and Duval, who  
will hit his first tee shot Thursday afternoon as Westwood walks to 
the first green. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to keep up with who is playing the best,'' Westwood  
said. ``Whoever is playing the best is going to drag everyone else 
along.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
